sequence: Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates, centered on a single point on the ice, while holding one or more body positions. They are performed by all disciplines of the sport, single skating, pair skating, and ice dance, and are a required element in most figure skating competitions. As The New York Times says, "While jumps look like sport, spins look more like art. While jumps provide the suspense, spins provide the scenery, but there is so much more to the scenery than most viewers have time or means to grasp".

Year 1211 (MCCXI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  June 17 – Battle of Antioch on the Meander: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I are initially victorious with the Latin mercenary cavalry (some 800 men) bearing the brunt of the casualties due to their flanking charge; exhausted by the effort in their attack, the Latin army under Emperor Theodore I (Laskaris) is struck in the flank and rear by the Seljuk forces.

Berchtesgaden  is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land, Bavaria, in southeastern Germany, near the border with Austria,  south of Salzburg and  southeast of Munich. It lies in the Berchtesgaden Alps, south of Berchtesgaden; the Berchtesgaden National Park stretches along three parallel valleys.The Kehlstein mountain , with its Kehlsteinhaus (Eagle's Nest) is located in the area.EtymologyBerchtesgaden, Upper Bavaria (Achental), earlier Perchterscadmen, Perhtersgadem, Berchirchsgadem, Berchtoldesgadem; the word underwent a Latin distortion of Old High German parach, Romance bareca 'hay shed'.

Panettone (, ;  ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan, usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas and New Year in Western, Southern, and Southeastern Europe as well as in South America, Eritrea, Australia, the United States and Canada.It has a cupola shape, which extends from a cylindrical base and is usually about 12–15 cm high for a panettone weighing 1 kg. Other bases may be used, such as an octagon, or a frustum with a star section shape more common to pandoro. It is made during a long process that involves curing the dough, which is acidic, similar to sourdough.

Alappuzha district , is one of the 14 districts in the state of Kerala in India. It was formed as Alleppey district on 17 August 1957, the name of the district being changed to Alappuzha in 1990, and is the smallest district in Kerala. Alleppey town, the district headquarters, was renamed Alappuzha in 2012, even though the anglicised name is still commonly used to describe the town as well as the district.The district is best known for its picturesque backwaters, by which it is well connected to other parts of Kerala, including the tourist destination of Kumarakom, the district being a well known tourist destination.

Year 1427 ( MCDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year marked significant events and developments in various fields including religion, politics, literature, and culture. In the Holy Roman Empire, the imperial election witnessed a major political shift, while tensions began brewing among various kingdoms in the region. Furthermore, Italy experienced a great cultural boom as various masterpieces were produced by notable artists and writers, contributing to the growth of Renaissance art. With discoveries being made, literature experienced a marked renaissance as vernacular languages saw a resurgence.

The Cape Cod Canal is an artificial waterway in the U.S. state of Massachusetts connecting Cape Cod Bay in the north to Buzzards Bay in the south, and is part of the Atlantic Intracoastal Waterway. The approximately  canal traverses the neck of land joining Cape Cod to the state's mainland. It mostly follows tidal rivers widened to  and deepened to  at mean low water, shaving  off the journey around the Cape for its approximately 14,000 annual users.Most of the canal is located in the town of Bourne, but its northeastern terminus is in Sandwich.

Lillian Evelyn Gilbreth ( Moller ; May 24 , 1878 – January 2 , 1972 ) was an American psychologist , industrial engineer, consultant, and educator, often referred to as the "First Lady of Engineering". Born in Oakland, California, she completed her PhD at the University of California, Berkeley in 1915, breaking barriers for women in her field. Alongside her husband, Frank Gilbreth, Lillian made significant contributions to the science of motion study and work simplification, with a focus on the human element. This groundbreaking work led to improved workplace efficiency, increased worker well-being, and the formation of modern ergonomics.

Mary Virginia Martin ( December 1 , 1913 – November 3 , 1990 ) was an American actress and singer . She gained prominence for her powerful voice and is best remembered for her iconic roles in popular Broadway musicals. Martin became a leading lady in the world of theatre during the 1940s and 1950s, winning multiple Tony Awards throughout her illustrious career. Notable performances included her role as Nellie Forbush in Rodgers and Hammerstein's South Pacific (1949), and as the enchanting Maria von Trapp in The Sound of Music (1959).

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River , in the town of Manapouri on the South Island of New Zealand. It is renowned for its stunning natural beauty, serving as a gateway to Fiordland National Park and Doubtful Sound. Visitors are attracted to its scenic charm, serene water surroundings, and abundant flora and fauna, as well as recreational opportunities including kayaking, boating, and fishing. Additionally, the area offers a perfect setting for eco-tourism, attracting nature enthusiasts who partake in guided nature walks, exploring the lush forests and serene shorelines that surround the enchanting harbour.

Year 1340 (MCCCXL) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 26 – King Edward III of England is declared King of France. April 8 – The Marinid galleys, under the command of Muhammad ibn Ali al-Azafi, rout the Castellan fleet, off the coast of Algeciras. April–July – Trapezuntine Civil War: An abortive uprising occurs against Irene Palaiologina of Trebizond, the first of a number of coups, revolts, and succession disputes. June 7 – Rotterdam is officially declared a city.

The Æsir ( Old Norse : ) are the gods of the principal pantheon in Norse religion . They include Odin, the All-Father, who is the god of war, wisdom, and poetry; Thor, the mighty thunder god and protector of mankind; Freyja, the goddess of fertility, love, and beauty; Loki, the mischievous shape-shifting trickster; and numerous other deities with various roles in mythology. These powerful beings reside in the realm of Asgard, connected to the mortal world through the great cosmic tree, Yggdrasil.

The Khlysts or Khlysty ( , `` whips '' ) were an underground Spiritual Christian sect , which split from the Russian Orthodox Church in the 17th century. As a breakaway religious movement, they believed that their practitioners could achieve salvation through sin by means of personal communication with the Holy Spirit. Central to their beliefs was ecstatic worship and prayer practices that involved bodily movements, singing, and the use of the knout (whips) as part of their rites. Persecuted by church and state authorities for their unorthodox and allegedly immoral behavior, the Khlysts survived in secrecy for centuries.

Mariner-H (Mariner Mars '71), also commonly known as Mariner 8, was (along with Mariner 9) part of the Mariner Mars '71 project. It was intended to go into Mars orbit and return images and data, but a launch vehicle failure prevented Mariner 8 from achieving Earth orbit and the spacecraft reentered into the Atlantic Ocean shortly after launch.MissionMariner 8 was launched on an Atlas-Centaur SLV-3C booster (AC-24). The main Centaur engine was ignited 265 seconds after launch, but the upper stage began to oscillate in pitch and tumbled out of control.

Year 1160 (MCLX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sends an embassy led by John Kontostephanos to Jerusalem, to ask King Baldwin III to nominate one of the princesses of the Crusader States, as a bride for the widowed emperor. Their two candidates are 15-year-old Maria of Antioch, and Melisende of Tripoli. Baldwin suggests Melisende, and her brother Count Raymond III sets about gathering an enormous dowry. The ambassadors are not satisfied, and delay the marriage for over a year.

Year 1494 (MCDXCIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – The Cetinje Octoechos (Цетињски октоих, an Eastern Orthodox octoechos (liturgy), first tone), the first incunabulum written in the Serbian recension of Church Slavonic, and the first book printed in Cyrillic in Southeast Europe, is completed in Cetinje. January 25 – Alfonso II becomes King of Naples. May – Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor, recognises Perkin Warbeck as rightful King of England. May 5 – Christopher Columbus first sights Jamaica.

Year 1184 (MCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  May 20 – Diet of Pentecost: Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa) organises a conference in Mainz. During the diet Frederick negotiates with Henry the Lion about an anti-French alliance with England. June 15 – Battle of Fimreite: King Sverre of Norway defeats and kills his rival, Magnus V (Erlingsson) near Fimreite. Sverre takes the throne and becomes sole ruler of Norway (until 1202).

Year 1350 ( MCCCL ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the 14th century, Europe witnessed significant historical events that shaped the course of its future. The Black Death pandemic, caused by the Yersinia pestis bacterium, swept through Asia, Europe, and North Africa, causing a severe demographic crisis and widespread upheavals. It peaked in Europe during the years 1347 to 1350, and estimates indicate it claimed 75 to 200 million lives in Eurasia, marking it as the most devastating pandemic in human history.

Year 1318 ( MCCCXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, several significant events occurred, which greatly influenced the course of history. The political landscape in Europe saw dramatic changes as King Birger of Sweden was deposed and replaced by his brother Magnus, marking the end of a fierce family feud. In the maritime industry, improvements in shipbuilding resulted in faster and more efficient trade and travel. This period was marked by devastating famines across Europe, which led to population decline and fostered a push for advancements in agricultural technologies.

Year 1395 ( MCCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, significant events took place shaping the medieval world. In Europe, the Ottoman Empire, led by Sultan Bayezid I, successfully defeated the Christian alliance under Sigismund, the Holy Roman Emperor, in the Battle of Nicopolis. Meanwhile, in East Asia, Ming Dynasty China began the construction of the Forbidden City in its capital, Nanjing. And on the Arabian Peninsula, the 14-year-old Sultan Qaitbay claimed the throne and took over the throne, securing control of the territory.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome , instead of the normal two. Trisomy occurs when an error called non-disjunction happens during the formation of eggs or sperm, leading to a fertilized cell having an extra chromosome. Trisomies can have significant consequences on a person's development and health, with outcomes ranging from mild to severe intellectual disabilities, physical abnormalities, and developmental delays. Some well-known examples of trisomies are Down syndrome (Trisomy 21), Edwards syndrome (Trisomy 18), and Patau syndrome (Trisomy 13).

Georg Hackl ( often named : Hackl Schorsch , ; born 9 September 1966 ) is a German former luger who competed from the late 1980s to the early 2000s. As one of the sport's most successful and decorated athletes, he earned three consecutive gold medals in men's singles luge at the Winter Olympics between 1992 and 1998, making him the first luger in history to achieve this feat. In addition to his Olympic success, Hackl has also won several World Championship titles and accumulated numerous podium finishes in World Cup competitions.

Year 1514 ( MDXIV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year witnessed various notable events that shaped the world's history, arts, and politics. The Spanish empire continued its expansion in America, cementing its dominance across the territories. King James IV of Scotland concluded treaties with France and Spain, which led to strong alliances across the continent. In Italy, Raphael painted the famed artwork "Sistine Madonna" during this time, showcasing the impact of the Renaissance on European arts and culture.

Phillis Wheatley Peters, also spelled Phyllis and Wheatly (c. 1753 – December 5, 1784) was an American author who was the first African-American author of a published book of poetry. Born in West Africa, she was sold into slavery at the age of seven or eight and transported to North America, where she was bought by the Wheatley family of Boston. After she learned to read and write, they encouraged her poetry when they saw her talent.On a 1773 trip to London with her master's son, seeking publication of her work, Wheatley met prominent people who became patrons.

Year 1455 (MCDLV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 8 – Pope Nicholas V publishes Romanus Pontifex, an encyclical addressed to King Afonso V of Portugal, which sanctions the conquest of non-Christian lands, and the reduction of native non-Christian populations to 'perpetual slavery'. (Later there will be a dramatic reversal when, in 1537, the bull Sublimis Deus of Pope Paul III forbids the enslavement of non-Christians.) February 23 – The Gutenberg Bible is the first book printed with movable type.

McLean Hospital ( formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum ) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont , Massachusetts , and a world-class facility that offers expert care for those struggling with mental health challenges. Established in 1811, it has been a longstanding beacon of support for its patients, pioneering cutting-edge treatment and research for nearly two centuries. Affiliated with Harvard Medical School, McLean has become an important academic resource in the realm of psychiatry. With a highly dedicated and experienced team of mental health professionals, the hospital is dedicated to providing personalized and compassionate care.

Year 1401 ( MCDI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1401 (MCDI), several noteworthy events occurred which shaped the future for years to come. For instance, Europe and Asia saw the rise of monarchs, treaties being formed, and discoveries made that altered the world map. Throughout this year, numerous major powers within these continents began negotiating alliances and trading partnerships. Similarly, numerous religious, technological, and scientific innovations emerged that sparked development in different realms.

Events  January–June  January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought. January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath, the Eastern Church in India cuts itself off from colonial Portuguese tutelage. February 2 – New Amsterdam (later renamed New York City) is incorporated. February 3 – Cardinal Mazarin returns to Paris from exile. March 14 – A Dutch fleet defeats the English in the Battle of Leghorn; the Dutch commander, Johan van Galen, later dies of his wounds. April 20 – Oliver Cromwell expels the Rump Parliament in England.

Year 1362 ( MCCCLXII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year was significant for its events that occurred around the world, affecting various civilizations and cultures. In Europe, it witnessed the Old Salt Route established in northern Germany, boosting trade in the region. Meanwhile, in Sweden, the young King Magnus Eriksson enforced royal authority against Swedish nobles. As the Hundred Years' War raged between England and France, the English saw major defeats at the Battles of La Rochelle and La Reole.

Year 1042 ( MXLII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This was a significant year in history, marked by several notable events taking place in various regions of the world. In England, King Harthacnut died suddenly at the age of 23, with his half-brother, Edward the Confessor, succeeding him. In France, the Normans established Fecamp, a maritime town located along the Normandy coast, where a major construction project of an abbey began in order to defend its inhabitants.

Year 1325 ( MCCCXXV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1325 (MCCCXXV), the world was marked by significant historical events, sociopolitical changes, and milestones in the field of arts and sciences. Rulers were engaged in territorial disputes and battles, while prominent personalities influenced culture and laid the groundwork for future developments. Some of the key highlights from 1325 include the foundation of the ancient city of Tenochtitlan, which would eventually become Mexico City. Moreover, wars continued in European regions, most notably in Italy where battles were fought amongst local feudal lords.

Bdellovibrio is a genus of Gram-negative , obligate aerobic bacterium . One of the more notable characteristics of this genus is its predatory nature, specifically its ability to invade and consume other Gram-negative bacteria, such as Escherichia coli and Pseudomonas aeruginosa. This unique behavior has generated significant interest in Bdellovibrio as a potential alternative to traditional antibiotics, particularly in the fight against multidrug-resistant bacterial infections. Moreover, research into the mechanism of bacterial predation is improving our understanding of microbial ecology, while also revealing potential targets for future development of new antimicrobial drugs or strategies.

Eleusine coracana, or finger millet, also known as ragi in India, kodo in Nepal, is an annual herbaceous plant widely grown as a cereal crop in the arid and semiarid areas in Africa and Asia. It is a tetraploid and self-pollinating species probably evolved from its wild relative Eleusine africana.Finger millet is native to the Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands. Interesting crop characteristics of finger millet are the ability to withstand cultivation at altitudes over 2000 m above sea level, its high drought tolerance, and the long storage time of the grains.History Finger millet originated in East Africa (Ethiopian and Ugandan highlands).

Year 1184 ( MCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the Holy Roman Empire, Emperor Frederick Barbarossa launched his third attempt to reduce the defiant Lombard League during the Italian campaign. Simultaneously, Saladin – the Sultan of Egypt and Syria – was focusing on consolidating his power throughout the Levant in a move that eventually culminated in the pivotal Battle of Hattin in 1187. Back in Europe, several pivotal structures were erected in England, like the Hospital of St. Cross in Winchester, and Nottingham Castle was constructed by Richard the Lionheart.

Kazimierz Funk ( ; February 23 , 1884 – November 19 , 1967 ) , commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk , was a Polish biochemist and a pioneer in the field of nutritional science. Born in Warsaw, Poland, he is best known for his discovery and isolation of various essential vitamins, such as vitamin B1, in 1912. This breakthrough led him to propose the term "vitamine" or "vital amine," the original name for vitamins. His research had profound implications in the prevention and treatment of vitamin-deficient diseases such as beriberi, scurvy, and pellagra, ultimately transforming human nutrition and revolutionizing the study of preventive medicine.

Year 1161 (MCLXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 3 – Battle of Oslo: King Inge I (the Hunchback) is defeated and killed, while fighting the forces of Haakon II (the Broadshouldered). He is succeeded by Haakon with the 5-year-old Magnus V as co-ruler, but not without challenges to his sovereignty. Magnus II (Henriksson), pretender to the Swedish throne, is murdered by Charles VII (or Karl), who becomes king of Sweden (until 1167).

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola , released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. The MC68010 was primarily used in computer systems, including Unix workstations, Amiga, and Apple Lisa. This microprocessor brought improvements, such as an enhanced instruction set, better addressing modes, and increased memory management capabilities. It featured an extended address bus (24 bits), allowing it to address up to 16 megabytes of memory, along with faster performance, better multitasking capabilities, and additional exception vector table attributes.

Symbiosis ( from Greek , , `` living together '' , from , , `` together '' , and , , "living" ) refers to the close and prolonged interaction between two or more organisms of different species that typically mutually benefit each other. The relationships may range from mutualism, where both parties benefit, to commensalism, where one organism benefits while the other is unaffected. Some symbiotic relationships can be so close that the individuals of one species cannot survive without their partner from the other species. This vital relationship can be found among numerous ecosystems and holds a crucial role in maintaining overall ecological balance.

Year 1293 ( MCCXCIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, major events around the world were taking place, particularly in Europe and Asia. In June, Mamluk Sultan of Egypt and Syria, Al-Ashraf Khalil, successfully captured the crusader city of Acre, bringing an end to the Crusader presence in the Holy Land. In Japan, the Kamakura shogunate faced a challenge by the imperial court, eventually leading to the demise of Emperor Daigo in favor of the newly-proclaimed Emperor Go-Fukakusa.

Jon Howard Appleton (January 4, 1939 – January 30, 2022) was an American composer, an educator and a pioneer in electro-acoustic music. His earliest compositions in the medium, e.g. "Chef d'Oeuvre" and "Newark Airport Rock" (1967) attracted attention because they established a new tradition some have called programmatic electronic music. In 1970, he won Guggenheim, Fulbright and American-Scandinavian Foundation fellowships. When he was twenty-eight years old, he joined the faculty of Dartmouth College where he established one of the first electronic music studios in the United States.

Year 1541 ( MDXLI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, multiple significant events transpired across the globe, primarily focusing on exploration and political developments. The Portuguese established a stronghold in Southeast Asia as European conquests in the New World intensified. Leaders struggled to navigate through warfare, succession, and diplomatic intricacies, ultimately impacting religious structures and causing many ideological schisms. The year 1541 witnessed great advancements in the scientific and cultural domains, stimulating knowledge growth and shaping history in numerous unforeseen ways.

is the Latin name under which the "Lamb of God" is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other Christian liturgies descending from the Latin liturgical tradition. It is the name given to a specific prayer that occurs in these liturgies, and is the name given to the music pieces that accompany the text of this prayer.The use of the title "Lamb of God" in liturgy is based on , in which St. John the Baptist, upon seeing Jesus, proclaims "Behold, the Lamb of God, who takes away the sin of the world!

Year 1578 (MDLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 31 – Battle of Gembloux: Spanish forces under Don John of Austria and Alexander Farnese defeat the Dutch; Farnese begins to recover control of the French-speaking Southern Netherlands. April 27 – The Duel of the Mignons claims the lives of two favorites of Henry III of France, and two favourites of Henry I, Duke of Guise. May 26 – The Alteratie in Amsterdam ends Catholic rule, and open Catholic worship there.

Year 1290 ( MCCXC ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, various notable events unfolded around the globe. King Edward I of England issued the Edict of Expulsion, leading to the expulsion of all Jews from the country, causing a large migration and impacting communities. In Asia, the Mongols extended their rule, bringing new levels of economic and cultural exchange among the Eastern nations. Simultaneously, European explorers sought new routes for trade, seeking fortunes and influencing global connectivity for centuries to come.

1581 ( MDLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Gregorian calendar, and a common year starting on Wednesday in the Julian calendar. During this year, significant events across the globe marked this time in history. In Europe, religious turmoil intensified as tensions between the Catholic Church and Protestant Reformation led to conflict, particularly between Spain and the Dutch rebels in the Low Countries. This was also a significant period for the expansion of global trade and colonization as explorers from Spain, Portugal, and England voyaged to the New World, discovering and conquering new territories.

Divorce ( also known as dissolution of marriage ) is the process of terminating a marriage or marital union . Divorce usually entails the canceling or reorganizing of the legal duties and responsibilities of marriage, thus dissolving the bonds of matrimony between a married couple under the rule of law in a particular jurisdiction. The divorce process often involves various aspects, such as division of property, child custody, alimony, and child support payments, which can be contested or agreed upon mutually. Grounds for divorce vary widely across cultures and religions, with factors like irreconcilable differences, adultery, abuse, and abandonment commonly cited.

Year 1182 (MCLXXXII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April – Massacre of the Latins: The Roman Catholic (called "Latin") inhabitants of Constantinople massacre the Venetian, Genoan, and other Latin officials and traders who rule as agents of Empress Maria of Antioch. She is the mother and regent of 12-year-old Emperor Alexios II. In August, Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Maria's late husband, Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos), raises an army and enters the city, representing himself as the 'protector' of Alexios.

Anne Boleyn ( ; 1501 – 19 May 1536 ) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536 , as the second wife of King Henry VIII, and the mother of Queen Elizabeth I. Born to noble parents Sir Thomas Boleyn and Lady Elizabeth Howard, her marriage to the king marked a defining period in England’s political and religious history. Their union, while initially passionate, was contentious, as the monarch sought annulment from his first wife, Catherine of Aragon, in a protracted process that eventually led to the break from the Catholic Church.

In mathematics, an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere, which is the set of points in -dimensional Euclidean space that are situated at a constant distance  from a fixed point, called the center. It is the generalization of an ordinary sphere in the ordinary three-dimensional space. The "radius" of a sphere is the constant distance of its points to the center. When the sphere has unit radius, it is usual to call it the unit -sphere or simply the -sphere for brevity.

Year 1444 (MCDXLIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+(-10(X)+50(L))+(-1(I)+5(V)) = 1444.Events  January–December  March 2 – The League of Lezhë, an alliance of Albanian principalities, is established in Lezhë; George Kastrioti Skanderbeg is proclaimed commander of the Albanian resistance.

Events  January–June  February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary, Queen of Scots, after Mary has been implicated in a plot to murder Elizabeth. Seven days later, on the orders of Elizabeth's privy council, Mary is beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle. February 12–24 – Period of exceptionally severe cold in western Europe. April 29 – Singeing the King of Spain's Beard: On an expedition against Spain, English privateer Sir Francis Drake leads a raid in the Bay of Cádiz, sinking at least 23 ships of the Spanish fleet.

Year 1208 ( MCCVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year marked several significant events across various realms. Europe was fraught with political strife and religious discord, as Pope Innocent III excommunicated the Count of Toulouse, starting the Albigensian Crusade against the Cathars. In Asia, Genghis Khan launched his conquest campaign of the Western Xia dynasty, bringing turmoil to northwestern China. Meanwhile, as trade flourished in Africa, the famed Mali Empire was on the verge of forming under its first Mansa, Sundiata Keita.

William Makepeace Thackeray (; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863) was a British novelist, author and illustrator. He is known for his satirical works, particularly his 1848 novel Vanity Fair, a panoramic portrait of British society, and the 1844 novel The Luck of Barry Lyndon, which was adapted for a 1975 film by Stanley Kubrick.BiographyThackeray, an only child, was born in Calcutta, British India, where his father, Richmond Thackeray (1 September 1781 – 13 September 1815), was secretary to the Board of Revenue in the East India Company.

Year 1321 (MCCCXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December c. May–June – Leper scare: Rumours that lepers (acting on the orders of Jews bribed by Moors) are attempting to poison the Christian population spread throughout southern France. August 14 – King Edward II of England reluctantly agrees to demands from his barons to send Hugh le Despenser, 1st Earl of Winchester, and his son Hugh Despenser the Younger into exile. October 29 – King Stephen Uroš II Milutin of Serbia dies.

Year 1377 ( MCCCLXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, a multitude of events transpired which helped shape history. Several nations in Europe underwent major shifts, including England's farewell to the famous monarch King Edward III, who died after a 50-year reign. Following his death, Edward's 10-year-old grandson Richard II ascended to the throne, signifying a new chapter in the royal lineage. Meanwhile, Florence struggled under a new government in the absence of the dynamic duo of nobles who once reigned: Cosimo and Lorenzo de' Medici.

Year 1435 (MCDXXXV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 11 – Sweden's first Riksdag of the Estates is summoned under rebel leader Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, who is elected rikshövitsman (military commander of the realm), in the absence of a king, on January 13. January 13 – Sicut Dudum, a papal bull forbidding the enslavement of the Guanche natives in Canary Islands by the Spanish, is promulgated by Pope Eugene IV. February 2 – The Kingdom of Naples passes to  René of Anjou.

Renate Titzia Groenewold (born 8 October 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer.Groenewold has won several Dutch Championships. In 1999, 2002 and 2003 she won the Dutch allround championship. At the European Allround Championships she has won various medals. Five times she came in third in the overall ranking. In 2005, she won the silver medal which was her best result at the European Championships. In 2001, she also came in third in the overall ranking on the World Allround Championships, which she won in 2004.Besides participating in the all-round championships Groenewold has participated in the championships for individual distances.

Year 1213 ( MCCXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, numerous historical events took place that impacted different aspects of society, such as politics, religion, and culture. Pope Innocent III proclaimed the Magna Carta "null and void" while significant conflicts like the Albigensian Crusade and the Anglo-French War escalated. The world experienced progress, change, and clashes in religion, science, arts, and feudal rights – demonstrating the continued development of diverse facets of civilization throughout this unique moment in history.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973 , to fly by the planets Mercury and Venus. The spacecraft provided us with the first close-up images of Mercury, the smallest planet in our solar system, and made key scientific discoveries about its surface, atmosphere, and magnetic properties. The mission also made significant findings about Venus's thick atmosphere and collected important data about solar radiation and particles present in space. The success of the Mariner 10 mission paved the way for future planetary exploration and provided a strong foundation for understanding the formation and dynamics of the inner solar system.

"Coven"  usually refers to a group or gathering of witches. The word "coven" (from Anglo-Norman covent, cuvent, from Old French covent, from Latin conventum = convention) remained largely unused in English until 1921 when Margaret Murray promoted the idea that all witches across Europe met in groups of thirteen which they called "covens".NeopaganismIn Wicca and other similar forms of neopagan witchcraft, such as Stregheria and Feri, a coven is a gathering or community of witches, like an affinity group, engagement group, or small covenant group.

Year 1552 (MDLII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January 15 – Henry II of France and Maurice, Elector of Saxony, sign the Treaty of Chambord. February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds the Chilean city of Valdivia, as Santa María la Blanca de Valdivia. February 24 – The privileges of the Hanseatic League are abolished in England. March – The Act of Uniformity imposes the Protestant Book of Common Prayer on England. March 26 – Guru Amar Das becomes the Third Sikh Guru.

Year 1361 (MCCCLXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 17 – An-Nasir Hasan, Mamluk Sultan of Egypt, is killed by one of his own mamluks, Yalbugha al-Umari, who, with the senior Mamluk emirs, has al-Mansur Muhammad installed as the new sultan. April 13 – The University of Pavia is founded, on the Italian Peninsula. July 27 – Battle of Visby: King Valdemar IV of Denmark conquers the city of Visby by defeating his peasant army. This allows Lübeck to become the new leading city of the Hanseatic League.

Year 1344 ( MCCCXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked several significant events that greatly impacted Europe, particularly relating to war and religion. The Hundred Years' War was intensifying as England claimed more victories over the French. Additionally, the Papacy returned to Rome, under Pope Clement VI, from Avignon in France, strengthening the power of the church in Italy. In North Africa, the Nasrid Kingdom of Granada seized control of the Kingdom of Algeciras after a bloody siege, further expanding their reign in the Iberian Peninsula.

The tale of the founding of Rome is recounted in traditional stories handed down by the ancient Romans themselves as the history of the Eternal City goes back to the very beginning of Western civilization. Central to these enduring legends are the twin brothers, Romulus and Remus, the supposed sons of Mars, the god of war. Abandoned at birth and nursed by a she-wolf, these infants were raised by a shepherd who would inadvertently forge a nation. With fates entwined, Romulus and Remus later discover their divine ancestry and decide to build a new city upon the banks of the River Tiber.

Andrew Stuart "Andy" Fastow (born December 22, 1961) is a convicted felon and former financier who was the chief financial officer of Enron Corporation, an energy trading company based in Houston, Texas, until he was fired shortly before the company declared bankruptcy. Fastow was one of the key figures behind the complex web of off-balance-sheet special purpose entities (limited partnerships which Enron controlled) used to conceal Enron's massive losses in their quarterly balance sheets. By unlawfully maintaining personal stakes in these ostensibly independent ghost-entities, he was able to defraud Enron out of tens of millions of dollars.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts , in the northeastern United States. Its historic, maritime character and ample beaches attract heavy tourism during the summer months. The cape is made up of 15 quaint, picturesque towns that offer unique coastal scenery, fresh seafood, beautiful sandy beaches, and various water sports opportunities. Renowned for its historic charm and beautiful landscape, Cape Cod has lighthouses, clam shacks, and cranberry bogs as distinctive landmarks. Visitors can also enjoy numerous recreational activities, such as hiking and cycling along the Cape Cod Rail Trail, kayaking, or sailing.

Year 1131 ( MCXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, several notable events took place that shaped history. Among these were political upheavals, religious conflicts, and cultural milestones. For instance, in Europe, there was ongoing strife between powerful nobles and their adversaries. Moreover, some monastic institutions expanded, gaining further influence over ecclesiastical affairs. At the same time, multiple empires grappled with internal and external challenges, revealing deep-seated issues within their ruling hierarchies.

Year 1472 ( MCDLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In 1472, significant events unfolded that shaped both political and cultural aspects of Europe and beyond. King Christian I of Denmark attempted to reestablish the Kalmar Union, but the resistance from the Swedish kingdom resulted in the loss of Northern Swedish territories. Elsewhere in Europe, William Caxton set up his first printing press, signaling the beginning of mass book production and creating an influential pathway for intellectual advancements in future centuries.

Howard Kingsbury Smith (May 12, 1914 – February 15, 2002) was an American journalist, radio reporter, television anchorman, political commentator, and film actor. He was one of the original members of the team of war correspondents known as the Murrow Boys.Early life and educationEarly career and CBS yearsWorld War IIUpon graduating, Smith worked for the New Orleans Item, with United Press in London, and with The New York Times. In January 1940, Smith was sent to Berlin, where he joined the Columbia Broadcasting System under Edward R. Murrow.

Year 990 ( CMXC ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This particular year held significance due to multiple occurrences that influenced and altered various realms - politics, society, and culture. Some key events during this time included Duke Mieszko I's historic unification of Poland, as well as Pope John XV ordaining the Synod of Reims, which held weight in both religious and political spheres. Meanwhile, powerful Viking leader Olav Tryggvason wielded his influence and Viking exploration experienced profound developments that expanded their impact beyond Scandinavia.

Bessarabia (; ; ; , Bessarabiya; ; , Bessarabiya; , Besarabiya) is a historical region in Eastern Europe, bounded by the Dniester river on the east and the Prut river on the west. About two thirds of Bessarabia lies within modern-day Moldova, with the Ukrainian Budjak region covering the southern coastal region and part of the Ukrainian Chernivtsi Oblast covering a small area in the north.In the aftermath of the Russo-Turkish War (1806–1812), and the ensuing Peace of Bucharest, the eastern parts of the Principality of Moldavia, an Ottoman vassal, along with some areas formerly under direct Ottoman rule, were ceded to Imperial Russia.

CBE may refer to:Travel CBE, IATA code for Greater Cumberland Regional Airport. CBE, ICAO code for Aerocaribe, airline based in Cancun, Mexico. CBE, Railway code for Coimbatore Junction Cross Bronx Expressway, a major freeway in the New York City borough of the Bronx.Communications CBE, the former callsign of the CBC Radio One AM station in Windsor, Ontario. CBE-FM, callsign of the CBC Radio Two FM station in Windsor, Ontario.Banking The Central Bank of Egypt, the central (or reserve) bank in Egypt.

Year 1175 ( MCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, significant events and developments took place that greatly influenced world history. Key among these was the construction of the Angkor Wat Temple in Cambodia by the Khmer King Suryavarman II. In Europe, Ireland witnessed the birth of the High King Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair, while Spain continued its long battle against the Moors in the famous Reconquista. As such, the year 1175 brought a multitude of milestones that shaped the social, cultural, and political realms for the decades to come.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County, in the U.S. state of Vermont. The population was 3,612 at the 2020 census. Home to some of the state of Vermont's wealthiest residents, the municipality is a commuter town for nearby Hanover, New Hampshire across the Connecticut River. The town is part of the Dresden School District, the first interstate school district in the United States, signed into law by President John F. Kennedy. The town contains the Norwich Mid-Century Modern Historic District.History The boundaries of Norwich were established on July 4, 1761, when Governor Benning Wentworth of New Hampshire defined the boundaries of townships in Vermont.

Year 1169 ( MCLXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year held a significant position in European history, witnessing critical moments such as the Norman Invasion of Ireland and a blood moon observed across several continents. Throughout Europe, territorial disputes, wars and power dynamics influenced various regions. The world experienced political and territorial changes including emerging republics, ongoing battles and the establishment of historic treaties, all which influenced the course of the history leading into the next century.

Robert von Ranke Graves ( 24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985 ) was a British poet , historical novelist , classicist, and translator. Born in Wimbledon, London, Graves grew up amidst the intellectual atmosphere of his time, joining the Royal Welch Fusiliers during the First World War. Deeply affected by his wartime experiences, he published his first collection of poetry in 1916, establishing a lifelong career as a prolific writer. Best known for his critically acclaimed historical novel "I, Claudius" (1934), Graves masterfully combined historical accuracy with compelling narratives.

Year 1529 (MDXXIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 2 – The Örebro Synod provides the theological foundation of the Swedish Reformation, following the economic foundation of it, after the Reduction of Gustav I of Sweden. March –  Battle of Shimbra Kure: Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi, with 200 men armed with matchlocks, defeats the army of Dawit II, Emperor of Ethiopia. March 25 – Blood libel against the Jewish community of Bosen (formerly in Hungary, today in Slovakia), on the first day of Passover.

A corporate haven, corporate tax haven, or multinational tax haven, is used to describe a jurisdiction that multinational corporations find attractive for establishing subsidiaries or incorporation of regional or main company headquarters, mostly due to favourable tax regimes (not just the headline tax rate), and/or favourable secrecy laws (such as the avoidance of regulations or disclosure of tax schemes), and/or favourable regulatory regimes (such as weak data-protection or employment laws).While the "headline" corporate tax rate in jurisdictions most often implicated in base erosion and profit shifting (BEPS) is always above zero (e.g.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml ) is a general-purpose , multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of ML (Meta Language) with a focus on expressiveness and efficiency. Developed by the French Institute for Research in Computer Science and Automation (INRIA) in the late 1990s, OCaml has been widely used for large-scale projects, providing robust support for functional, imperative, and object-oriented programming styles. Its sophisticated static type-checking system ensures code safety and maintainability, making it suitable for developing critical systems in industries such as finance, research, and security.

Year 1327 ( MCCCXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, many events unfolded that helped shape the course of history. These included important transitions in the ruling dynasties across the continents, technological advancements such as the water-powered mechanical clock in Italy, and evolving religious dynamics with the canonization of Saint Thomas Aquinas. Furthermore, cultural and educational institutions thrived as construction commenced on several magnificent buildings, reflecting the Renaissance spirit prevalent during that era.

Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov (;  – 10 March 1940) was a Russian writer, medical doctor, and playwright active in the first half of the 20th century. He is best known for his novel The Master and Margarita, published posthumously, which has been called one of the masterpieces of the 20th century.He is also known for his novel The White Guard (also called Belaya gvardiya) , his plays Ivan Vasilievich, Flight (also called The Run) , The Days of the Turbins , and other works of the 1920s and 1930s.

Solidarity Electoral Action (, AWS) was a political coalition in Poland. Since 1997, its official name has been Akcja Wyborcza Solidarność Prawicy (AWSP) or Electoral Action Solidarity of the Right. Ruch Społeczny AWS (RS AWS), or Social Movement for Electoral Action Solidarity, was the political arm of the Solidarity trade union and was formerly the leading party within AWS.BackgroundAWS was formed in 1996 as a coalition of over 30 parties, uniting liberal, conservative and Christian-democratic forces. Marian Krzaklewski was its first chairman. In 1997 the coalition was joined by RS AWS, and by the Freedom Union.

Year 1318 (MCCCXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March – King Birger of Sweden is deposed, and forced to flee to Denmark (alternative date is April). April 1 – Berwick-upon-Tweed is retaken by the Scottish from the English. April – The inhabitants of Benevento, Italy rise against the Pope, and demand some political autonomy. The rebellion is crushed by William of Frejus, and the archbishop of Naples. May 11 – Battle of Dysert O'Dea: The Irish armies of Conor O'Dea defeat the Hiberno-Normans under Richard de Clare.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe . It was published by Sierra from 1987 to 2009. The games follow the misadventures of a balding, leisure suit-wearing middle-aged man named Larry Laffer, in his desperate attempts to impress women and succeed in life. The series gained popularity due to its combination of humor, cartoonish graphics, and risqué subject matter, incorporating light-hearted sexual content, dating sim elements, and subtle cultural commentary. Despite initial controversy and some moral objections to its adult-oriented nature, Leisure Suit Larry ultimately gained a cult following and established itself as an iconic video game series in pop culture history.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD . These early settlers, called the Lucayan people, were a branch of the Arawak tribe that originated in South America. The Lucayans spread throughout the archipelago, where they led a simple lifestyle relying on fishing, farming, and trade with other Caribbean communities. As they evolved and thrived, their society began to display its distinct Bahamian character. However, the peaceful lives of the Lucayans faced devastation with the arrival of Spanish explorers, led by Christopher Columbus in 1492.

Year 993 (CMXCIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The 12-year-old King Otto III gives the Sword of Saints Cosmas and Damian (also known as the Sword of Essen) as a gift to the convent in Essen. It symbolises the martyrdom of Cosmas and Damian, the patron saints of the city. Charles, duke of Lower Lorraine, dies in prison in Orléans (see 991). He is succeeded by his son Otto II, who inherits the full dukedom and pledges his allegiance to Otto III.

Arthrobacter ( from the Greek , `` jointed small stick ” ) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found in soil, where it plays a significant role in nutrient recycling and the decomposition of organic matter. These Gram-positive, rod-shaped bacteria exhibit unique adaptability to various environments due to their ability to transform into dormant, resistant forms under unfavorable conditions. Arthrobacter is well known for its capabilities in bioremediation, the process of using living organisms to detoxify polluted environments, such as soils contaminated with pesticides or heavy metals. Some strains have also been used to produce useful biodegradable plastics and pharmaceutical intermediates.

Perpignan (, , ;  ;  ;  ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department (known as Northern Catalonia) in southern France, in the heart of the plain of Roussillon, at the foot of the Pyrenees a few kilometres from the Mediterranean Sea and the scrublands of the Corbières massif. It is the centre of the Perpignan Mediterranée Métropole metropolitan area.In 2016 Perpignan had a population of 121,875 (Perpignanais(e) in French, Perpinyanés(a) in Catalan) in the commune proper, and the metropolitan area had a total population of 268,577, making it the last major French city before the Spanish border.

Lazzi (; from the Italian lazzo, a joke or witticism) are stock comedic routines that are associated with Commedia dell'arte. Performers, especially those playing the masked Arlecchino, had many examples of this in their repertoire, and would use improvisatory skills to weave them into the plot of dozens of different commedia scenarios. These largely physical sequences could be improvised or preplanned within the performance and were often used to enliven the audience when a scene was dragging, to cover a dropped line or cue, or to delight an expectant audience with the troupe's specialized lazzi.Lazzi could be completed by a single player (e.g.

Niihau (Hawaiian: ), anglicized as Niihau , is the westernmost main and seventh largest inhabited island in Hawaii. It is  southwest of Kauaʻi across the Kaulakahi Channel. Its area is . Several intermittent playa lakes provide wetland habitats for the Hawaiian coot, the Hawaiian stilt, and the Hawaiian duck. The island is designated as critical habitat for Brighamia insignis, an endemic and endangered species of Hawaiian lobelioid. The United States Census Bureau defines Niihau and the neighboring island and State Seabird Sanctuary of Lehua as Census Tract 410 of Kauai County, Hawaii.

Year 1444 ( MCDXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1444 (MCDXLIV), several significant events transpired throughout the world, impacting politics, culture, and religion. In Europe, the Crusade of Varna commenced as Christian powers, including Hungary and the Polish-Lithuanian union, sought to contain the rising Ottoman Empire's influence. Across the sea, the Iberian kingdom of Portugal reached a major milestone in navigation as Gil Eanes completed the first successful voyage around Cape Bojador in Africa, a dangerous maritime endeavor.

Year 1149 (MCXLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) recovers Corfu with the help of the Venetians, who defeat the Sicilian fleet. During the three-month siege, Byzantine admiral Stephen Kontostephanos  is killed by a stone thrown by a catapult. Manuel prepares an offensive against the Normans, King Roger II sends a fleet (some 40 ships) under George of Antioch to pilliage the suburbs of Constantinople.

Year 1401 (MCDI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 6 – Rupert, King of Germany, is crowned King of the Romans at Cologne. March 2 – William Sawtrey, a Lollard, is the first person to be burned at the stake at Smithfield, London. March 13 – The Samogitians, supported by Grand Duke Vytautas of Lithuania, rebel against the Teutonic knights and burn two castles. Vytautas is granted increased autonomy by King Jogaila of the Poland–Lithuania union. March 17 – Turko-Mongol emperor Timur sacks Damascus.

Casimir IV ( in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon ; ; Lithuanian : ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1492) was the Grand Duke of Lithuania and later became the King of Poland in 1447. Born in Kraków, Poland, he was the second son of King Władysław II Jagiełło and Sophia of Halshany. He is renowned for his ability to balance power between Poland and Lithuania, both geopolitically and socially. As a capable and effective ruler, Casimir played a crucial role in uniting these territories, reinforcing the Polish-Lithuanian alliance that held prominence in 15th century Eastern Europe.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy recedes from the observer is continuously increasing with time.The accelerated expansion was discovered during 1998, by two independent projects, the Supernova Cosmology Project and the High-Z Supernova Search Team, which both used distant type Ia supernovae to measure the acceleration. The idea was that as type Ia supernovae have almost the same intrinsic brightness (a standard candle), and since objects that are further away appear dimmer, we can use the observed brightness of these supernovae to measure the distance to them.

Year 1358 ( MCCCLVIII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the year 1358, various significant events unfolded across Europe and Asia. In Europe, the Golden Bull was issued by Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, establishing specific conditions and freedoms for German noble princes, resulting in increased autonomy. The same year witnessed the French peasant uprising called the Jacquerie, triggered by burdensome taxation, famine, and aristocratic indifference, resulting in a violent period of retaliation against French nobles.

Year 1443 (MCDXLIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–December  July 22 – Battle of St. Jakob an der Sihl (Old Zürich War): The forces of the city of Zürich are defeated, but the Swiss Confederacy have insufficient strength to besiege and take the city. November 8 – Battle of Niš: John Hunyadi and the army of the Crusade of Varna defeat three armies of the Ottoman Empire, and capture the city of Niš in modern-day Serbia; Skanderbeg deserts the Ottoman camp and goes to Albania.

Events January–June February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary , Queen of Scots, for her involvement in various plots against her. Tensions between England and Scotland rise further as Catholic sympathizers stand by the beleaguered Scottish queen. March 10 – In what is seen as the beginning of the Anglo-Spanish War, Elizabeth sends a covert expeditionary force led by Sir Francis Drake to attack the Spanish ports in the Americas. April 12 – John Dee, Elizabeth's advisor, delivers the "British Empire" speech at a public lecture, signaling the nation's intent to grow and expand its territorial possessions.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene, outsider, wild human, an "other" who has not been "corrupted" by civilization, and therefore symbolizes humanity's innate goodness. Besides appearing in many works of fiction and philosophy, the stereotype was also heavily employed in early anthropological works.In English, the phrase first appeared in the 17th century in John Dryden's heroic play The Conquest of Granada (1672), wherein it was used in reference to newly created man. "Savage" at that time could mean "wild beast" as well as "wild man".

Proline (symbol Pro or P) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid (used in the biosynthesis of proteins), although it does not contain the amino group  but is rather a secondary amine. The secondary amine nitrogen is in the protonated NH2+ form under biological conditions, while the carboxyl group is in the deprotonated −COO− form. The "side chain" from the α carbon connects to the nitrogen forming a pyrrolidine loop, classifying it as a aliphatic amino acid. It is non-essential in humans, meaning the body can synthesize it from the non-essential amino acid L-glutamate.

Year 1270 ( MCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked a period of significant changes around the globe, as regions recovered from past disasters and progress was made in various fields. Among important events during this time were the construction of important castles and cathedrals in Europe, the expansion of the Mongol Empire in Asia, and new discoveries in science, art, and culture. Trade flourished, which in turn brought new innovations, explorations, and migrations, and thus shaping human history for years to come.

Ross Powers (born February 10, 1979) is an American world champion halfpipe snowboarder from South Londonderry, Vermont, director of the snowboarding program at the Stratton Mountain School in Stratton, Vermont and a philanthropist.CareerThough he originally rode at Stratton Mountain, Vermont, his home mountain is now Okemo, Vermont. Powers helps with the design of the Superpipe and also helped design the RossCross Family Terrain Park. Powers also runs a snowboard camp through Okemo. He led the U.S. sweep in the 2002 Winter Olympics men's halfpipe competition, one day after his 23rd birthday.

Year 990 (CMXC) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Al-Mansur, de facto ruler of Al-Andalus, conquers the Castle of Montemor-o-Velho (modern Portugal), expanding the Umayyad Caliphate of Córdoba. The city of Lund, Sweden is founded, during the reign of the Danish king Sweyn Forkbeard (approximate date). Africa  The Ghana Empire takes the Berber town of Aoudaghost (modern Mauritania) as the West African nation makes further gains. Construction of the Al-Hakim Mosque by orders of the Fatimid vizier Gawar Al-Siqilli begins in Cairo (modern Egypt).

Year 1412 ( MCDXII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1412 (MCDXII), significant events occurred around the globe. Joan of Arc, a symbol of French resistance and later, a Roman Catholic saint, was born on January 6. Also, Muscovy and the Republic of Novgorod signed a peace treaty that strengthened the unity between these powerful nations. Socially, music and arts continued to flourish during the transition from the Late Middle Ages into the Renaissance era. In Asia, the Tran Dynasty was deposed, allowing the Ming Dynasty to establish direct control of Vietnam.

Year 1501 (MDI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 17 – Cesare Borgia returns triumphantly to Rome, from Romagna. March 25 – Portuguese navigator João da Nova probably discovers Ascension Island. It is definitely sighted and named on May 20, 1503 (Feast of the Ascension) by Afonso de Albuquerque. April – The Rebellion of the Alpujarras ends with the surrender of the last Muslim insurgents in the Alpujarra Mountains, who are given the choice of expulsion or conversion to Christianity.

Year 1464 ( MCDLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1464 (MCDLXIV), various significant events took place, impacting both Europe and the global stage. This leap year started on a Sunday and featured significant cultural, political, and historical changes. Notably, the Renaissance continued to gather steam throughout Europe, which profoundly influenced the continent’s art, literature, and learning. The Byzantine Empire further declined in power, and Western European nations commenced global exploration to locate trade routes, driven primarily by Spain and Portugal, shaping history for centuries to come.

A horoscope (or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart, astrological chart, astro-chart, celestial map, sky-map, star-chart, cosmogram, vitasphere, radical chart, radix, chart wheel or simply chart) is an astrological chart or diagram representing the positions of the Sun, Moon, planets, astrological aspects and sensitive angles at the time of an event, such as the moment of a person's birth. The word horoscope is derived from the Greek words ōra and scopos meaning "time" and "observer" (horoskopos, pl.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts, in the northeastern United States. Its historic, maritime character and ample beaches attract heavy tourism during the summer months. The name Cape Cod, coined in 1602 by Bartholomew Gosnold, is the ninth oldest English place-name in the U.S.As defined by the Cape Cod Commission's enabling legislation, Cape Cod is conterminous with Barnstable County, Massachusetts. It extends from Provincetown in the northeast to Woods Hole in the southwest, and is bordered by Plymouth to the northwest.

Year 1160 ( MCLX ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was an eventful year in global history, as it marked a significant period of political changes and various military conflicts. Several vital events happened during 1160, impacting society in various ways. King Louis VII of France divorced his wife Eleanor of Aquitaine, who then married Henry II, giving him control of England, as well as various lands in France. This paved the way for centuries of territorial disputes and power struggles.

A mace is a blunt weapon , a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end of a handle to deliver powerful blows. Historically, maces were often used by cavalry to deliver concussive force to their adversaries, smashing armor and breaking bones. These medieval weapons come in various shapes, such as a flanged or spiked metal head, to inflict even greater damage. In the later Middle Ages, maces began to feature spiked heads designed specifically to pierce the joints and gaps in plate armor, further increasing their battlefield effectiveness.

Year 1162 (MCLXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 6 – German forces, led by Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), capture Milan; much of the city is destroyed three weeks later, on the emperor's orders. The fortifications are demolished, and the churches are destroyed. The population is dispersed, and the commune abolished. The fate of Milan leads to the submission of Brescia, Piacenza, and many other northern Italian cities.

Year 1558 (MDLVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1558th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 558th year of the 2nd millennium, the 58th year of the 16th century, and the 9th year of the 1550s decade.Events  January–June  January 7 – French troops, led by Francis, Duke of Guise, take Calais, the last continental possession of the Kingdom of England. January 9 – Geneva becomes independent from the Canton of Bern.

Year 1024 ( MXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This significant year marked the commencement of the Umayyad emirate in Spain and the Arab capture of Corsica. Also during this time, German king Henry II established Bamberg Cathedral. Across Asia, Empress Zoë Porphyrogenita assumed the Byzantine throne alongside Romanos III. Culturally, in Japan, renowned playwright Sei Shōnagon completed her popular piece "The Pillow Book," providing a rich account of life at the Heian court.

Events January–June January 1 Colonel George Monck ( with his regiment ) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Coldstream and begins his advance towards London in support of the English Restoration, leading to the eventual reinstatement of the monarchy. This eventful movement gives the name "Coldstream Guards" to the famous British military unit. February 5 – In Spanish Naples, a great public building known as the Collegio della Compagnia della Missione is finally completed after a construction period lasting for over a decade. Its establishment marks a significant milestone in the dissemination of religious and cultural knowledge in the city.

In geometry , two figures or objects are congruent if they have the same shape and size , or if one has the same shape and size as the mirror image of the other. Congruent objects can be rotated, reflected, or translated, without altering their properties. In order for figures to be congruent, all of their corresponding sides and angles must be equal in length and degree. These criteria, called "congruence criteria," usually fall into five categories: Side-Angle-Side (SAS), Angle-Side-Angle (ASA), Side-Side-Side (SSS), Angle-Angle-Angle (AAA), and Right Angle-Hypotenuse-Side (RHS).

1499 (MCDXCIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 8 – Louis XII of France marries Anne of Brittany, in accordance with a law set by his predecessor, Charles VIII. May 19 – 13-year-old Catherine of Aragon, the future first wife of Henry VIII of England, is married by proxy to his brother, 12-year-old Arthur, Prince of Wales. July 22 – Battle of Dornach: The Swiss decisively defeat the army of Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC . The Late Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East and eastern Mediterranean was a significant event during this time. Societal upheaval, natural disasters, and population decline marked this era, ultimately leading to the fall of many great civilizations, such as the Hittites, Mycenaeans, and the Egyptian New Kingdom. Trade routes were disrupted, which severely affected economies and contributed to the loss of numerous technical advancements. This tumultuous period eventually paved the way for the rise of new societies, heralding the beginning of the Iron Age and the development of various distinct cultures.

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus of the family Pinaceae . Pinus is the sole genus in the subfamily Pinoideae. These trees are widely distributed across the northern hemisphere, and they are especially abundant in North America, Europe, and Asia. Pine trees can be distinguished from other conifers by their needles, which typically grow in clusters or fascicles. Each fascicle usually has between two to five needles, varying according to the species. Additionally, pine trees produce distinctive woody cones as their seed carriers, which differ in size and shape depending on the type of pine.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East, spanning modern-day Iraq, Syria, Lebanon, Palestine, Israel, Jordan, and Northern Egypt, together with the northern region of Kuwait, southeastern region of Turkey and the western portion of Iran. Some authors also include Cyprus.The region is one of the cradles of civilization because it is one location where settled farming first emerged as people started the process of clearance and modification of natural vegetation to grow newly domesticated plants as crops. Early human civilizations such as Sumer in Mesopotamia flourished as a result.

Year 1186 (MCLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 27 – Constance of Sicily marries Henry (the future Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor). John the Chanter becomes Bishop of Exeter. The Byzantine Empire recognizes the independence of Bulgaria and Serbia. Joscius becomes Archbishop of Tyre. Jayavarman VII, the king of Cambodia, founds the temple of Ta Prohm. After the death of the child-king Baldwin V, his mother succeeds him as Sibylla of Jerusalem, and appoints her disfavoured husband Guy de Lusignan king consort.

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating. In competitions, multiple skaters (typically between four and six) skate on an oval ice track with a length of . The rink itself is  long by  wide, which is the same size as an Olympic-sized figure skating rink and an international-sized ice hockey rink. Related sports include long track speed skating and inline speed skating.HistoryShort-track skating developed from speed skating events that were held with mass starts. This form of speed skating was mainly practised in the United States and Canada, as opposed to the international form, where athletes skated in pairs.

In software quality assurance , performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness, stability, speed, and scalability under a particular workload. It involves the assessment of various factors such as resource usage, throughput, latency, and response times, with the goal of identifying potential bottlenecks, ensuring reliability, and enhancing the user experience. By conducting performance testing, developers and QA teams can uncover issues before the software is deployed to end users, helping prevent costly and time-consuming post-release fixes.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation , probably via settlement from South America , through the Amerindian Taino tribes who inhabited the island in pre-Columbian times, to the arrival of Europeans in the early 16th century. The British took control of Anguilla in 1666, although French colonial forces briefly overtook the island several times throughout its history. The island has experienced sugar cane farming, various treaties, uprisings, and administrative disputes. With several revolutions against British rule, Anguilla ultimately gained separate administration and eventual independence, officially becoming an Overseas British Territory in 1980.

In category theory , a branch of mathematics , the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of universal constructions. It generalizes the concepts of the inverse limit in algebra and the direct limit in topology. Limits are essential in defining adjunctions, which express relationships between various functors and act as bridges between different categories. Furthermore, the idea of a colimit complements the notion of a limit by considering co-constructions and opposites. Together, both limit and colimit are fundamental in studying concepts such as commutative diagrams, equalizers, pullbacks, and monomorphisms that help us reveal the underlying structures of diverse mathematical fields.

Freestyle skiing is a  skiing discipline comprising aerials, moguls, cross, half-pipe, slopestyle and big air as part of the Winter Olympics. It can consist of a skier performing aerial flips and spins and can include skiers sliding rails and boxes on their skis. Known as "hot-dogging" in the early 1970s, it is also commonly referred to as freeskiing, jibbing, as well as many other names, around the world.History Ski acrobatics have been practiced since the 1930s/1940s. Aerial skiing was popularized in the 1950s by Olympic gold medalist Stein Eriksen. Early US competitions were held in the mid-1960s.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973, to fly by the planets Mercury and Venus. It was the first spacecraft to perform flybys of multiple planets.Mariner 10 was launched approximately two years after Mariner 9 and was the last spacecraft in the Mariner program. (Mariner 11 and Mariner 12 were allocated to the Voyager program and redesignated Voyager 1 and Voyager 2. )The mission objectives were to measure Mercury's environment, atmosphere, surface, and body characteristics and to make similar investigations of Venus.

Year 1210 ( MCCX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This particular year held historical significance, with events unfolding throughout the continents. In Europe, the construction of the magnificent Salisbury Cathedral in England began. Simultaneously, the Livonian Crusade commenced in present-day Latvia, while King Sancho I of Portugal made significant headway in capturing the Alentejo region from the Moors. The Albigensian Crusade, against Cathar heretics in southern France, also intensified under Pope Innocent III. These crucial events collectively shaped regional powers and territories in subsequent centuries.

Year 1354 ( MCCCLIV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events during 1354 include the signing of the Treaty of Stralsund, which resulted in Sweden regaining its territories in the Northern Baltic region, and the Ottoman Empire capturing the city of Gallipoli, marking their first stronghold in Europe. Additionally, in the art world, famed Italian painter Giovanni da Rimini began work on the illuminated manuscripts known as the Bolognese Bible. Meanwhile, in France, a large increase in alms and aids revealed growing concerns about the growing poor population.

Frederick James Prinze (born Frederick Karl Pruetzel; June 22, 1954 – January 29, 1977) was an American stand-up comedian and actor. Prinze was the star of the NBC-TV sitcom Chico and the Man from 1974 until his suicide in 1977, when he shot himself in the head at the young age of 22. Prinze was the father of actor Freddie Prinze Jr.Early lifePrinze was born Frederick Karl Pruetzel (German spelling: Prützel) at Saint Clare's Hospital in Manhattan, New York City the son of Edward Karl Pruetzel and Maria de Gracia Pruetzel (née Graniela y Ramirez).

Year 1059 ( MLIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a time of political and social turmoil, with significant events happening in various regions across the globe. In the Byzantine Empire, Nikephoros Bryennios staged an unsuccessful revolt against Emperor Isaac I Comnenos. In Scotland, King Macbeth lost his life at the Battle of Lumphanan, allowing Malcolm III to take his throne. Over in France, King Philip I enacted the Peace and Truce of God, attempting to bring about law and order amidst increasing violence among feudal lords.

Year 994 (CMXCIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 15 – Battle of the Orontes: Fatimid forces, under Turkish general Manjutakin (also the governor of Damascus), besiege Apamea (modern Syria). Emperor Basil II sends a Byzantine expeditionary army, led by Dux Michael Bourtzes, to relieve the city in alliance with the Hamdanid Dynasty. Manjutakin defeats with his forces the Hamdanids, and attacks the Byzantine force in the rear. The Byzantine army panics and flees, losing some 5,000 men in the process.

Year 1329 (MCCCXXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 1 – King John of Bohemia (of the Teutonic Order) captures Medvėgalis, an important fortress of the pagan Grand Duchy of Lithuania, and baptizes 6,000 of its defenders. February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1332). March 27 – Pope John XXII condemns some teachings of Meister Eckhart as heretical. April – Antipope Nicholas V is excommunicated by Pope John XXII.
