Year 1527 ( MDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was marked by numerous significant events that occurred in Europe and Asia, shaping the course of history. In April, the Spanish and German troops infamously sacked the city of Rome during the Spanish conquest of the Papal States, an event known as the Sack of Rome. This would weaken the Pope's authority for decades and ignite widespread Reformation. Also, in June, the famed explorer and conquistador John Cabot would reach Newfoundland, eventually resulting in England establishing the Province of Canada.

Berchtesgaden is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land , Bavaria , in southeastern Germany , near the border with Austria. This picturesque region, known for its stunning alpine landscapes, is a popular destination for nature lovers and outdoor enthusiasts. Visitors can explore the serene Königssee, a lake embedded among mountains, or embark on scenic hikes and treks in the surrounding Nationalpark Berchtesgaden. The town is also rich in history and features significant World War II sites like the Obersalzberg and the infamous Eagle's Nest. With its charming traditional architecture and warm Bavarian hospitality, Berchtesgaden is an idyllic haven for travellers seeking both relaxation and adventure.

ext3, or third extended filesystem, is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel. It used to be the default file system for many popular Linux distributions. Stephen Tweedie first revealed that he was working on extending ext2 in Journaling the Linux ext2fs Filesystem in a 1998 paper, and later in a February 1999 kernel mailing list posting. The filesystem was merged with the mainline Linux kernel in November 2001 from 2.4.15 onward. Its main advantage over ext2 is journaling, which improves reliability and eliminates the need to check the file system after an unclean shutdown.

Year 1422 (MCDXXII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 10 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Deutschbrod: The Hussites defeat 2,000 Royalist Crusaders. March 21–May 2 – Hundred Years' War – Siege of Meaux: Meaux surrenders to the English. June 10–September – The Ottoman sultan Murad II besieges Constantinople; the siege is broken off as a result of the rebellion of Küçük Mustafa. August 22 – Use of the Spanish era dating system in the Kingdom of Portugal ceases.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae. Giant bamboos are the largest members of the grass family. The origin of the word "bamboo" is uncertain, but it probably comes from the Dutch or Portuguese language, which originally borrowed it from Malay or Kannada.In bamboo, as in other grasses, the internodal regions of the stem are usually hollow and the vascular bundles in the cross-section are scattered throughout the stem instead of in a cylindrical arrangement. The dicotyledonous woody xylem is also absent.

Mariner 2 (Mariner-Venus 1962), an American space probe to Venus, was the first robotic space probe to conduct a successful planetary encounter. The first successful spacecraft in the NASA Mariner program, it was a simplified version of the Block I spacecraft of the Ranger program and an exact copy of Mariner 1. The missions of the Mariner 1 and 2 spacecraft are sometimes known as the Mariner R missions. Original plans called for the probes to be launched on the Atlas-Centaur, but serious developmental problems with that vehicle forced a switch to the much smaller Agena B second stage.

In the performing arts , a scenario ( , ; from Italian : `` that which is pinned to the stage or scene, translated from scenarius ") refers to the skeletal framework on which a theatrical performance or film is based. It outlines the sequence of events, themes, settings, and characters to create a narrative that provides structure to the production. A well-crafted scenario serves as a guiding roadmap, helping performers to synchronize their actions, allowing them to effectively engage and connect with the audience, and aiding directors to deliver the intended experience.

Michelangelo Antonioni  (, ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007) was an Italian film director, screenwriter, editor, and painter. He is best known for his "trilogy on modernity and its discontents"—L'Avventura (1960), La Notte (1961), and L'Eclisse (1962)—as well as the English-language films Blowup (1966) and The Passenger (1975). His films have been described as "enigmatic and intricate mood pieces" that feature elusive plots, striking visual composition, and a preoccupation with modern landscapes.

Aloysius Lilius ( c. 1510 – 1576 ) , also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio , Luigi Giglio , was an Italian doctor, astronomer, and philosopher. He is best known for developing the Gregorian calendar, which replaced the Julian calendar in 1582. His proposal to reform the calendar was commissioned by Pope Gregory XIII to achieve more accurate calculations for the date of the Christian holiday Easter. Born in Cirò, Calabria, Lilius's major contribution to astronomy was based on his research about the discrepancy in the equinoxes, due to the incorrect duration estimation of a year.

Year 1387 (MCCCLXXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  Elizabeta Kotromanic, mother of Mary, Queen of Hungary and the former regent of Hungary, is murdered in prison by the Croatian rebels (her daughter is liberated on 4 June). January 1 – Charles III ascends to the throne of Navarre, after the death of his father, Charles II. January 5 – John I succeeds his father, Peter IV, as King of Aragon and Valencia, and forms an alliance with France and Castile.

Year 1383 ( MCCCLXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This particular year marked several significant events across various regions of the world. In Europe, the power struggle following the death of Portuguese King Ferdinand I resulted in a period of conflict known as the 1383-85 Crisis, which would eventually lead to the establishment of the House of Aviz. Meanwhile in Asia, the Ottomans under Sultan Murad I made rapid territorial gains by capturing much of present-day Greece, Albania and Macedonia, solidifying their dominance in the Balkans.

The National Botanic Gardens (Irish: Garraithe Náisiúnta na Lus) is a botanical garden in Glasnevin, 5 km north-west of Dublin city centre, Ireland. The 19.5 hectares are situated between Glasnevin Cemetery and the River Tolka where it forms part of the river's floodplain.The gardens were founded in 1795 by the Dublin Society (later the Royal Dublin Society) and are today in State ownership through the Office of Public Works. They house approximately 20,000 living plants and many millions of dried plant specimens. There are several architecturally notable greenhouses.

Year 1174 ( MCLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events that took place include the construction of the Tower of Pisa in Italy, beginning under architect Bonanno Pisano, and continuing for two centuries due to multiple interruptions. England witnessed the Treaty of Falaise, in which King William the Lion of Scotland agreed to acknowledge English King Henry II as his feudal lord after his capture during a failed invasion of Northumberland. Pope Alexander III also confirmed Waldenses as a Christian denomination, a group known for living a life of poverty and adherence to the Bible.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken  (June 7, 1896 – October 31, 1986) was an American physicist and chemist, primarily responsible for the early development of molecular orbital theory, i.e. the elaboration of the molecular orbital method of computing the structure of molecules. Mulliken received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1966 and the Priestley Medal in 1983.Early yearsRobert Mulliken was born in Newburyport, Massachusetts. His father, Samuel Parsons Mulliken, was a professor of organic chemistry at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. As a child, Robert Mulliken learned the name and botanical classification of plants and, in general, had an excellent, but selective, memory.

Events  January–June  January 22 – Impostor Mary Carleton is hanged at Newgate Prison in London, for multiple thefts and returning from penal transportation. February 10 – Molière's comédie-ballet The Imaginary Invalid premiers in Paris. During the fourth performance, on February 17, the playwright, playing the title rôle, collapses on stage, dying soon after. March 29 – Test Act: Roman Catholics and others who refuse to receive the sacrament of the Church of England cannot vote, hold public office, preach, teach, attend the universities or assemble for meetings in England.

Year 1037 (MXXXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – A revolt in northern Italy is started by Archbishop Aribert of Milan. King Henry III (eldest son of Emperor Conrad II) travels south of the Alps to quell it. February – At an Imperial Diet in Pavia (assembled by Conrad II), Aribert is accused of fomenting a revolt against the Holy Roman Empire, Conrad orders his arrest. May – Conrad II, with Pavian assistance, lays siege to Milan at the Porta Romana side, but the city holds out.

Jacques René Chirac ( , , ; 29 November 193226 September 2019 ) was a French politician who served as President of France from 1995 to 2007. Prior to that, he had held other notable positions, including Mayor of Paris (1977-1995) and Prime Minister of France on two separate occasions (1974-1976, 1986-1988). As President, Chirac's notable achievements included reforms in the healthcare and pension systems, an increase in national minimum wage, and implementing significant public transport projects such as Tramway and RER E. An advocate for the European Union, Chirac was known for his opposition to the 2003 US-led invasion of Iraq.

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive , Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed from 1977 until 2001 when it was acquired by RadiSys Corporation. During its time in operation, Microware was highly renowned for its OS-9 operating system, a highly versatile and efficient real-time operating system used primarily in embedded systems, data communication devices, and process control applications. In addition, Microware developed several peripheral devices and software packages, like compilers and network services that supported and extended the capabilities of its primary OS-9 offering.

Kazimierz Funk (; February 23, 1884 – November 19, 1967), commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was a Polish and American biochemist, generally credited with being among the first to formulate (in 1912) the concept of vitamins, which he called "vital amines" or "vitamines".AchievementsAfter reading an article by the Dutchman Christiaan Eijkman that indicated that persons who ate brown rice were less vulnerable to beri-beri than those who ate only the fully milled product, Funk tried to isolate the substance responsible, and he succeeded. Because that substance contained an amine group, he called it "vitamine".

J. Robert Oppenheimer ( ; April 22 , 1904 – February 18 , 1967 ) was an American theoretical physicist and academic who is best known as one of the key figures in the development of the atomic bomb during World War II. Born in New York City, Oppenheimer studied at Harvard University and then completed his PhD at the University of Göttingen, where he explored quantum mechanics. His role as the scientific director of the Manhattan Project led him to oversee the Los Alamos Laboratory, ultimately resulting in the construction of the first atomic bomb.

Events  January–March  January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets. The ban is lifted after three months. January 12 – Scottish minister James Renwick, one of the Covenanters resisting the Scottish government's suppression of alternate religious views, publishes the Declaration of Lanark. January 21 – The Ottoman Empire army is mobilized in preparation for a war against Austria that culminates with the 1683 Battle of Vienna. January 24 – The first public theater in Brussels, the Opéra du Quai au Foin, is opened.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy. Slapstick may involve both intentional violence and violence by mishap, often resulting from inept use of props such as saws and ladders. The term arises from a device developed for use in the broad, physical comedy style known as commedia dell'arte in 16th-century Italy. The "slap stick" consists of two thin slats of wood, which make a "slap" when striking another actor, with little force needed to make a loud—and comical—sound.

Panettone ( , ; ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan , usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas and New Year. This traditional delicacy features a fluffy, brioche-like dough infused with flavors of citrus, vanilla, and candied fruits. Other ingredients, such as raisins and chocolate, may also be incorporated into the mixture. To make the perfect Panettone, the dough undergoes a lengthy process of leavening, ensuring its characteristically airy texture. Upon baking, it rises into a cupola shape with a slightly crispy exterior.

Year 1329 ( MCCCXXIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year held several notable events that would have a lasting impact on the world. For example, on February 1st, Pope John XXII issues a Papal Bull, Quia quorundam, against the heresies and mystical theologies promoted by some within the church. Later, in the same year, a peace treaty between England and Scotland was concluded with the Treaty of Edinburgh-Northampton. Furthermore, the economic prosperity of Florence led to the founding of the famous Palazzo Vecchio, still an important cultural landmark in modern-day Italy.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( (Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov), , born on 27 July 1946) is a retired Kazakh Air Force officer and a former cosmonaut. He is the first person from Kazakhstan to go to space.Early lifeToktar Aubakirov was born in Karkaraly district, Karaganda region, Kazakh SSR, which is now Kazakhstan. After graduating from the 8th grade of a secondary school he started working as a metal turner at the Temirtau foundry, whilst attending an evening school. In 1965 he joined the Armavir Military Aviation Institute of the Anti-Air Defence Pilots.

Year 1023 (MXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  The Judge-Governor of Seville in Al-Andalus (modern Spain) takes advantage of the disintegration of the Caliphate of Córdoba and seizes power as Abbad I, founding the Abbadid dynasty. December – Abbad I declares the Taifa of Seville independent from Córdoban rule. Abd ar-Rahman V is proclaimed Caliph at Córdoba. Asia  April – An epidemic in Kyoto (Japan) is so severe that there are corpses in the streets; disease spreads throughout the country.

Year 1295 (MCCXCV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 20 – Pope Boniface VIII proposes the Treaty of Anagni, seeking to bring peace between the house of Anjou and Sicily; the effort is in vain. June 26 – Przemysł II is crowned King of Poland in Gniezno Cathedral, the first coronation of a Polish ruler in 219 years. October 23 – The first treaty forming the Auld Alliance, between Scotland and France against England, is signed in Paris.

The Asian Games , also known as Asiad , is a continental multi-sport event held every four years among athletes from all over Asia. The Games were first held in 1951 and have since grown in size and popularity, now featuring over 10,000 athletes from 45 countries. With numerous events spanning across multiple sports categories, such as aquatics, gymnastics, equestrian, and martial arts, the Asian Games showcase a unique combination of cultures and skills in a highly competitive atmosphere. It fosters solidarity among Asian nations, while inspiring athletes to represent their respective countries and push their physical and mental limits.

Events January – March January 7 – In India , Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had been opposing the Mughal rule, is captured and executed by the imperial forces under Kam Baksh, a younger son of Emperor Aurangzeb, further intensifying tensions between the local populace and Mughal Empire. February 17 – In Japan, an era of economic stability and cultural growth commences as Emperor Nakamikado abdicates and Emperor Sakuramachi ascends to the throne. March 6 – Sweden signs a treaty with France, effectively terminating their long-standing alliance with Great Britain, significantly impacting European diplomatic dynamics.

Year 1194 (MCXCIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  February 4 – King Richard I (the Lionheart) is ransomed for an amount of 150,000 marks (demanded by Emperor Henry VI), raised by his mother Eleanor of Aquitaine – who travels to Austria to gain his release. Henry will never receive the full amount he demanded. In March, Richard returns to England, and remains for only a few weeks before returning to the Continent.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation, probably via settlement from South America, through its colonization by the English in the early modern period, to the present day. Following a series of rebellions and a short-lived period as an independent republic during the 1960s, Anguilla has been a separate British overseas territory since 1980.Pre-Columbian AnguillaThe earliest inhabitants of Anguilla were Amerindian people from South America, commonly (if imprecisely) referred to as Arawaks. These people travelled to the island on rafts and in dugout canoes, settling in fishing, hunting and farming groups.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force, that existed from 1918 to 1964. It was under the political authority of the Secretary of State for Air.Organisations before the Air MinistryThe Air CommitteeOn 13 April 1912, less than two weeks after the creation of the Royal Flying Corps (which initially consisted of both a naval and a military wing), an Air Committee was established to act as an intermediary between the Admiralty and the War Office in matters relating to aviation.

Andorra, officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra<ref>Funk and Wagnalls Encyclopedia##, 1993</ref> , is a sovereign landlocked microstate in Southwestern Europe, located in the eastern Pyrenees mountains and bordered by Spain and France.9th to 19th centuriesAndorra claims it is the last independent survivor of the Marca Hispanica, the buffer states created by Charlemagne to keep the Islamic Moors from advancing into Christian France. Tradition holds that Charlemagne granted a charter to the Andorran people in return for their fighting the Moors.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive , rod-shaped , facultatively anaerobic , motile , beta-hemolytic , spore-forming bacterium commonly found in soil and vegetation, as well as various food products. This opportunistic pathogen is known to cause foodborne illnesses, mainly manifested through gastrointestinal disorders like nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramps, and diarrhea. Two types of toxins produced by B. cereus are responsible for these symptoms: emetic toxin that causes vomiting and diarrheal toxin that results in diarrhea. To prevent food poisoning caused by this bacterium, it is crucial to follow proper food handling and storage practices, including adequate cooking, refrigeration, and strict hygiene measures.

Events < onlyinclude > January–June January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed , establishing an alliance between Charles X of Sweden and Bogislaw XIV, Duke of Pomerania. This solidifies Sweden's influence in the Baltic region and paves the way for the upcoming conflict between Sweden and Poland. February 7 – Englishman John Donne is named Dean of St. Paul's Cathedral in London, elevating him to a significant position in the Church of England. April 12 – The Scottish Parliament authorizes King Charles I to unite Scotland and England under one banner, despite ongoing concerns about the weakening of Scottish identity and independence.

Year 1149 ( MCXLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1149 marked significant events in various regions of the world. In Europe, political turmoil prevailed as Conrad III, King of Germany and Holy Roman Emperor, left for the Crusades, leaving Germany under regency. Meanwhile, the power struggles continued in England between Empress Matilda and King Stephen over the crown. In the Levant, Christian forces endeavored to reclaim the Holy Land from the Muslim rule, leading to significant conflicts such as the disastrous Battle of Inab.

Major League Baseball (MLB) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the world. , a total of 30 teams play in Major League Baseball—15 teams in the National League (NL) and 15 in the American League (AL)—with 29 in the United States and 1 in Canada. The NL and AL were formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively. Beginning in 1903, the two leagues signed the National Agreement and cooperated but remained legally separate entities until 2000 when they merged into a single organization led by the Commissioner of Baseball.

The European bison ( Bison bonasus ) or the European wood bison , also known as the wisent ( or vice versa), is a majestic species that inhabits the dense forests and grasslands across parts of eastern and central Europe. Once on the brink of extinction, concerted conservation efforts have resulted in a remarkable resurgence for this captivating herbivore. Today, European bison populations can be found flourishing in protected areas like Bialowieza Forest in Poland and Belarus, providing not only a spectacular sight for nature enthusiasts but also valuable benefits to the ecosystems they call home.

Year 1024 (MXXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Basil II prepares a Byzantine expedition to invade Sicily. Governor Ahmed al-Akhal appeals to the Zirids of Ifriqiya for help. They dispatch a fleet, but these are caught up in a storm and destroyed near Pantelleria. Battle of Lemnos:  Kievan Viking raiders (800 men) sail through the straits at Abydos to the Aegean Sea. From there they make for the island of Lemnos, but are defeated by a Byzantine fleet of the Cibyrrhaeot Theme.

Year 1303 (MCCCIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 24 – Battle of Roslin: The Scots defeat the English. April 4 – Battle of Arques: The Flemings defeat the French. April 20 – Pope Boniface VIII founds the University of Rome La Sapienza. May 29 – The Treaty of Paris restores Gascony to the English. August 8 – 1303 Crete earthquake: An earthquake destroys the Lighthouse of Alexandria in Egypt, one of the seven wonders of the world.

Events March 18 – Jacques de Molay , the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar , is burned at the stake in Paris, ending a powerful era for the legendary order. His dramatic execution is ordered by Philip IV of France, who accused de Molay and the Knights Templar of various charges such as heresy, financial corruption, and blasphemy to weaken their influence and seize their wealth. The downfall of the Knights Templar leads to the rise of other military and religious orders across Europe, ultimately paving the way for centuries of power struggles, alliances, and transformations that shape the course of history.

Events January–March January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against the aggressive expansion of France, further strengthening their alliance and pooling military resources. This treaty comes at a time of great uncertainty in Europe, as King Louis XIV continues his quest for power, causing tensions and a push for security among smaller nations. February 5 – Tensions continue to escalate when the Duke of Brunswick launches a successful surprise attack against a Swedish garrison in Bremen. This event brings greater political instability to the region, with European leaders watching closely, as an ever-increasing concern for a possible domino effect surfaces.

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea , mainly occupied by the countries of Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Georgia. This region, home to a diverse array of ethnicities, languages, and religions, is characterized by a complex and tumultuous history. Situated at the intersection of Europe and Asia, it has played an important strategic role and has been contested among various powers, including the Persian, Ottoman, and Russian Empires. The Caucasus is also known for its natural beauty, featuring rugged mountain landscapes, rich ecosystems, and significant bio- and cultural diversity.

Year 1131 (MCXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  August 21 – King Baldwin II falls seriously ill, after his return from Antioch. He is moved to the patriarch's residence near the Holy Sepulchre, where he bequeaths the kingdom to his daughter Melisende, her husband Fulk and their infant son, Baldwin. He takes monastic vows, and dies soon after. Baldwin is buried in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, at Jerusalem.

Year 1136 ( MCXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In 1136, historical events took place that greatly shaped the medieval world. Alfonso I, the king of Aragon and Navarre, initiated military campaigns and successful battles in the Islamic region of Andalusia, capturing key strongholds including Peñaflor, Cuenca, and Mora. This earned him the nickname, "Alfonso the Battler". Elsewhere in Europe, tensions between England and Wales escalated, leading to Welsh rebellion led by King Owain Gwynedd, igniting wars that lasted for several decades.

Year 1292 (MCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  April 5 – The Papal election, 1292–94 begins. November – Michael II becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch. November 17 (Julian calendar) – John Balliol is selected by King Edward I of England as King of Scotland, from among 13 competitors for the Crown of Scotland; Edward then treats John as a puppet ruler and Scotland as a vassal state, eventually provoking the Wars of Scottish Independence, commencing in 1296.

Year 1186 ( MCLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, significant events unfolded across Europe and Asia. The Third Crusade saw the launch of Christian armies to reclaim the Holy Land following Saladin's capture of Jerusalem. Meanwhile, a peace treaty was signed between William of Scotland and Henry II of England, helping to solidify relations in the region. Farther east, the formation of the Khanate of the Golden Horde ushered in an era of stability in the Mongolian Empire.

Casimir IV (in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon;  ; Lithuanian: ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June 1492) was Grand Duke of Lithuania from 1440 and King of Poland from 1447, until his death. He was one of the most active Polish-Lithuanian rulers, under whom Poland, by defeating the Teutonic Knights in the Thirteen Years' War recovered Pomerania, and the Jagiellonian dynasty became one of the leading royal houses in Europe.The great triumph of his reign was bringing Prussia under Polish rule. The rule of Casimir corresponded to the age of "new monarchies" in western Europe.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 16 – Francesco Morosini, the Doge of Venice since 1688, dies after ruling the Republic for more than five years and a few months after an unsuccessful attempt to capture the island of Negropont from the Ottoman Empire during the Morean War. January 18 – Sir James Montgomery of Scotland, who had been arrested on January 11 for conspiracy to restore King James to the throne, escapes with the aid of the two persons guarding him and flees to France, arriving in Paris on February 15. January 21 (January 11 O.S.)

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating . In competitions , multiple skaters ( typically between four and six) race on an oval ice track measuring approximately 111 meters in length. This thrilling, fast-paced sport requires a combination of speed, strength, endurance, and precise technique for optimal performance. The races typically vary between 500 and 3,000 meters, testing both an athlete's agility and determination. Unlike long-track speed skating, where skaters race against the clock, in short-track, racers directly compete with each other, which often results in exciting and tactical races.

The European bison (Bison bonasus) or the European wood bison, also known as the wisent ( or ), or the zubr , or colloquially the European buffalo, is a European species of bison. It is one of two extant species of bison, alongside the American bison. The European bison is the heaviest wild land animal in Europe and individuals in the past may have been even larger than their modern-day descendants. During late antiquity and the Middle Ages, bison became extinct in much of Europe and Asia, surviving into the 20th century only in northern-central Europe and the northern Caucasus Mountains.

Year 1347 (MCCCXLVII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–December  January 26 – Charles University in Prague is founded by a bull issued by Pope Clement VI at the request of Charles I, King of Bohemia. February 2 – The Byzantine civil war of 1341–1347 between John VI Kantakouzenos and the regency for John V Palaiologos ends with Kantakouzenos entering Constantinople. April – The Knights Hospitaller defeat a Turkish fleet, and sink 100 ships off Imbros.

Year 1559 (MDLIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 15 – Elizabeth I of England is crowned, in Westminster Abbey. February 27 – Queen Elizabeth I of England establishes the Church of England, with the Act of Uniformity 1558 and the Act of Supremacy 1558. The Oath of Supremacy is reinstated. March 23 – Emperor Gelawdewos of Ethiopia, defending his lands against the invasion of Nur ibn Mujahid, Sultan of Harar, is killed in battle. His brother, Menas, succeeds him as king.

Poltava (, ;  ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine. It is the capital city of the Poltava Oblast (province) and of the surrounding Poltava Raion (district) of the oblast. Poltava is administratively incorporated as a city of oblast significance and does not belong to the raion. It has a population ofHistoryIt is still unknown when Poltava was founded, although the town was not attested before 1174. However, for reasons unknown, municipal authorities chose to celebrate the city's 1100th anniversary in 1999.

Vapor pressure (or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US; see spelling differences) or equilibrium vapor pressure is defined as the pressure exerted by a vapor in thermodynamic equilibrium with its condensed phases (solid or liquid) at a given temperature in a closed system. The equilibrium vapor pressure is an indication of a liquid's evaporation rate. It relates to the tendency of particles to escape from the liquid (or a solid). A substance with a high vapor pressure at normal temperatures is often referred to as volatile. The pressure exhibited by vapor present above a liquid surface is known as vapor pressure.

Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates , centered on a single point on the ice, while holding a specific body position. They can be performed individually or as part of a combination spin sequence, showcasing both the skater's flexibility and control. There are several types of spins, such as the upright, camel, and sit spins, each with its unique form and style. To increase their spin speed and intensity, skaters often incorporate variations and difficult features, like changes in position or edge.

Year 1020 (MXX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Summer – Emperor Henry II conducts his third Italian military campaign. He makes plans to invade the south, but remains non-commital. June 15 – Byzantine troops under Catepan Basil Boioannes (supported by his ally Prince Pandulf IV) capture the fortress of Troia. The French city of Saint-Germain-en-Laye is founded by King Robert II (the Pious). King Canute the Great codifies the laws of England (approximate date).

Events January–March January 11 – 1693 Sicily earthquake : Mount Etna erupts , causing a devastating earthquake that affects parts of eastern Sicily and Malta. This catastrophe leads to the death of over 60,000 people and significant destruction of towns and infrastructure, further emphasizing the unpredictability of natural disasters in the region. Survivors are forced to grapple with severe aftershocks and displacement as a result of the immense destruction. Local economies suffer from loss of infrastructure, agricultural disruption, and decreases in population, ultimately causing a shift in the socioeconomic and political landscape of affected areas throughout the year.

Year 1538 (MDXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June February 24 – Treaty of Nagyvárad: Peace is declared between Ferdinand I, future Holy Roman Emperor and the Ottoman Empire. John Zápolya is recognized as King of Hungary (Eastern Hungarian Kingdom), while Ferdinand retains the northern and western parts of the Kingdom, and is recognized as heir to the throne. April 26 – Battle of Las Salinas: Almagro is defeated by Francisco Pizarro, who then seizes Cusco.

Year 1136 (MCXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Raymond of Poitiers, son of the late Duke William IX of Aquitaine, arrives at Antioch. Patriarch Ralph of Domfront (against the wishes of Princess Alice) arranges a marriage in secret with her 8-year-old daughter Constance. She is kidnapped and taken to the cathedral in Antioch, where Ralph hastily marries her to Raymond. Alice leaves the city, now under the control of Raymond and Ralph, and retires to Latakia, Syria.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman . Set in the beautiful state of Hawaii, the show follows an elite team of detectives, known as the "Five-O" task force, as they investigate high-stakes criminal activities occurring on the islands. Led by the seasoned detective, Steve McGarrett (originally portrayed by Jack Lord and later by Alex O'Loughlin in the 2010 reboot), the task force takes on cases that involve terrorism, international intrigue, and even matters affecting national security.

Events  January–June  January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England. February – English pirates carry out the sack of Campeche in Mexico. March 4 – The Prince Edward Islands in the sub-antarctic Indian Ocean are discovered by Barent Barentszoon Lam, of the Dutch ship Maerseveen, and named Dina (Prince Edward) and Maerseveen (Marion). March 5 – Emperor Go-Sai's reign ends, and Emperor Reigen ascends to the throne of Japan. March 24 – King Charles II of England issues the Charter of Carolina, establishing the Province of Carolina, and dividing it between eight Lords Proprietors.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC. The Late Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East and eastern Mediterranean is often considered to begin in this century.Events 1200 BC: The first civilization in Central and North America develops in about 1200 BC in the coastal regions of the southern part of the Gulf of Mexico. Known as the Olmec civilization, its early site is at San Lorenzo. 1200 BC: The Phoenicians found the port of Lisbon, Portugal 1197 BC: The beginning of the first period (1197 BC – 982 BC) by Shao Yong's concept of the I Ching and history.

Year 1137 (MCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor John II (Komnenos) leads a Byzantine expeditionary force into Cilicia (the Byzantine fleet guards his flank). He defeats the Armenians under Prince Leo I ("Lord of the Mountains"), and captures the cities of Mersin, Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra. Leo retreats to the great fortifications of Anazarbus – where its garrison resists for 37 days. The Byzantine siege engines batter down its walls, and the city is forced to surrender.

Year 1236 ( MCCXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year was particularly significant for Europe as many events of historical importance occurred. During this year, Lithuania converted to Christianity under King Mindaugas. In the same vein, Ramon Berenguer IV, the Count of Provence, led a Crusade that successfully captured the Balearic Islands from the Moors. Furthermore, 1236 saw Ferdinand III of Castile retake Córdoba after more than 500 years of Muslim rule, marking a milestone in the ongoing Spanish Reconquista campaign.

.Year 1134 (MCXXXIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place Asia  Count Hugh II (du Puiset), in alliance with the Egyptian city of Ashkelon, revolts against King Fulk V of Jerusalem, attempting to take Jaffa. Hugh submits to Fulk and is exiled for three years. While awaiting for a boat to Italy he is attacked by a Breton knight, but survives the attempted murder. Hugh retires to the Sicilian court of his cousin, King Roger II, who appoints him with the lordship of Gargano, where he dies soon afterwards.

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election , held on Tuesday , November 8 , 1988. This election saw the contest between the incumbent Vice President George H. W. Bush of the Republican Party and Governor of Massachusetts, Michael Dukakis from the Democratic Party. The primary campaigns of both parties focused on various issues like arms control agreements, economic prosperity, and drug use during that era. Bush and his running mate, Dan Quayle, defeated Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen after an intense campaign, where Bush presented a strong continuation of Reagan-era policies.

OS-9 is a family of real-time, process-based, multitasking, multi-user operating systems, developed in the 1980s, originally by Microware Systems Corporation for the Motorola 6809 microprocessor. It was purchased by Radisys Corp in 2001, and was purchased again in 2013 by its current owner Microware LP.The OS-9 family was popular for general-purpose computing and remains in use in commercial embedded systems and amongst hobbyists. Today, OS-9 is a product name used by both a Motorola 68000-series machine language OS and a portable (PowerPC, x86, ARM, MIPS, SH4, etc.)

Year 1211 ( MCCXI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, numerous events took place, both significant and trivial, shaping history and the lives of many. In particular, the year marked significant advancements in the areas of culture, politics, religion, and war. It witnessed important developments such as the beginning of the reign of Malik Al-Adil, who became the King of Damascus after overthrowing his brother, Sultan Al-Adil I of Egypt.

The foreign relations of Albania are its relations with other governments and peoples . Foreign relations are conducted through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in close coordination with the President and Prime Minister of the country. The main objectives of Albania's foreign policy include maintaining and strengthening diplomatic ties, pursuing economic cooperation, and promoting national security interests. In recent years, Albania has pursued a path of closer integration with international institutions, especially NATO and the European Union, reflecting its ambition to become an active member of the global community. Additionally, the nation actively participates in regional initiatives and maintains diplomatic relationships with countries across the globe.

Year 1208 (MCCVIII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place  Asia  April 15 – A fire breaks out in the Song Chinese capital city of Hangzhou, raging for four days and nights, destroying 58,097 houses over an area of more than , killing 59 people, and an unrecorded number of other people, who are trampled while attempting to flee. The government provides temporary lodging for 5,345 people, in nearby Buddhist and Taoist monasteries. The collective victims of the disaster are given 160,000 strings of cash, along with 400 tons of rice.

Events January–June January–March – Archangelsk is founded as New Kholmogory in northern Russia , by Ivan the Terrible . January 21 – The Royal Exchange officially opens in London, serving as a center of commerce and trade. February 8 – Catherine de Medici introduces ballet in the Court of France during celebrations for a diplomatic treaty signing. March 14 – Construction begins on St. Augustine's Tower, the only remaining part of the original structure of the Great Hall and a recognizable landmark of Hackney today. April 28 – First recorded eruption of a volcano on the island of Sao Jorge, in the Azores archipelago.

The Commonwealth Games , often referred to as the Friendly Games , is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from the Commonwealth of Nations, a group of 54 member states that includes some of the most diverse and dynamic countries in the world. Held every four years since 1930, the Games foster unity, cultural exchange, and athletic excellence among participating countries. From the traditional competitions like track and field, swimming, and gymnastics, to newer events such as rugby sevens and beach volleyball, the Games showcase a wide variety of sports while promoting fair play, inclusion, and camaraderie among its competitors.

Wenceslaus IV (also Wenceslas; ; , nicknamed "the Idle"; 26 February 136116 August 1419), also known as Wenceslaus of Luxembourg, was King of Bohemia from 1378 until his death and King of Germany from 1376 until he was deposed in 1400. As  he belonged to the House of Luxembourg, he was also Duke of Luxembourg from 1383 to 1388.BiographyWenceslaus was born in the Imperial city of Nuremberg, the son of Emperor Charles IV by his third wife Anna von Schweidnitz, a scion of the Silesian Piasts, and baptized at St. Sebaldus Church.

Events  January–March  January 17 – Tuscarora War: Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County, North Carolina, in a second offensive against the Tuscarora. Heavy snows force the troops to take refuge in Fort Reading, on the Pamlico River. February 1 – Skirmish at Bender, Moldova: Charles XII of Sweden is defeated by the Ottoman Empire. February 4 – Tuscarora War: The Carolina militia under Colonel James Moore leaves Fort Reading, to continue the campaign against the Tuscarora. February 25 – Frederick William I of Prussia begins his reign.

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan , a former United States Representative from Nebraska , during the 1896 Democratic National Convention in Chicago. It is considered one of the most famous speeches in American political history, and was pivotal in securing Bryan the Democratic nomination for the presidential elections. The speech vehemently advocated for the free coinage of silver, reflecting Bryan's belief that allowing silver to be used as currency, alongside gold, would empower farmers and working-class people by leading to economic expansion and thus increased prosperity.

Operetta is a form of theatre and a genre of light opera. It includes spoken dialogue, songs, and dances. It is lighter than opera in terms of its music, orchestral size, length of the work, and at face value, subject matter. Apart from its shorter length, the operetta is usually of a light and amusing character. It sometimes also includes satirical commentaries. "Operetta" is the Italian diminutive of "opera" and was used originally to describe a shorter, perhaps less ambitious work than an opera. Operetta provides an alternative to operatic performances in an accessible form targeting a different audience.

Year 1140 (MCXL) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – King Fulk of Jerusalem confronts Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk ruler (atabeg) of Mosul, near Dara'a in southern Syria. Turkish forces under Mu'in al-Din (supported by the Crusaders) besiege Banias. Europe  Spring – King Conrad III enfeoffs Henry II (Jasomirgott), a member of the House of Babenberg, with the County Palatine of the Rhine (belonging to the Holy Roman Empire).

Year 1298 ( MCCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events of 1298 include the beginning of the Anglo-French War as France attempts to curb the expanding influence of the English king Edward I. The Battle of Falkirk takes place in July, marking a significant victory for the Scottish knight, William Wallace, over the English forces. Pope Boniface VIII begins centralizing the Papacy in Rome with the execution of prominent prelates opposing his policies. Venice establishes Europe's first known public bank, called Banco Giro, initiating modern-day banking practices.

Élie Ducommun ( 19 February 1833 , Geneva – 7 December 1906 , Bern ) was a Swiss peace activist and co-founder of the International Peace Bureau (IPB) who, together with fellow Swiss peace activist Charles Albert Gobat, received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1902. Born to a well-established Swiss family, he pursued careers in journalism, publishing, and education throughout his life. With a deep passion for peace advocacy, Ducommun used his position to raise awareness on issues related to disarmament and resolution of conflicts through negotiation. Through the IPB, he brought together organizations dedicated to global peace efforts, promoting dialogue and communication.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 5 – King Charles II of England gives the title Duke of St Albans to Charles Beauclerk, the illegitimate son of Charles and his mistress, Nell Gwyn. The title acknowledges the young man's noble heritage and strengthens his social standing. January 23 – Chinese Emperor Kangxi sets the newly implemented policy of sacrificing every Han to preserve Qing hegemony in Chinese territory. February 17 – Danish King Christian V issues the Code of Danish Law, compiling a consistent set of laws applicable to the whole nation, significantly strengthening his rule and streamlining administration.

Year 1363 (MCCCLXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 9 – Haakon VI of Norway marries Margaret I of Denmark. August – The Revolt of Saint Titus, against the rule of the Republic of Venice in the Kingdom of Candia (island of Crete), begins. August 30–October 4 – Battle of Lake Poyang: The Dahan rebel forces of Chen Youliang are defeated by the Red Turban Rebel forces of Zhu Yuanzhang, during the final decade of Yuan Dynasty control over China.

The Duchy of Anjou ( , ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire . Its capital was Angers, and it was bordered by the provinces of Maine to the north, Touraine to the east, and Poitou to the south. Anjou's history dates back to the early Middle Ages when it was part of the Carolingian Empire. Throughout its history, the Duchy underwent various changes in control, notably becoming part of the Angevin Empire during the 12th century. Anjou eventually fell under the rule of the Kingdom of France, with intermittent periods of English control, particularly during the Hundred Years' War.

Year 1171 ( MCLXXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events that year included the rebuilding of Saladin's army, laying the groundwork for further expansion and consolidation of his territories in the Levant. In Europe, strong tensions arose between the rulers of England and France, hinting at the prolonged hostilities that would emerge in the centuries to follow. Additionally, in Norway, the Þing alliance began, planting the seeds of local governance and conflict resolution that would later shape the country's political landscape.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray , which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Sedley amid their adventures in and around British high society during the early 19th century. While the book was initially published as a 19-volume monthly serial from 1847 to 1848, it eventually achieved critical acclaim as a complete work due to its memorable characters and satirical depiction of social climbing. Vanity Fair brilliantly exposes the flaws and corruption of Regency England, utilizing characters from diverse backgrounds. Ambitious anti-heroine Becky Sharp manipulates and outsmarts society's norms while kindhearted Amelia remains trapped within its boundaries.

The Hubble Space Telescope (often referred to as HST or Hubble) is a space telescope that was launched into low Earth orbit in 1990  and remains in operation. It was not the first space telescope, but it is one of the largest and most versatile, renowned both as a vital research tool and as a public relations boon for astronomy. The Hubble telescope is named after astronomer Edwin Hubble and is one of NASA's Great Observatories, along with the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory (1991–2000), the Chandra X-ray Observatory (1999–present), and the Spitzer Space Telescope (2003–2020).

Acetic acid bacteria ( AAB ) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid as the major end product. These bacteria are ubiquitous in nature, found in various environments such as soil, water, fruits, and food products like vinegar, kombucha, and sourdough. AAB are essential in industrial processes and biotechnological applications, including biofuel production, food fermentation, and bio-waste treatment. Although AAB provide many benefits, they can also cause spoilage of alcoholic beverages and fruit products due to the formation of undesirable acetic acid.

Events  March 18 – Jacques de Molay, the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar, is burned at the stake in Paris, France. April 4 – Exeter College, Oxford is founded in England by Walter de Stapledon, Bishop of Exeter. June 24 – Battle of Bannockburn: Scottish forces led by Robert the Bruce defeat Edward II of England, regaining Scotland's independence. August 31 – King Haakon V of Norway moves his capital from Bergen to Oslo, where he builds Akershus Fortress, from which Norway is ruled for the next 500 years.

Year 1420 ( MCDXX ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year saw significant developments in politics, architecture, and exploration. The Treaty of Troyes ended the conflict between England and France, bringing peace and creating an alliance. Construction on several major European landmarks, including the Ospedale degli Innocenti and Brunelleschi's Dome, began during this time. Exploration of new territories expanded as Portuguese navigators started exploring the Atlantic islands, heralding a period of discoveries and overseas expansion. Overall, 1420 marked substantial progress in Europe's culture, innovation, and diplomacy.

Year 1390 (MCCCXC) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – The Treaty of Lyck confirms an alliance between Vytautas and the Teutonic Knights, in the Lithuanian Civil War against Vytautas's cousin, Jogaila. April 14 – John VII Palaiologos overthrows his grandfather, John V Palaiologos, as Byzantine Emperor. April 19 – Robert III succeeds his father, Robert II, as King of Scotland. May 26 – Lithuanian Civil War: The Treaty of Königsberg is signed in Königsberg, between Samogitian nobles and representatives of the Teutonic Knights.

Peter Halsten Thorkelson ( February 13 , 1942 – February 21 , 2019 ) , known professionally as Peter Tork , was an American musician and actor, best known as the keyboardist and bass guitarist of the Monkees, a popular rock band during the 1960s. Born in Washington D.C., Tork initially worked as a folk musician and even performed with other prominent acts of his time like Stephen Stills. In 1966, Tork rose to stardom after joining the Monkees for their debut TV show. He soon gained immense popularity among fans for his fun-loving personality and talented performances, resulting in a lasting legacy and influence in pop culture.

Jacques René Chirac (, , ; 29 November 193226 September 2019) was a French politician who served as President of France from 1995 to 2007. Chirac was previously Prime Minister of France from 1974 to 1976 and from 1986 to 1988, as well as Mayor of Paris from 1977 to 1995.After attending the École nationale d'administration, Chirac began his career as a high-level civil servant, entering politics shortly thereafter. Chirac occupied various senior positions, including Minister of Agriculture and Minister of the Interior. In 1981 and 1988, he unsuccessfully ran for President as the standard-bearer for the conservative Gaullist party Rally for the Republic.

Year 1151 (MCLI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  September 7 – Geoffrey of Anjou dies, and is succeeded by his son Henry, aged 18. After the Battle of Ghazni, the city is burned by the Prince of Ghur. The first plague and fire insurance policy is issued in Iceland. Bolton Abbey is founded in North Yorkshire, England. Anping Bridge is completed in China's Fujian province. Its total length will not be exceeded until 1846.

Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov ( ; – 10 March 1940 ) was a Russian writer , medical doctor , and playwright active during the first half of the 20th century. He is best known for his novel "The Master and Margarita," a masterpiece of the 20th-century literature, combining elements of fantasy, political satire, and philosophical discussion. Bulgakov began his career as a physician, but shifted focus to literature due to his passion for writing. He produced multiple plays, such as "Days of the Turbins" and "The Fatal Eggs," touching on themes like revolution, ethics, and morality.

Events January–June January 24 – King Charles II of England dissolves the `` Cavalier Parliament '' , after nearly 18 years in session, marking the end of an era in British political history. February 2 – James II of England, also known as the Duke of York, founds the city of Albany, New York, expanding English influence in the New World. March 18 – James Scott, Duke of Monmouth, illegitimate son of Charles II, lands in Scotland in an attempt to claim the throne, beginning the Monmouth Rebellion. May 12 – Pope Innocent XI excommunicates French King Louis XIV, escalating religious tensions in Europe.

Major League Baseball ( MLB ) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the United States and Canada. Founded in 1903, the MLB currently consists of 30 teams divided into two leagues, the American League and the National League, each featuring 15 teams. Each year, teams compete through a regular season, culminating in the playoffs and ultimately, the World Series, where the best teams from each league face-off to become the world champions of baseball. MLB is renowned globally for showcasing exceptional talent and generating a passion for the game that captivates fans from diverse backgrounds.

Year 1354 (MCCCLIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  Early in the year – Ibn Battuta returns from his travels at the command of Abu Inan Faris, sultan of Morocco, who appoints a scribe to write an account of the adventures. February 12 –  The Treaty of Stralsund settles border disputes between the duchies of Mecklenburg and Pomerania. March 2 –  The Gallipoli earthquake occurs, followed within a month by Turkish capture and settlement (see Fall of Gallipoli).

Year 1213 (MCCXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  May 15 – King John of England submits to Pope Innocent III, who in turn lifts the interdict of 1208. May 30 – Battle of Damme: The English fleet under William Longespée, 3rd Earl of Salisbury, destroys a French fleet off the Belgian port in the first major victory for the fledgling Royal Navy. September 12 – Battle of Muret: The Toulousain and Aragonese forces of Raymond VI of Toulouse and Peter II of Aragon are defeated by the Albigensian Crusade, under Simon de Montfort.

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov ( ; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974 ) was a Soviet general and Marshal of the Soviet Union, often regarded as one of the greatest military leaders in history. Throughout his career, he successfully commanded troops in some of the most crucial battles of World War II, including the Battle of Moscow, the Battle of Stalingrad, and the Siege of Leningrad. After the war, he held various prestigious posts, serving as Defense Minister, a member of the Central Committee of the Communist Party, and a key military advisor to Soviet leaders such as Joseph Stalin and Nikita Khrushchev.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago. Formerly one of the "Big Five" accounting firms (along with PricewaterhouseCoopers, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, Ernst & Young, and KPMG), the company had provided auditing, tax and consulting services to large corporations. By 2001, it had become one of the world's largest multinational corporations.In 2002, the firm voluntarily surrendered its licenses to practice as Certified Public Accountants in the United States after it was found guilty of crimes in the firm's auditing of Enron, an energy corporation based in Texas, which had filed for bankruptcy in 2001.

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC (c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka). It is impossible to precisely date events around this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis. Towards the end of this millennium, the islands of Great Britain and Ireland were severed from continental Europe by rising seawater.CommunitiesPopulationNeolithic culture and technology were established in the Near East by 7000 BC and there is increasing evidence through the millennium of its spread or introduction to Europe and the Far East.

Solidarity Electoral Action ( , AWS ) was a political coalition in Poland . Since 1997 , its official name has been Akcja Wyborcza Solidarność (Solidarity Electoral Action). Formed in 1996 as a response to Poland's political and economic issues, the coalition brought together several conservative political parties and organizations. AWS secured a significant victory in the 1997 parliamentary elections and subsequently established a coalition government with the Freedom Union (UW). Led by Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek, the government focused on EU integration, constitutional reform, and economic development.

Year 1515 ( MDXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1515 (MDXV), a number of significant events took place in politics, science, and art, marking it as a historically important year. Major developments were seen across Europe, as dynasties changed hands and explorers sought new territories. It was also an era of artistic progression during the peak of the Italian Renaissance. Leaders like King Louis XII of France and Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor, ruled during a time when the great Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo Buonarroti created some of their most celebrated works.

In probability theory, the central limit theorem (CLT) establishes that, in many situations, when independent random variables are summed up, their properly normalized sum tends toward a normal distribution (informally a bell curve) even if the original variables themselves are not normally distributed. The theorem is a key concept in probability theory because it implies that probabilistic and statistical methods that work for normal distributions can be applicable to many problems involving other types of distributions. This theorem has seen many changes during the formal development of probability theory.

Year 1237 (MCCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – Emperor Frederick II assembles an expeditionary force (some 15,000 men) to crush the rebellious Lombard League. He crosses the Alps to Verona – where he is joined by Lord Ezzelino III da Romano, including troops from Brescia, Vicenza, Padua, and Treviso. Frederick relies on his allies for support, and in doing so he provokes the opposition of earlier supporters, such as the House of Este, who now sides with the Lombards.

Year 1429 ( MCDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1429, significant historical events unfolded as various nations faced momentous challenges and welcomed transformative changes. Joan of Arc, a young French peasant girl, came into prominence by lifting the siege of Orléans in May, turning the tide in favor of France during the Hundred Years' War. Later that year, she would witness Charles VII being crowned as the King of France at the Cathedral of Reims. Meanwhile, Cosimo de' Medici gained political prominence in Florence, shaping the early years of the powerful Medici dynasty.

Events  January–March  January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company, of the German state of Brandenburg, signs a greaty with representatives of the Ahanta tribe in what is now Ghana to establish the fort and settlement of Groß Friedrichsburg in honor of Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. The location is later renamed Princes Town, also called Pokesu. January 6 – The tragic opera Phaëton, written by Jean-Baptiste Lully and Philippe Quinault, is premiered at the Palace of Versailles. January 27 – Gove's Rebellion breaks out in the Province of New Hampshire in North America as a revolt against the Royal Governor, Edward Cranfield.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 1 – The Abenaki tribe and the Massachusetts colonists sign a treaty, ending the conflict in New England. January 4 – The Palace of Whitehall in London, England is destroyed by fire. January 23 – George Louis (who in 1714 will become King George I of Great Britain) becomes Elector of Hanover upon the death of his father, Ernest Augustus. Because the widow of Ernest Augustus, George's mother Sophia, was heiress presumptive as the cousin of Anne, Queen of Great Britain, and Anne's closest eligible heir, George will become King of Great Britain.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling (; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994) was a Swedish actress, novelist and film director.Early lifeZetterling was born in Västerås, Sweden to a working class family. She started her career as an actress at the age of 17 at Dramaten, the Swedish national theatre, appearing in war-era films.CareerZetterling appeared in film and television productions spanning six decades from the 1940s to the 1990s. Her breakthrough came in the 1944 film Torment written by Ingmar Bergman, in which she played a controversial role as a tormented shopgirl.

Year 1301 (MCCCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 14 – The death of Andrew III of Hungary ends the Árpád Dynasty in Hungary, resulting in a power struggle between Wenceslaus III of Bohemia, Otto III, Duke of Bavaria, and Charles Robert of Naples. February 7 – Edward of Caernarvon (later King Edward II of England) becomes the first Prince of Wales. March 3 – Emperor Go-Nijō succeeds Emperor Go-Fushimi on the throne of Japan.

Year 1464 (MCDLXIV) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+50(L)+10(X)+(-1(I)+5(V)) = 1464).Events  January–December  April 25 – Battle of Hedgeley Moor in England: Yorkist forces under John Neville defeat the Lancastrians under Sir Ralph Percy, who is killed.

Peter Halsten Thorkelson (February 13, 1942 – February 21, 2019), known professionally as Peter Tork, was an American musician, composer, and actor who was best known as the keyboardist and bass guitarist of the Monkees and a co-star of the TV series The Monkees (1966–1968).Tork grew up in Connecticut and in the mid-1960s as part of the Greenwich Village folk scene in New York City, he befriended musician Stephen Stills. After moving to Los Angeles with Stills, he was recruited for the musical television sitcom The Monkees. The success of the show made him a teen idol from 1966 to 1968.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence ( August 8 , 1901 – August 27 , 1958 ) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and inventor, who was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his development of the cyclotron, an essential tool for atomic research. Through this groundbreaking invention, Lawrence made crucial discoveries regarding nuclear reactions and energy, paving the way for both peaceful and military applications of nuclear technology. He later founded the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, which became key players in the development of the U.S. atomic energy and defense programs.

Year 1132 (MCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Summer – Imad al-Din Zengi, Seljuk governor (atabeg) of Aleppo and Mosul, marches on Baghdad (the capital of the Abbasid Caliphate) to add it to his dominions. He is defeated by the forces of Caliph Al-Mustarshid near Tikrit (modern Iraq). Zengi flees and escapes with help of Tikrit's governor Najm ad-Din Ayyub (the father of Saladin) who conveys him across the River Tigris.

Dari (, , ), or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of the Persian language spoken in Afghanistan. Dari is the term officially recognised and promoted since 1964 by the Afghan government for the Persian language, hence it is known as Afghan Persian or Eastern Persian in many Western sources. As Professor Nile Green remarks "the impulses behind renaming of Afghan Persian as Dari were more nationalistic than linguistic" in order to create an Afghan state narrative. Persian in Afghanistan is generally called Fārsi (فارسی) by Persian-speakers and Pārsi (پارسی) by ethnic Pashtuns.

In mathematics, two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common. Equivalently, two disjoint sets are sets whose intersection is the empty set. For example, {1, 2, 3} and {4, 5, 6} are disjoint sets, while {1, 2, 3} and {3, 4, 5} are not disjoint. A collection of more than two sets is called disjoint if any two distinct sets of the collection are disjoint.GeneralizationsThis definition of disjoint sets can be extended to a family of sets : the family is pairwise disjoint, or mutually disjoint if  whenever .

Year 1377 (MCCCLXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Battle of Đồ Bàn: Trần Duệ Tông, Trần dynasty Emperor of Đại Việt (Vietnam), is killed. January 17 – Pope Gregory XI moves the Papacy back from Avignon to Rome. January 27 – The Bad Parliament begins sitting in England. Influenced by John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster, it undoes the work done by the Good Parliament, the previous year, to reduce corruption in the Royal Council.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state's military forces. The governor has a duty to enforce state laws, the power to either approve or veto bills passed by the Montana State Legislature, to convene the legislature at any time, and to grant pardons and reprieves.The current Montana Constitution, ratified in 1972, calls for a 4-year term for the governor, commencing on the first Monday in January following an election. The governor is term-limited to 8 years in any 16-year period. The constitution provides for the election of a lieutenant governor for the same term as the governor.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy, authority or control within the Internet. Domain names are used in various networking contexts and for application-specific naming and addressing purposes. In general, a domain name identifies a network domain, or it represents an Internet Protocol (IP) resource, such as a personal computer used to access the Internet, a server computer hosting a website, or the web site itself or any other service communicated via the Internet. As of 2017, 330.6 million domain names had been registered.Domain names are formed by the rules and procedures of the Domain Name System (DNS).

A killer is someone or something that kills , such as a murderer or a serial killer . Killer or The Killer may also refer to an entity, like an animal or disease, that has the capability to take lives. It's important to understand the motive or the root cause behind the actions of a killer, as this can range from survival instincts to mental illness or a deeply rooted personal trauma. Society often grapples with how to handle these killers; our moral compass directs us towards punishing and deterring future offenses while attempting to address underlying factors to create a safer community for all.

Events  January–June  January 1 Colonel George Monck (with his regiment) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Coldstream, and begins his advance towards London in support of the English Restoration. Samuel Pepys begins his diary. February 3 – George Monck and his regiment arrive in London. February 13 – Charles XI becomes king of Sweden at the age of five, upon the death of his father, Charles X Gustavus. February 27 – John Thurloe is reinstated as England's Secretary of State, having been deprived of his offices late in the previous year. March 16 – The Long Parliament disbands.

The Stoned Guest is a "half-act opera" by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Bach. The title is a play on the "stone guest" character in Don Giovanni by Mozart, as well as the opera The Stone Guest by Alexander Sergeyevich Dargomïzhsky after the play by Pushkin. The work is a parody of classical opera, although some critics consider it to be the equal of many classical works in technical ability. The opera appears on the 1970 album of the same name.The loose story combines elements of Don Giovanni with elements of Carmen by Georges Bizet.

Prince Igor is an opera in four acts with a prologue , written and composed by Alexander Borodin . The composer based the story on the 12th-century epic, "The Lay of Igor's Campaign", which tells of Prince Igor Svyatoslavich's efforts to defeat the invading Polovtsians. Set in the medieval period, the opera chronicles Igor's misfortunes, from his disastrous battle against the nomadic tribe to his eventual capture, and eventual escape. Along the way, love, passion, and redemption arise, intertwined with memorable choral, instrumental, and solo vocal works, creating a Russian national masterpiece.

Year 1396 ( MCCCXCVI ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1396 (MCCCXCVI), several notable events shaped the political and cultural landscape across the globe. While some countries embraced new beginnings with new rulers, others saw their people engage in conflicts that would redefine their national trajectories. As political alliances shifted and major battles marked turning points in world history, a number of historical landmarks were also established during this time, shedding light on the important occurrences of this period.

Year 1343 (MCCCXLIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 14 – Arnošt of Pardubice becomes the last bishop of Prague and, subsequently, the first Archbishop of Prague. January 27 – Pope Clement VI issues his bull Unigenitus, defining the doctrine of "The Treasury of Merits" or "The Treasury of the Church" as the basis for the issuance of indulgences by the Catholic Church. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising begins in Estonia.

Year 1406 (MCDVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 4 – James I becomes King of Scotland, after having been captured by Henry IV of England. October 7 – French troops comprising 1,000 men at arms land on Jersey, and fight a battle against 3,000 defenders. October 13 – Richard Whittington is elected Lord Mayor of London for a second full term. He holds this office simultaneously, with that of Mayor of the Calais Staple. October 26 – Eric of Pomerania marries Philippa, daughter of Henry IV of England.

Year 1527 (MDXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June January 1 – Croatian nobles elect Ferdinand I of Austria as King of Croatia in the Parliament on Cetin. January 5 – Felix Manz, co-founder of the Swiss Anabaptists, is drowned in the Limmat in Zürich by the Zürich Reformed state church. March 17 – Battle of Khanwa: Babur defeats Rajput ruler Rana Sanga. This and two other major Moghul victories lead to their domination of northern India. Dhaulpur fort is taken by Babur.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene , outsider , wild human , an "other" who has not been "corrupted" by civilization, and therefore symbolizes humanity's innate goodness. Existing as a romanticized ideal, the noble savage signifies an individual untainted by the vices and complexities that come with modern society, exemplifying simpler, virtuous values often linked to life in nature. Writers such as Jean-Jacques Rousseau praised this ideal as they criticized aspects of modern society like inequality, selfishness and insincerity, yearning for an existence of purity, freedom, and morality embodied by the noble savage.

Year 1239 ( MCCXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a year marked by notable events and changes in political and social landscapes. Europe was in the throes of political turmoil, as kingdoms vied for power and territory. This year was significant due to several notable births, marriages, and deaths that would shape history in the decades to come. At the same time, scientific advancements continued as scholars and theologians from all around the known world engaged in debates and discourses in the hallowed halls of universities, shaping human progress during the Middle Ages.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating , such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy is moving away from us increases over time. This acceleration is believed to be driven by dark energy, a mysterious force that counteracts gravity and pushes galaxies apart. Consequently, the distance between galaxies is constantly growing, causing the universe to expand at an ever-increasing rate. Scientists believe that this process may lead to the eventual dispersion of galaxy clusters and a "Big Freeze," as stars become unable to form from a lack of raw materials.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage ( born 9 July 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two gold medals and one silver medal at the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City. Throughout his successful career, he set several world records in various events including the 5,000-meter and 10,000-meter races. Uytdehaage became known for his elegant skating style and endurance, earning admiration from both his peers and fans around the world. After retiring from professional sports in 2007, Uytdehaage transitioned to a career in motivational speaking and sports consultancy, sharing his passion for athletics and promoting health and wellness.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC. It was a period of great change for several civilizations. In Africa, Carthage is founded by the Phoenicians. In Egypt, a severe flood covers the floor of Luxor temple, and years later, a civil war starts.It is the beginning of the Iron Age in Central Europe, with the spread of the Proto-Celtic Hallstatt culture, and the Proto-Celtic language.Events890s BC  899 BC: The first year of King Yih of Zhou's reign is marked by a solar eclipse.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago . Formerly one of the `` Big Five '' accounting firms, it provided auditing, tax, and consulting services to large corporations worldwide. Established in 1913, the company thrived and was once renowned for its prestige, professionalism, and rigorous adherence to ethical standards. However, the 2001 Enron scandal caused a rapid decline in the company's credibility and customer base. Accused of accounting fraud and document tampering, Arthur Andersen was convicted in a high-profile trial, ultimately leading to its dissolution in 2002.
