Skeptics, however, dismissed the event as another attempt to manipulate the public. Either way, Sunday was to be a day to remember – one of pivotal change and unforeseen revelation.

Year 1366 ( MCCCLXVI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, several significant events occurred in various regions across Europe and Asia. The year marked the beginning of construction of The Basilica di Santa Maria del Fiore, now known as the Florence Cathedral, in Italy. In Europe, the Battle of Gąsawa between Teutonic Knights and various Polish allies escalated. Meanwhile, in China, Zhu Yuanzhang, a peasant who would later establish the Ming Dynasty, started leading rebellions against the declining Yuan Dynasty.

Business is the activity of making one's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (such as goods and services). Simply put, it is "any activity or enterprise entered into for profit. "Having a business name does not separate the business entity from the owner, which means that the owner of the business is responsible and liable for debts incurred by the business. If the business acquires debts, the creditors can go after the owner's personal possessions. A business structure does not allow for corporate tax rates.

The Witan, literally "wise men", was the king's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the seventh century until the 11th century. It was composed of the leading magnates, both ecclesiastic and secular, and meetings of the council were sometimes called the Witenagemot. Its primary function was to advise the king on subjects such as promulgation of laws, judicial judgments, approval of charters transferring land, settlement of disputes, election of archbishops and bishops and other matters of major national importance. The witan also had to elect and approve the appointment of a new king.

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov (; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974) was a Soviet general and Marshal of the Soviet Union. He also served as Chief of the General Staff, Minister of Defence, and was a member of the Presidium of the Communist Party (later Politburo). During the Second World War, Zhukov oversaw some of the Red Army's most decisive victories.Born to a poor peasant family from central Russia, Zhukov was conscripted into the Imperial Russian Army and fought in the First World War. He served in the Red Army during the Russian Civil War.

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus  of the family Pinaceae. Pinus is the sole genus in the subfamily Pinoideae. The Plant List compiled by the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew and Missouri Botanical Garden accepts 126 species names of pines as current, together with 35 unresolved species and many more synonyms. The American Conifer Society (ACS) and the Royal Horticultural Society accept 121 species. Pine may also refer to the lumber derived from pine trees; pine is one of the more extensively used types of wood used as lumber.

Events January–March January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company , of the German state of Brandenburg , signs a greaty with the native Kpengla dynasty, obtaining a trading monopoly and establishing a fortress on the African Gold Coast. This marks the beginning of Germany's involvement in the Atlantic slave trade. January 19 – William III of England joins the League of Augsburg against France. February 4 – The Great Storm hits Devon and Somerset, causing flooding, property damage, and an estimated 15,000 deaths. February 12 – Treaty of Limerick is signed between Irish noblemen and the new government.

The Zwinger is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden , Germany . Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann , it was constructed between 1710 and 1728 as an orangery and exhibition gallery for Augustus the Strong, the ruler of Saxony at the time. The name Zwinger refers to its location between two outer walls, symbolizing a border region. Today, the complex hosts multiple museums, including the renowned Gemäldegalerie Alte Meister, a painting gallery showcasing works from renowned artists such as Raphael, Rembrandt, and Rubens. It is also home to the Mathematisch-Physikalischer Salon and the Porzellansammlung, making the Zwinger a major cultural attraction in Dresden.

The African clawed frog ( Xenopus laevis , also known as the xenopus , African clawed toad , African claw-toed frog or the platanna) is an aquatic species native to sub-Saharan Africa. Its characteristic features include its fully webbed hind feet, slippery skin, and vestigial claws. These frogs are incredibly adaptive, which is one of the reasons they have been so widely spread around the globe through accidental introductions via the pet trade, research and ornamental purposes. In the wild, African clawed frogs inhabit ponds, rivers, and streams, feeding on small fish, insects, and invertebrates.

Year 1236 (MCCXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – A fleet consisting of ships from the republics of Venice, Genoa and Pisa arrive at Constantinople. It is headed by Geoffrey II of Villehardouin, ruler of Achaea, who brings 100 of his own knights, 300 cross-bowman, and 500 archers. Geoffrey, formally a vassal of Emperor John I of Constantinople, breaks the blockade of the city, sinks 15 Byzantine ships and enters the Golden Horn.

Events  January–June  January 18 – François, Duke of Anjou, attacks Antwerp. February 4 – Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg, newly converted to Calvinism, formally marries Agnes von Mansfeld-Eisleben, a former canoness of Gerresheim, while retaining his position as Archbishop-Elector of Cologne. March 10 – The Queen Elizabeth's Men troupe of actors is ordered to be founded in England. May – Battle of Shizugatake in Japan: Shibata Katsuie is defeated by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, who goes on to commence construction of Osaka Castle. May 22 – Ernest of Bavaria is elected as Roman Catholic Archbishop of Cologne, in opposition to Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg.

Events January–June January 22 – Impostor Mary Carleton is hanged at Newgate Prison in London , for multiple thefts and bigamy. February 3 – A severe frost begins in England, lasting until mid-April, causing widespread disruption of water supply and transportation. March 14 – Battle of Kühnhausen: Sweden and France defeat Denmark and Norway, asserting dominance over Northern Europe. April 11 – Anglo-Spanish War intensifies with Spain laying siege on British-controlled Gibraltar. May 19 – New York Governor, Sir Edmund Andros, sets aside Manhattan for religious tolerance, paving the way for religious diversity in America.

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine ( sometimes referred to as St. John 's and also nicknamed St. John the Unfinished) is located in New York City and is considered one of the world's largest and most renowned Episcopal cathedrals. This architectural masterpiece showcases an eclectic mix of architectural styles, ranging from Romanesque to Gothic Revival, providing an awe-inspiring ambience for visitors and worshippers alike. Over the years, the Cathedral has been a cornerstone for community life and advocacy, featuring music and arts programs, interfaith dialogues, and social services outreach initiatives.

The term chat room, or chatroom (and sometimes group chat; abbreviated as GC), is primarily used to describe any form of synchronous conferencing, occasionally even asynchronous conferencing. The term can thus mean any technology ranging from real-time online chat and online interaction with strangers (e.g., online forums) to fully immersive graphical social environments.The primary use of a chat room is to share information via text with a group of other users. Generally speaking, the ability to converse with multiple people in the same conversation differentiates chat rooms from instant messaging programs, which are more typically designed for one-to-one communication.

The Witan , literally `` wise men '' , was the king 's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the 9th century to the 11th century. It was composed of religious leaders, important noblemen, and other key figures in society. The Witan advised the king on matters of governance, law, and policy, as well as aiding in diplomacy with foreign nations. Additionally, the Witan played a role in selecting successors to the throne. The group's influence in decision-making gradually waned after the Norman Conquest of 1066, as King William I centralised power and implemented a feudal system that eventually evolved into the parliament of modern England.

Lazzi ( ; from the Italian lazzo , a joke or witticism ) are stock comedic routines that are associated with the traditional Italian comic theater genre known as Commedia dell'Arte. Dating back to the 16th century, these theatrical sketches incorporate physical humor, satirical commentary, and quick-witted banter as central elements of their performances. Frequently involving exaggerations, gags, and often bawdy elements, Lazzi provide not only an entertaining distraction but also a tool for comic actors to develop unique and memorable characters. Nowadays, Lazzi influence can be observed in contemporary comedy genres, particularly in slapstick, stand-up, and sketch comedy.

Events  January–June  January 24 – King Charles II of England dissolves the "Cavalier Parliament", after nearly 18 years. February 3 – Moroccan troops from Fez are killed, along with their commander Moussa ben Ahmed ben Youssef, in a battle against rebels in the Jbel Saghro mountain range, but Moroccan Sultan Ismail Ibn Sharif is able to negotiate a ceasefire allowing his remaining troops safe passage back home. February 5 – The Treaty of Celle is signed between France and Sweden on one side, and the Holy Roman Empire, at the town of Celle in Saxony (now in Germany).

Events January–June January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas : The Portuguese beat the Spaniards in a critical engagement, further consolidating their independence. February 17 – Members of England's Long Parliament submit the Eikon Basilike, a manifesto supposedly authored by King Charles I, asserting the divine right of kings. March 30 – Sikh leader Guru Har Rai establishes his successor, Har Krishan, as the eighth Sikh Guru. May 7 – Anglo-Spanish War: War declared between England and Spain, impacting international trade and further tensions.

Mariner-H ( Mariner Mars '71 ) , also commonly known as Mariner 8 , was ( along with Mariner 9 ) part of NASA's Mariner Mars Project, which aimed to conduct in-depth investigations of the Martian surface and atmosphere. Launched in May 1971, Mariner 8 faced unfortunate technical malfunctions that prevented it from completing its mission objectives, including failing to reach Mars' orbit. In contrast, Mariner 9 succeeded in its endeavor, becoming the first spacecraft to orbit Mars and subsequently provide critical information and images of the planet's surface.

Year 1366 (MCCCLXVI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  March 13 – Henry II deposes his half-brother, Pedro of Castile, to become King of Castile. October 12 – Frederick III of Sicily forbids decorations on synagogues. October 26 – Comet 55P/Tempel–Tuttle passes  from Earth.Date unknown  Thomas Fraser obtains lands in Aberdeenshire, upon which he starts the building of a towerhouse, that will later be known as Muchalls Castle. Muhammed V builds the Granada Hospital in Granada (in present-day Spain).

Year 1435 ( MCDXXXV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, numerous significant events shaped the world's history. In Europe, the French continued their military campaign in the Hundred Years War, leading to the capture of many English strongholds in France. Meanwhile, the Treaty of Arras sought to reconcile differences between Charles VII and Duke Philip of Burgundy. In Portugal, Lisbon's Saint Vicente de Fora church was founded, while Pope Eugenius IV dissolved the Council of Basel, marking a critical shift in papal politics.

William Makepeace Thackeray ( ; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863 ) was a British novelist , author and illustrator, best known for his satirical works portraying the intricacies and shortcomings of early 19th century society. He achieved prominence for his classic novel Vanity Fair, often considered as one of the masterpieces of English literature, alongside other works like The Luck of Barry Lyndon and Pendennis. Born in India, Thackeray spent most of his life in England, where he contributed to the burgeoning literary scene, first as a journalist before turning to full-time writing.

Maximilian II ( 31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death Maximilian II was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death on October 12, 1576. He was born on July 31, 1527, as the eldest son of Emperor Ferdinand I and Anne of Bohemia and Hungary. Maximilian's reign saw attempts to bring about religious peace in the empire, particularly by pushing for more tolerance towards Protestants in order to ease the religious tension stemming from the Reformation. Though these efforts initially had some success, their effects ultimately diminished due to growing radicalism within both Catholic and Protestant camps.

The Stoned Guest is a `` half-act opera '' by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Bach. This parody of Mozart's opera Don Giovanni and various other classic opera styles was first performed in 1970, featuring a nonsensical plot, unconventional musical arrangements, and intentionally absurd staging. Set in Madrid, the story revolves around a wily aristocrat who impersonates a notorious phantom outlaw in order to satisfy his appetite for mischief and court the eccentric and unsuspecting Baroness of Lostonda. Alongside Don Octave, several zany characters create laughter as they dance, disguise themselves, and ponder their peculiar destinies.

Events January–June January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan , known as the Ratio Studiorum , is issued . March 11 – The Peace of Madrid is signed, ending the war between France and Spain. April 17 – A powerful eruption of Mount Etna devastates Catania and other settlements in Sicily, leaving many inhabitants homeless. May 6 – British astronomer Jeremiah Horrocks observes the transit of Venus across the Sun's face, greatly contributing to our understanding of planetary movements. June 8 – Thirty Years' War: The Battle of Nördlingen begins, ultimately leading to a significant victory for the Catholic forces and influencing the course of European religious conflicts.

Year 1455 ( MCDLV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1455 (MCDLV), which began on a Wednesday, significant global events shaped the course of history. Europe, in particular, witnessed major shifts in political, religious, and cultural dynamics. The Hundred Years War between France and England saw the Battle of Castillon leading to French victory and England's loss of power in France. Additionally, the first-ever printing press developed by Johannes Gutenberg greatly enhanced the dissemination of ideas, thus contributing to the intellectual, spiritual, and social growth of Western societies.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description , understanding and prediction of natural phenomena , based on empirical evidence and experimentation. It is an umbrella term encompassing fields such as physics, chemistry, biology, earth science, astronomy, and ecology, among others. Natural scientists apply the scientific method to study the fundamental principles and mechanisms that govern the natural world, thus unveiling its diverse intricacies. These investigations pave the way for valuable insights and advances, ranging from improved disease treatments, technological innovations, strategies to address climate change, and an enhanced understanding of our universe.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe. It was published by Sierra from 1987 to 2009, then by Codemasters starting in 2009. The first six Leisure Suit Larry titles, along with Magna Cum Laude and Love for Sail Mobile, were distributed by Vivendi Games (now Activision Blizzard), while Box Office Bust and Reloaded were distributed by Codemasters. Currently the games are being published and distributed by Assemble Entertainment.The games follow Larry Laffer, a balding, double entendre-speaking, leisure suit-wearing man in his 40s. The stories generally revolve around his attempting, usually unsuccessfully, to seduce attractive young women.

Events January–June January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought . January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath , the Eastern Church of St. Thomas Christians in India split into factions, leading to the formation of the indigenous Malankara Church. January 26 – Francis Drake, an English sea captain, completes his circumnavigation of the Earth and is knighted by Queen Elizabeth I. March 17 – Dutch explorer Dirk Hartog sets foot on Western Australian soil for the first time. May 28 – The Counter-Reformation is confirmed at the Papal Curia through the Fifth Session of the Council of Trent.

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic , waterways and railroads . All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil and gas pipelines are regulated by the Ministry of Transportation of Azerbaijan Republic. In recent years, the country has significantly invested in developing its infrastructure to support various means of transportation, both in terms of public transport and freight traffic. The country's road network has been rapidly expanding, linking all major cities and neighboring countries. In addition to public buses and minibuses, Azerbaijan has a fast-growing metro system in Baku, its capital city.

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday, February 29. By adding a second leap day (Friday, February 30) Sweden reverted to the Julian calendar and the rest of the year (from Saturday, March 1) was in sync with the Julian calendar. Sweden finally made the switch from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar in 1753. This year has 367 days.Events  January–March  January 8 – Total eclipse of the sun visible from  January 12 – The premiere of the opera Idoménée by André Campra takes place at the Théâtre du Palais-Royal in Paris.

Year 1362 (MCCCLXII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Grand Duchy of Lithuania switches New Year to January 1, before any other country does. January 16 – The "Grote Mandrenke" storm tide strikes the Netherlands, England, Germany and Denmark, destroying the Danish settlement of Rungholt in the Duchy of Schleswig, and the Humber estuary port of Ravenser Odd in England. The East Frisian island of Buise is broken into two by North Sea floods.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, United States, and is located halfway between the "tip" and "elbow" of Cape Cod. The town had a population of 3,566 at the 2020 census, which swells nearly sixfold during the summer. A total of 70% of the town's land area is under protection, and nearly half of it is part of the Cape Cod National Seashore. Wellfleet is famous for its oysters, which are celebrated in the annual October Wellfleet OysterFest.History The area was originally settled by Europeans in the 1650s as Billingsgate (after the famous fish market in East London).

Broca 's area , or the Broca area ( , also , ) , is a region in the frontal lobe of the brain that plays a vital role in the production of speech and language. It is named after Pierre Paul Broca, a French physician and anthropologist, who discovered its significance in 1861 after examining patients with speech impairments. This area is located in the posterior part of the frontal lobe, near the lateral sulcus, which separates it from the parietal lobe. Its precise function includes controlling the facial movements necessary for articulation, as well as contributing to language comprehension and processing.

Year 1185 (MCLXXXV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August – King William II (the Good) lands in Epirus with a Siculo-Norman expeditionary force of 200 ships and 80,000 men (including 5,000 knights), and marches as far as the Byzantine city of Thessalonica, which he takes and pillages (massacring some 7,000 Greek citizens). September 11–12 – Isaac II (Angelos) leads a revolt in Constantinople and deposes Emperor Andronikos I (Komnenos).

In physics , quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy , more precisely a scalar field , postulated as an explanation for the observation of an accelerating rate of the expansion of the universe. The concept of quintessence arises from the desire to understand the nature of dark energy and to develop an accurate cosmological model. It differs from the more commonly-accepted model of dark energy – the cosmological constant – by being dynamic and able to evolve with the universe. Its dynamic nature would provide a richer variety of phenomena for understanding cosmic acceleration and offering possible clues to further our knowledge of the cosmos.

Year 1579 (MDLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Monday of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 6  – The Union of Arras unites the southern Netherlands under the Duke of Parma, governor in the name of king Philip II of Spain. January 23 –  The Union of Utrecht unites the northern Netherlands in a confederation called the United Provinces. William I of Orange becomes Stadtholder, and the Duc d'Anjou, younger brother of Henry III of France, is invited to become hereditary sovereign.

Year 1559 ( MDLIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked the beginning of significant events that unfolded over the year. As a pivotal moment in European history, Protestantism strengthened its foothold with the coronation of England's Elizabeth I on January 15, creating new political and religious alliances across the continent. Meanwhile, the French Wars of Religion initiated and tensions continued to brew between Catholics and Protestants. In scientific advances, Galileo Galilei's groundbreaking treatise De Revolutionibus became a topic of discourse, revolutionizing the study of planetary motion in the European scientific community.

Louis I , also Louis the Great ( ; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian ( ; 5 March 132610 September 1382), was King of Hungary and Croatia from 1342 to 1382, as well as King of Poland from 1370 to 1382. He was a member of the House of Anjou, and his remarkable accomplishments earned him the title of "Great." His rule marked an era of prosperity and progress in Central Europe, largely due to his excellent diplomatic skills and decisive military campaigns. Despite challenges from several dukes and outside invasions, Louis managed to significantly expand his domain, modernizing the infrastructure and stabilizing the region politically.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Tuesday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–March  January 12 – Parts of the Netherlands adopt the Gregorian calendar. January 18 – The electorate of Brandenburg-Prussia becomes the Kingdom of Prussia, as Elector Frederick III is proclaimed King Frederick I.  Prussia remains part of the Holy Roman Empire. It consists of Brandenburg, Pomerania and East Prussia. Berlin is the capital. January 28 – The Chinese storm Dartsedo. February 17 (February 6, 1700 O.S.) – The 5th Parliament of King William III is assembled.

Year 1317 ( MCCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, history witnessed significant events across Europe and the Far East. In Ireland, the Bruce invasion continued as Scotland's Edward Bruce declared himself High King of the country. England, crippled by widespread famine, endured its worst winter in decades, further exacerbating the challenges for the royal government. In France, the Hospitaller and the Teutonic Order waged relentless battles. Further east, the Kheraites tribes migrated, influencing the events of Mongol Empire and Central Asian history.

Year 1404 (MCDIV) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April or May – Battle of Blackpool Sands: Local English forces defeat an attempted raid from Saint-Malo on the port of Dartmouth, Devon; the French commander, William du Chastel, is killed. June 14 – Rebel leader Owain Glyndŵr, having declared himself Prince of Wales, allies with the French against the English. He later begins holding parliamentary assemblies. October 17 – Pope Innocent VII succeeds Pope Boniface IX, as the 204th pope.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy . Slapstick comedy can often include pratfalls, clumsy actions, and ludicrous situations that provoke laughter in the audience. This genre of humor can be traced back to the ancient Roman and Greek theater and was heavily influenced by commedia dell'arte in the Italian Renaissance. Slapstick became even more popular with the introduction of silent films, where comedians like Charlie Chaplin, Buster Keaton, and Laurel and Hardy excelled in conveying humorous situations through actions and exaggerated facial expressions alone.

is the Latin name under which the `` Lamb of God '' is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other liturgical rites of the Christian church. "Agnus Dei" translates to "Lamb of God" and refers to Jesus Christ as the sacrificial lamb, signifying his ultimate act of love and redemption through his crucifixion. It is also a part of the Latin liturgical chants sung or recited during various rituals and ceremonies. The use of the Agnus Dei symbolizes the strong belief in Jesus as the Savior of humanity, and by uttering these words, Christians worldwide commemorate and celebrate the sacrifice that he made on behalf of all.

Year 1502 (MDII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 1 – Portuguese explorers, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sail into Guanabara Bay, Brazil, mistaking it for the mouth of a river, which they name Rio de Janeiro. February 12 – Isabella I issues an edict outlawing Islam in the Crown of Castile, forcing virtually all her Muslim subjects to convert to Christianity. May 3 – Portuguese navigator João da Nova discovers the uninhabited island of Saint Helena.

Year 996 ( CMXCVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, various noteworthy events took place throughout the world. In Asia, Emperor Taizu of Song inaugurated the Song Dynasty in China after defeating the powerful Northern Han. Japan witnessed the formal recognition of Kyoto's Kitano Tenmangu Shrine. In Europe, King Otto III celebrated his silver wedding with Theophanu in Rome and funded a range of new buildings and projects, contributing significantly to Europe's architectural heritage.

Year 1373 ( MCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, many important events took place in Europe and Asia, greatly shaping the world we know today. Some of these events include the consolidation of power for kingdoms such as Portugal and Lithuania, as well as the spread of influence of the Ottoman Empire in the east. There were significant military conflicts involving various European countries and these regional wars, skirmishes and conquests played a major role in transforming alliances, solidifying boundaries and laying foundations for future nation states.

Year 1171 (MCLXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 12 – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) orders the arrest of all Venetians in his empire, and seizes their ships and goods. In September, Doge Vitale II Michiel leads a Venetian fleet (120 ships) against the Byzantines, conquering the cities of Trogir and Dubrovnik. But the plague takes a heavy toll among the fleet's crewmen; half the ships have to be burned to keep them from falling into enemy hands.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga , which are separated geographically by the Murray River and politically by the state border between New South Wales and Victoria. This thriving metropolitan area, strategically located between Sydney, Melbourne, and Canberra, has a combined population of over 90,000 residents. Known for its natural beauty, diverse culture, and friendly community, Albury-Wodonga is considered one of the top inland growth areas in Australia. Boasting rich cultural events, renowned recreational facilities, and promising future development projects, it serves as a major regional center for commerce, transport, health, education, and government.

Year 1406 ( MCDVI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, numerous significant events occurred worldwide, forever altering the course of history. From Europe, where political rivalries and conflicts escalated, to Asia, with Chinese achievements marking a golden era, 1406 was filled with moments that demonstrated human brilliance, struggle, and an undeniable pursuit of progress. Through complex power struggles and developing technologies, this common year bore witness to civilizations further advancing as they laid foundations that would impact the world for centuries to come.

Élie Ducommun (19 February 1833, Geneva – 7 December 1906, Bern) was a Swiss peace activist. He was a Nobel laureate, awarded the 1902 Nobel Peace Prize, which he shared with Charles Albert Gobat.Born in Geneva, he worked as a tutor, language teacher, journalist and a translator for the Swiss federal Chancellery (1869–1873).In 1867 he helped to found the Ligue de la paix et de la liberté (League of Peace and Freedom), though he continued working at other positions, including secretary for the Jura-Simplon Steel Company from 1873 to 1891.

Year 1201 ( MCCI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this time, the world saw several significant events, particularly in Europe and Asia. The Crusader states in the Holy Land experienced turbulent political shifts, with both alliances and battles dominating the landscape. In Asia, the Song Dynasty, and later the Yuan Dynasty, ruled large parts of China. Alongside, the empire of Genghis Khan also began its expansive rise, which would come to influence European politics in future years.

Year 1250 ( MCCL ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1250 (MCCL), several significant events occurred across different regions of the world, particularly in Europe, Asia, and Africa. Major political changes unfolded, as rulers and kingdoms fought for dominance and territories, influencing trade, alliances, and power dynamics across these continents. Some well-known battles also took place, profoundly impacting the course of history for years to come. Meanwhile, innovations and discoveries flourished during this period, contributing significantly to advancements in culture, religion, and sciences.

Year 1439 ( MCDXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This particular year was significant as it witnessed notable advancements in Europe and Asia. In Europe, the technology of moveable type was invented by Johannes Gutenberg, leading to the revolutionizing of communication methods and an increase in literacy rates. Meanwhile, in Asia, the Jurchen tribes began the unification process under Nurhaci, which would eventually result in the emergence of the powerful Manchu state, setting the stage for the later Qing Dynasty in China.

Year 1413 ( MCDXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year was significant for a variety of political and cultural events, such as the ascension of Henry V to the English throne after his father King Henry IV's death. Meanwhile, in Asia, the Chinese Ming Dynasty conducted successful naval raids under Admiral Zheng He, expanding their influence over Southeast Asia. Europe was in the throes of artistic growth during the Renaissance period, with famous sculptor Donatello producing numerous outstanding works during this year, significantly impacting the history of art.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence (August 8, 1901 – August 27, 1958) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and winner of the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his invention of the cyclotron. He is known for his work on uranium-isotope separation for the Manhattan Project, as well as for founding the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.A graduate of the University of South Dakota and University of Minnesota, Lawrence obtained a PhD in physics at Yale in 1925. In 1928, he was hired as an associate professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley, becoming the youngest full professor there two years later.

Year 1429 (MCDXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 12 – Battle of Rouvray (or "of the Herrings"): English forces under Sir John Fastolf defend a supply convoy, which is carrying rations (food) to the army of William de la Pole, 4th Earl of Suffolk at Orléans, from attack by the Comte de Clermont and John Stewart. April 29 – Siege of Orléans: Joan of Arc enters Orléans with a relief expedition. May 7 – The Tourelles, the last English siege fortification at Orléans, falls.

Year 1370 (MCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 9 – Timur becomes first Amir of the Timurid Empire, following the Siege of Balkh which establishes his rule over the Chagatai Khanate, completing his conquest of Central Asia and parts of Persia. May 24 – The Treaty of Stralsund ends the war between Denmark and the Hanseatic League. September 19 – Hundred Years' War: Siege of Limoges – The English led by Edward the Black Prince retake the city from the French by storm with wide destruction, effectively ending the Limoges enamel industry.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold, Suffolk, England, by George and Ernest Adnams. It produces cask ale and pasteurised bottled beers. Annual production is around 85,000 barrels.In 2010, the company established the Copper House distillery for the production of gin, vodka and whisky.HistoryThe earliest recorded brewing on the Adnams site was in 1396 by Johanna de Corby.The Sole Bay Brewery in Southwold was purchased in 1872 by George and Ernest Adnams. The company was incorporated in 1890, and has remained independent since then, producing a range of beers for distribution mainly in East Anglia.

Edmund of Abingdon ( also known as Edmund Rich , St Edmund of Canterbury , Edmund of Pontigny , French Saint Édouard d'Abingdon, or Edme d'Abingdon) was an English-born prelate and scholar, serving as the Archbishop of Canterbury between 1233 and 1240. Known for his intelligence and devotion, Edmund sought to enforce religious discipline among the clergy and laity alike, though he was met with resistance from those who prioritized political motives. As conflict increased, Edmund retired to the Cistercian monastery at Pontigny, France, where he would devote the remainder of his life to prayer and contemplation.

Year 1472 (MCDLXXII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 20 – Orkney and Shetland are returned by Norway to Scotland, as a result of a defaulted dowry payment. December 31 – The city council of Amsterdam prohibits snowball fights: "Neymant en moet met sneecluyten werpen nocht maecht noch wijf noch manspersoon." ("No one shall throw with snowballs, neither men nor (unmarried) women.") Date unknown  The first printed edition of Dante Alighieri's Divine Comedy is published in Foligno.

Acetic acid bacteria (AAB) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid during fermentation. The acetic acid bacteria consist of 10 genera in the family Acetobacteraceae. Several species of acetic acid bacteria are used in industry for production of certain foods and chemicals.DescriptionAll acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes. Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature. They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars. They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.

Year 1449 ( MCDXLIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked a year of significant events in Europe and Asia. In France, the Hundred Years War had briefly come to an end after the decisive French victory at Castillon, paving the way for peace with England. Elsewhere in Europe, tensions continued between the Kingdom of Poland and Teutonic Knights, leading to the 13 Years War in the coming decade. Meanwhile, the Portuguese explored the African continent, unveiling new trade opportunities while navigating through previously uncharted territory.

OS-9 is a family of real-time , process-based , multitasking , multi-user operating systems , developed in the 1980s , originally by Microware Systems Corporation and later acquired by RadiSys Corporation. OS-9 was designed for microprocessor systems, focusing primarily on embedded systems and industrial control applications. Due to its modularity and adaptable components, OS-9 became popular across a variety of industries, including aerospace, telecommunications, and automation. The operating system provides advanced features, such as memory protection and efficient scheduling algorithms, which ensure stability, reliability, and reduced downtime.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces . The basic goal of algebraic topology is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, which are functions that preserve topological properties. Examples of such invariants include homology groups, cohomology groups, and fundamental groups, which provide a simplified representation of a space while capturing essential features of its structure. Algebraic topology has applications in various areas of mathematics, including analysis, geometry, and knot theory, as well as physics and engineering, particularly in data analysis, computational methods, and optimization.

Roger Williams (21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683) was a Puritan minister, theologian, and author who founded Providence Plantations, which became the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations and later the U.S. State of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations, now the State of Rhode Island. He was a staunch advocate for religious freedom, separation of church and state, and fair dealings with Native Americans.Williams was expelled by the Puritan leaders from the Massachusetts Bay Colony and established Providence Plantations in 1636 as a refuge offering what he termed "liberty of conscience."

Year 1433 ( MCDXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, significant events occurred that greatly influenced the course of world history. Notably, Europe's cultural and political landscape was rapidly evolving, with important breakthroughs in exploration and art. For instance, under the aegis of Portugal's Prince Henry the Navigator, the voyages of the Azores commenced. Moreover, celebrated Flemish artist Jan van Eyck created his renowned "Arnolfini Wedding" painting, which stood as a symbol of burgeoning prosperity and burgeoning trade relationships in Northern Europe.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County , in the U.S. state of Vermont . The population was 3,612 at the 2020 census, showing a slight increase from 2010. The picturesque town is located along the Connecticut River and offers various outdoor recreational activities. Norwich has maintained its historic New England charm, featuring quaint homes, tree-lined streets, and numerous small shops, restaurants, and local businesses. Its local residents have a strong sense of community and pride in the town's top-rated schools, cultural offerings, and historic architecture. As a result, Norwich remains a peaceful and family-friendly haven within Vermont.

Year 1150 (MCL) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Battle of Tara: The Byzantines defeat the Serbian-Hungarian army under Grdeša, count (župan) of Travunija, near the snow-covered Tara River. The Serbs are overpowered, and Grand Prince Uroš II is forced to accept the peace agreement made by Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos). Uroš is succeeded by his brother Desa, who  becomes co-ruler of the Principality of Serbia (until 1153).

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack , such as in a sail line or mooring line. This knot is easily adjustable and can be quickly untied when no longer needed. It works well in various conditions, whether at sea, in camping, or for general purposes around the house. To create a shank, start by finding the midpoint of the rope or section that you want to shorten. Fold the rope to create a bight and take the working ends of the rope to either side of the loop, effectively forming an overhand loop knot.

Year 1570 ( MDLXX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1570 saw numerous significant events, including geopolitical changes, technological advancements, and cultural shifts. In Europe, Queen Elizabeth I's reign oversaw religious transformations, with tensions rising between Catholics and Protestants. Also, Ivan IV expanded Russia's territories, founding several cities like Tula, Rzhev, and Zavidovo. In Asia, Japan saw the rise of powerful feudal lords Oda Nobunaga and Tokugawa Ieyasu.

Year 1301 ( MCCCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Telerius and Sabinus (or, less frequently, year 1054 Ab urbe condita). The dominant event during 1301 was the spread of Catholicism, as well as the Crusader kingdoms in the Eastern Mediterranean, further influencing politics in Europe and Asia. In this year, significant territorial and dynastic disputes emerged, laying the groundwork for subsequent religious and secular power struggles in the following centuries.

In geometry, two figures or objects are congruent if they have the same shape and size, or if one has the same shape and size as the mirror image of the other.More formally, two sets of  points are called congruent if, and only if, one can be transformed into the other by an isometry, i.e., a combination of rigid motions, namely a translation, a rotation, and a reflection. This means that either object can be repositioned and reflected (but not resized) so as to coincide precisely with the other object.

Johan August Arfwedson ( 12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841 ) was a Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium in 1817, while analyzing the mineral petalite. Born in Skagerhult, Arfwedson studied mineralogy and chemistry under the renowned chemist Jöns Jakob Berzelius. With his guidance, Arfwedson's breakthrough would greatly influence future research and applications in medicine, batteries, and the nuclear industry. Sadly, Arfwedson was unable to isolate lithium in its pure elemental form due to limitations in scientific processes available at that time. This was later achieved in 1821 by William Thomas Brande using electrolysis.

Year 1509 ( MDIX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Notable events that took place during this year included Henry VII of England's passing, resulting in Henry VIII taking over the throne, as well as Portugal expanding its exploration and navigation reach towards India, helping them solidify trade routes. Various religious establishments, like Oxford and Leipzig universities, embarked on reforms and structures that would guide and refine European intellectual discourse during the 16th century. A significant Renaissance period in cultural history, the year 1509 represented shifting powers, achievements, and pursuits.

Year 1524 (MDXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 17 – Florentine explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano, on board La Dauphine in the service of Francis I of France, sets out from Madeira for the New World, to seek out a western sea route to the Pacific Ocean. March – Spanish conquistador Pedro de Alvarado destroys the Kʼicheʼ kingdom of Qʼumarkaj, taking the capital, Quiché. March 1 (approximate date) – da Verrazzano's expedition makes landfall at Cape Fear.

Palermo ( , ;  , locally also  or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy, the capital of both the autonomous region of Sicily and the Metropolitan City of Palermo, the city's surrounding metropolitan province. The city is noted for its history, culture, architecture and gastronomy, playing an important role throughout much of its existence; it is over 2,700 years old. Palermo is in the northwest of the island of Sicily, by the Gulf of Palermo in the Tyrrhenian Sea.The city was founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as  ("flower").

Events  January–June  January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy, the millones. March – Maurice of Nassau, Prince of Orange, takes Breda, by concealing 68 of his best men in a peat-boat, to get through the impregnable defences. March 14 – Battle of Ivry: Henry IV of France again defeats the forces of the Catholic League, under Charles, Duke of Mayenne. May–August – Henry IV of France unsuccessfully attempts to besiege Paris. Henry is forced to raise the siege, when Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma comes to its rescue with a Spanish army.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics ( LASP ) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics (LASP) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. Founded in 1948, LASP focuses on studying Earth's atmosphere, solar interactions, planetary atmospheres and surfaces, and space weather phenomena. This esteemed institution strives to increase our understanding of our planet and the cosmos, fostering collaboration among experts in various scientific disciplines. Committed to education, LASP promotes professional training in atmospheric and space sciences by mentoring young professionals and hosting outreach activities.

Year 1442 ( MCDXLII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, several important events occurred throughout the world. The island of Sao Tome, off the coast of West Africa, was discovered by Portuguese navigators exploring new maritime routes. Europe saw the Treaty of Toledo signed by King Alfonso V of Portugal and King Juan II of Castile, agreeing on the dominions and alliances between the two kingdoms. Meanwhile, Korea began cultivating crops using modernized agricultural systems under King Sejo's regime, influencing their agricultural productivity for centuries to come.

Uracil  (symbol U or Ura) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are represented by the letters A, G, C and U. The others are adenine (A), cytosine (C), and guanine (G). In RNA, uracil binds to adenine via two hydrogen bonds. In DNA, the uracil nucleobase is replaced by thymine. Uracil is a demethylated form of thymine.Uracil is a common and naturally occurring pyrimidine derivative. The name "uracil" was coined in 1885 by the German chemist Robert Behrend, who was attempting to synthesize derivatives of uric acid.

Year 1290 (MCCXC) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Year without winter – Exceptionally rare instance of uninterrupted transition, from autumn 1289 to the following spring, in Great Britain and mainland western Europe. March 1 – The University of Coimbra is founded in Lisbon, Portugal by King Denis of Portugal; it moves to Coimbra in 1308. July 10 – Ladislaus IV of Hungary is assassinated by three Cumans (Árbóc, Törtel and Kemence), at the castle of Körösszeg (modern-day Cheresig) in Romania.

Year 1552 ( MDLII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, significant events unfolded in various parts of the world, including Europe, Asia, and America. The Treaty of Passau, a major milestone during the European Reformation, was signed by Protestant and Catholic factions in August, paving the way for religious peace in Germany. Meanwhile, Ivan the Terrible began his expansionist campaign in Asia, marking Russia's ambitious pursuit of lands and wealth in the east.

Year 1235 (MCCXXXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Connacht in Ireland is finally conquered by the Hiberno-Norman Richard Mór de Burgh; Felim Ua Conchobair is expelled. A general inquisition begins in France. The Byzantine emperor John III Doukas Vatatzes and the Bulgarian tsar Ivan Asen II besiege Constantinople, in an attempt to take it from its Latin rulers, John of Brienne and Baldwin II. Angelo Sanudo successfully negotiates a two-year truce. Elizabeth of Hungary (d. 1231) is canonized, by Pope Gregory IX.

As of March 1 (O.S. February 19), where then Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the Gregorian calendar did not, the Julian calendar fell one day further behind, bringing the difference to 11 days until February 28 (O.S. February 17), 1800.In Sweden, the year started in the Julian calendar and remained so until February 28. Then, by skipping the leap day, the Swedish calendar was introduced, letting February 28 be followed by March 1, giving the entire year the same pattern as a common year starting on Monday.

Year 1175 (MCLXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  King Henry II begins living openly with his mistress Rosamund Clifford, raising suspicions about their relationship and alienating Henry's wife, Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Eleanor of Aquitaine is held under house arrest at Old Sarum Castle in Wiltshire. She is kept in comfort there – fine clothes for her are dispatched regularly from London. Treaty of Windsor: High King Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair (or Roderic O'Conner) relinquishes his title and agrees to submit to Henry II as vassal of Connacht in Ireland.

Jan Bos (born 29 March 1975) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist. In the late 1990s he was world champion in speed skating and he competed in the 1998 and 2002 Winter Olympics.Speed skaterIn 1998 Bos both became the world champion sprint and won the silver medal that year in the 1000 meter sprint during the Winter Olympics in Nagano. He won the silver medal on that same distance in Salt Lake City.He competed at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens in the team sprint track cycling event, together with his brother Theo Bos, who won the silver at the individual sprint, and Teun Mulder.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in October 2013. Originating in the Gulf of Mexico, the storm merged with a cold front, amplifying its intensity before moving up the eastern seaboard. In its wake, Karen left a trail of devastation, with widespread flooding and landslides destroying numerous homes and displacing thousands of residents. Emergency management teams from various states coordinated with federal agencies for swift relief efforts. Sadly, numerous fatalities were recorded due to flood-related accidents, and several communities took months to recover from the significant economic impacts.

Sigismund of Luxembourg ( 15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437 ) was a monarch who reigned as king of Hungary, Croatia, and Bohemia, and Holy Roman Emperor for four years, marking him as one of the most influential European rulers in the Late Middle Ages. Known for his exceptional diplomatic skills, Sigismund managed to navigate complex political situations by bridging disputes among various regions, sects, and people in the quest for peace and stability. As a strong patron of the arts, Sigismund further contributed to the thriving culture in Eastern and Central Europe during his time.

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae . Bamboos are unique in their quick growth rate and extensive versatility, native to a wide range of habitats including tropical, subtropical, and temperate regions across East Asia, the Americas, and Africa. There are more than 1,400 species varying in size, ranging from small shrubs to giant timber species. They play vital ecological and economical roles in areas where they're found. Bamboos hold multiple applications, such as being used as building materials, culinary resources, and ornamental purposes.

Year 1524 ( MDXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked a year of significant global events, exploration and discoveries. On April 17th, Giovanni da Verrazzano reached present-day New York Harbor, setting the stage for the establishment of the region in the following decades. The famous Mixton War also took place in 1524 between indigenous people and Spaniards in New Granada, causing widespread destruction and eventually leading to major territorial changes. While cultures continued to interact through trade and war, Europe, Asia and the New World experienced great innovations and transformations shaping history forever.

Ross Powers ( born February 10 , 1979 ) is an American world champion halfpipe snowboarder from South Londonderry , Vermont. Growing up on the slopes of Stratton Mountain, Powers quickly gained recognition as a prodigy in snowboarding. In his illustrious career, he has clinched three medals in the Winter X Games, which includes two gold medals and one silver. His extraordinary performances also propelled him to win a gold medal at the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City and a bronze at the 1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, making him a prominent figure in the snowboarding community.

Year 1037 ( MXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events from this year included the death of renowned Persian polymath Ibn Sina, also known as Avicenna, whose work contributed to advancements in several fields such as medicine, astronomy, and mathematics. In politics, King Canute the Great of Denmark passed away, causing a struggle for power amongst his successors. Tensions continued to escalate between Byzantine Empire and the Muslim nations, particularly with the loss of a critical battle against the Seljuk Turks near Aleppo.

1581 (MDLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) in the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Thursday (link will display full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  March 18 – The Parliament of England's Act against Reconciliation to Rome imposes heavy fines, for practising Roman Catholicism. March 25 – Iberian Union: Philip II of Spain is crowned Philip I of Portugal. April 4 – Following his circumnavigation of the world, Francis Drake is knighted by Elizabeth I of England. July–December  July 14 – English Jesuit Edmund Campion is arrested.

Year 996 (CMXCVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  February - Chotoku Incident: Fujiwara no Korechika and Takaie shoot an arrow at Retired Emperor Kazan 2 March: Emperor Ichijo orders the imperial police to raid Korechika’s residence - Empress Teishi (sister of Korechika) cuts her hair because of the humiliation - Takaie is arrested, Korechika is absent  5 March: Korechika returns with his head shaven and attired as a monk Europe  Spring – King Otto III starts his first expedition to Italy from Regensburg, and proceeds over the Brenner Pass.

Events  January–March  January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York, Maine, United States, are killed in the Candlemas Massacre, carried out by French soldiers led by missionary Louis-Pierre Thury, along with a larger force of Abenaki and Penobscot Indians under the command of Penobscot Chief Madockawando during King William's War, between the French colonists and their indigenous allies, against the English colonists. At least 112 English survivors are captured and taken from the Maine District of the  Province of Massachusetts Bay and forced to walk to French Canada, where they are held until Massachusetts captain John Alden pays a ransom.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls of fortifications or splinter their wooden gates. In its simplest form, a battering ram is just a large, heavy log carried by several people and propelled with force against an obstacle; the ram would be sufficient to damage the target if the log were massive enough and/or it were moved quickly enough (that is, if it had enough momentum). Later rams encased the log in an arrow-proof, fire-resistant canopy mounted on wheels. Inside the canopy, the log was swung from suspensory chains or ropes.

Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed, establishing an alliance between Charles X Gustav of Sweden and Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. January 24 – The first Jewish doctor in the Thirteen Colonies of America, Jacob Lumbrozo, arrives in Maryland. April 1 – Lwów Oath: John II Casimir Vasa, King of Poland, crowns the Black Madonna of Częstochowa as Queen and Protector of Poland in the cathedral of Lwów, after the miraculous saving of the Jasna Góra Monastery during the Deluge, an event which changed the course of the Second Northern War.

Year 1212 (MCCXII) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   England  July 10 – The Great Fire: The most severe of several early fires of London burns most of the city to the ground; over 3,000 people die, many of them by drowning in the River Thames. According to a contemporary account: "An awful fire broke out on the Southwark side of London Bridge; while it was raging, a fire broke out at the other end also and so hemmed in the numerous crowds who had assembled to help the distressed.

Year 1567 (MDLXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January – A Spanish force under the command of Captain Juan Pardo establishes Fort San Juan, in the Native American settlement of Joara. The fort is the first European settlement in present-day North Carolina. January 20 – Battle of Rio de Janeiro: Portuguese forces under the command of Estácio de Sá definitively drive the French out of Rio de Janeiro. January 23 – After 45 years' reign, the Jiajing Emperor dies in the Forbidden City of China.

In mathematics , two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common . Equivalently , disjoint sets are sets whose intersection is the empty set, denoted by ∅. In simple terms, they do not overlap or share any common members. Disjoint sets play a crucial role in various mathematical operations and theorems, including the calculation of probabilities using the addition rule and set theoretic concepts in Venn diagrams. Additionally, these sets form a foundational component in graph theory, allowing us to better understand connectivity, networks, and algorithms.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force, from its establishment in 1918 until its merger into the Ministry of Defence in 1964. Responsible for national defence and civil aviation coordination, the Air Ministry played a crucial role in maintaining the British airspace, along with researching and developing advancements in air technology during World War I and World War II. In addition, the ministry controlled aircraft production, regulated training, managed aviation personnel and logistics, and fostered international cooperation through aviation treaties and agreements.

Lillian Evelyn Gilbreth ( Moller; May 24, 1878 – January 2, 1972) was an American psychologist, industrial engineer, consultant, and educator who was an early pioneer in applying psychology to time-and-motion studies. She was described in the 1940s as "a genius in the art of living." Gilbreth, one of the first female engineers to earn a Ph.D., is considered to be the first industrial/organizational psychologist. She and her husband, Frank Bunker Gilbreth, were efficiency experts who contributed to the study of industrial engineering, especially in the areas of motion study and human factors.

Year 1391 (MCCCXCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 6 – Massacre of 1391: Anti-Jewish pogroms erupt in Seville, Spain. Many thousands of Jews are massacred, and the violence spreads throughout Spain and Portugal, specially to Toledo, Barcelona and Mallorca. This event marks a turning-point in the history of the Spanish Jews, with most of the survivors leaving the Iberian Peninsula or being forced to convert. July 18 – Tokhtamysh–Timur war: Battle of the Kondurcha River – Timur defeats Tokhtamysh of the Golden Horde, in present day southeast Russia.

Samuel de Champlain (; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635) was a French colonist, navigator, cartographer, draftsman, soldier, explorer, geographer, ethnologist, diplomat, and chronicler. He made between 21 and 29 trips across the Atlantic Ocean, and founded Quebec, and New France, on 3 July 1608. An important figure in Canadian history, Champlain created the first accurate coastal map during his explorations, and founded various colonial settlements.Born into a family of sailors, Champlain began exploring North America in 1603, under the guidance of his uncle, François Gravé Du Pont.

Year 1321 ( MCCCXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events during this year included the beginning of the infamous Children's Crusade, led by the charismatic French peasant Stephen of Cloyes, who inspired thousands of children and adolescents to embark on a holy pilgrimage to the Holy Land with the goal of converting Muslims to Christianity. The crusade ultimately resulted in great tragedy and hardship, as many participants were abandoned, sold into slavery, or lost at sea during their journey.

Tequila is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant , primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila, Mexico, in the region of Jalisco. Other areas with legal rights to produce tequila are the states of Nayarit, Tamaulipas, Guanajuato, and Michoacán. Tequila can be categorized into different varieties such as Blanco, Joven, Reposado, Añejo, and Extra Añejo. These types differ in their aging process, flavors, and colors. Dating back to the 16th century, tequila is a deeply-rooted part of Mexican culture, history, and culinary traditions.

Botulinum toxin (BoNT) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species. It prevents the release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine from axon endings at the neuromuscular junction, thus causing flaccid paralysis. The toxin causes the disease botulism. The toxin is also used commercially for medical and cosmetic purposes.The seven main types of botulinum toxin are named types A to G (A, B, C1, C2, D, E, F and G). New types are occasionally found. Types A and B are capable of causing disease in humans, and are also used commercially and medically.

Spiro Theodore Agnew (November 9, 1918 – September 17, 1996) was the 39th vice president of the United States, serving from 1969 until his resignation in 1973. He is the second vice president to resign the position, the other being John C. Calhoun in 1832. Agnew was born in Baltimore to a Greek immigrant father and an American mother. He attended Johns Hopkins University and graduated from the University of Baltimore School of Law. He worked as an aide to U.S. Representative James Devereux before he was appointed to the Baltimore County Board of Zoning Appeals in 1957.

In software quality assurance, performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload. It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.Testing typesLoad testing Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing. A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.

Year 1379 (MCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  May 29 – John I succeeds his father, Henry II, as King of Castile and King of León. June 30 – New College, Oxford, is founded in England by William of Wykeham, Bishop of Winchester. July 1 – Forces of the Republic of Venice and Ottoman Turks, having invaded Constantinople, restore John V Palaiologos as Byzantine co-emperor. Andronikos IV Palaiologos is allowed to remain as co-emperor, but is confined to the city of Silivri for the remainder of his life.

Year 1525 ( MDXXV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events that occurred in 1525 included the German Peasants' War and the Battle of Pavia, which greatly impacted European politics and society. Martin Luther's rejection of the German peasants' demands for social equality and liberty during the peasants' revolt influenced the Reformation. Moreover, the Spanish Empire emerged victorious in the Battle of Pavia, capturing the French king Francis I, which marked the decline of French influence in the Italian Peninsula and the dominance of Charles V in Europe.

Year 1494 ( MCDXCIV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1494 was marked by various notable events that took place across the world. The Treaty of Tordesillas was signed, dividing the newly discovered lands outside Europe between the Spanish Empire and Portugal. France's King Charles VIII commenced the first Italian War by invading the Italian peninsula in a quest for the Kingdom of Naples. Meanwhile, Italian polymath Luca Pacioli published the world's first accounting and bookkeeping textbook, significantly impacting global financial systems for centuries to come.

Eric Arthur Heiden ( born June 14 , 1958 ) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater, who is considered one of the greatest athletes in the history of the sport. During his illustrious career, Heiden achieved unparalleled success, including winning five individual gold medals at the 1980 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid, a record that still stands today. He also set multiple world records in various distances throughout his career. Following his retirement from speed skating, Heiden pursued his passion for medicine and graduated from Stanford University's School of Medicine in 1991.

Year 1532 (MDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 22 – São Vicente is established as the first permanent Portuguese settlement in Brazil. March 18 – The English Parliament bans payment by the English Church to Rome. April – Battle of Quipaipan in Peru: Atahualpa wins the civil war in the Inca Empire, defeating his brother Huáscar. May 13 – Francisco Pizarro lands on the northern coast of Peru. May 16 – Sir Thomas More resigns as Lord Chancellor of England.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese ( born 17 April 1954 ) is an Italian former racing driver , who raced in Formula One from 1977 to 1993. Born in Padua, Italy, Patrese started his professional racing career with karting at just nine years old, and then eventually transitioned into competing in single-seaters. Known for his successful racing partnerships with iconic teams such as Alfa Romeo, Williams, and Benetton, Patrese holds six Grand Prix victories, including the 1982 Monaco Grand Prix, 1989 San Marino Grand Prix, and the 1991 Mexican Grand Prix.

GNU Privacy Guard ( GnuPG or GPG ) is a free-software replacement for Symantec 's PGP cryptographic software suite . GnuPG, an open-source alternative, employs the same cryptographic principles as Symantec's PGP suite but without the licensing constraints, making it a popular choice among users who prefer open-source solutions for data privacy and encryption. It offers robust and secure cryptographic operations like encryption, decryption, digital signatures, and authentication. GnuPG provides a versatile key management system, making it suitable for various platforms, including email encryption and signing, file encryption, and securing sensitive communication.

Events January–June January 23 – The Triple Alliance of 1668 is formed between England , Sweden and the United Provinces of the Netherlands to counter the expansionist policies of Louis XIV of France. Despite facing economic hardships, the three countries decide to unify in their diplomatic approach in a bid to combat the aggressive actions of France. As the alliance gains momentum, tensions mount in Europe, leading to sporadic military confrontations along bordering territories. Meanwhile, internally, the participating nations must navigate delicate political situations as citizens debate the value and viability of this new Triple Alliance in the face of an increasingly assertive and powerful French regime.

Black's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States. Henry Campbell Black (1860–1927) was the author of the first two editions of the dictionary.HistoryThe first edition was published in 1891 by West Publishing, with the full title A Dictionary of Law: containing definitions of the terms and phrases of American and English jurisprudence, ancient and modern, including the principal terms of international constitutional and commercial law, with a collection of legal maxims and numerous select titles from the civil law and other foreign systems. A second edition was published in 1910 as A Law Dictionary.

CBE may refer to : Travel CBE , IATA code for Greater Cumberland Regional Airport . CBE , ICAO code for SriLankan Airlines. Education CBE, competency-based education, a teaching approach focused on students acquiring skills and demonstrating proficiency in learning areas. Finance CBE, Center for Banking Education, an institution that provides comprehensive and focused training to financial institutions globally. Entertainment CBE, acronym for Chris Brown Entertainment, an American record label founded by Chris Brown in 2007. Technology CBE, abbreviation for Cell Broadband Engine, a microprocessor architecture designed by Sony, Toshiba, and IBM for applications in video game consoles, such as PlayStation 3.

In cosmology, the cosmological constant (usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda: Λ), alternatively called Einstein's cosmological constant, is the constant coefficient of a term Albert Einstein temporarily added to his field equations of general relativity. He later removed it. Much later it was revived and reinterpreted as the energy density of space, or vacuum energy, that arises in quantum mechanics. It is closely associated with the concept of dark energy.Einstein originally introduced the constant in 1917 to counterbalance the effect of gravity and achieve a static universe, a notion which was the accepted view at the time.

Andorra , officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra < ref > , is a sovereign landlocked microstate nestled in the eastern Pyrenees mountains, bordered by Spain to the south and France to the north. The territory spans 468 square kilometers, making it the sixth-smallest nation in Europe. It boasts a rich history and diverse cultural heritage influenced by both neighboring countries. As one of the last remaining principalities in the world, the government operates under a co-principality, with the President of France and Bishop of Urgell acting as co-princes.

Uracil ( symbol U or Ura ) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are represented by the letters A, G, C, and U. The others are adenine (A), guanine (G), and cytosine (C). Uracil is structurally similar to thymine (T), which is one of the nucleobases found in DNA. However, uracil replaces thymine in RNA molecules. Uracil's primary role is in the formation of complementary base pairings during the transcription and translation process of RNA.

In art history, literature and cultural studies, Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world. These depictions are usually done by writers, designers, and artists from the Western world. In particular, Orientalist painting, depicting more specifically "the Middle East", was one of the many specialisms of 19th-century academic art, and the literature of Western countries took a similar interest in Oriental themes.Since the publication of Edward Said's Orientalism in 1978, much academic discourse has begun to use the term "Orientalism" to refer to a general patronizing Western attitude towards Middle Eastern, Asian, and North African societies.

Year 1556 ( MDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year was marked by several important events worldwide. In October, the deadliest earthquake in human history, the Shaanxi earthquake, struck China causing over 800,000 deaths and immense damage. Meanwhile, in Europe, Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor, abdicated his throne, making way for his son Philip II to ascend as the ruler of Spain and other territories. The same year witnessed England’s prominent church, Ely Cathedral, endure considerable damage due to a severe storm.

In metaphysics , extension signifies both 'stretching out ' ( Latin : extensio ) as well as later 'taking up space' ( Latin : occupatio spatii ). These dual meanings illustrate the two core aspects of the concept - an ongoing process and its resultant state. Extension represents the act of a substance expanding, whether through physical forces or changes in properties. It also conveys the capacity of an entity to fill or occupy a region of space. A comprehensive understanding of extension thus requires an examination of the interplay between these constituent aspects and their influence on the form, substance, and presence of objects in reality.

Year 1526 ( MDXXVI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1526 was marked by significant events that occurred across the world, reshaping the socio-political landscape in the regions. This was particularly the case in the fields of warfare, religion, and conquest. In Europe, it was marked by the defeat of King Louis II of Hungary by the Ottoman Empire in the Battle of Mohacs, subsequently leading to the disintegration of the Hungarian Kingdom. This marked a period of Ottoman expansion and domination over parts of Eastern Europe.

Events January–December February 21 – The Prussian Confederation is formed . April 9 – Christopher of Bavaria is elected King of Denmark, Norway, and Sweden, thus beginning the Kalmar Union era of joint Scandinavian rule. May 27 – The fall of Constantinople to the Ottoman Empire marks the end of the Byzantine Empire and paves the way for the Ottomans' rapid expansion throughout southeastern Europe. June 13 – The Ladislaus the Posthumous is crowned King of Hungary. August 29 – John de La Pole, the Duke of Suffolk, becomes an influential figure in the English government during the later stages of the Hundred Years' War.

Mercia (, ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy. The name is a Latinisation of the Old English  or  (West Saxon dialect;  in the Mercian dialect itself), meaning "border people" (see March). Mercia dominated what would later become England for three centuries, subsequently going into a gradual decline while Wessex eventually conquered and united all the kingdoms into the Kingdom of England.The kingdom was centred on the valley of the River Trent and its tributaries, in the region now known as the English Midlands. The court moved around the kingdom, and there was no fixed capital city.

Year 1490 (MCDXC) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – Anne of Brittany announces that all those who ally themselves with the king of France will be considered guilty of the crime of Lèse-majesté. March 13 – Charles II becomes Duke of Savoy at age 1; his mother Blanche of Montferrato is regent. March or April – 1490 Ch'ing-yang event, a presumed meteor shower or air burst over Qingyang in Ming dynasty China, said to have caused casualties.
