Year 1526 (MDXXVI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 14 – Treaty of Madrid: Peace is declared between Francis I of France and Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor. Francis agrees to cede Burgundy and abandons all claims to Flanders, Artois, Naples, and Milan. April 21 – Battle of Panipat: Babur becomes Mughal emperor, invades northern India and captures Delhi, beginning the richest dynasty in the world, the Mughal Empire, which lasts until 1857.

Year 1165 ( MCLXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1165 (MCLXV), various significant events occurred, impacting politics, religion, and society of the time. As a year marked by new rulers, political conflicts, and significant religious occurrences, the trajectory of regional power dynamics shifted dramatically. Important milestones of this period included coronations of regional kings and intricate political alliances, making it an essential and exciting year in human history. Year 1165 was merely a stepping stone, building toward the massive socio-political shifts that the world would experience over the next several centuries.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls or gates of fortifications. The main body of the battering ram consisted of a large, heavy beam made from a dense, durable material such as oak. At the front, a strong and pointed head, usually resembling a ram's head, was mounted to effectively break through walls. During assaults, the ram was typically covered by a movable, tortoise-like protective roof known as a penthouse, or 'turtle', that defended the ramming crew from enemy projectiles.

Events January–June March 13 – Battle of Tondibi : In Mali , forces sent by the Saadi Dynasty ruler of Morocco, Sultan Ahmad al-Mansur, led by Judar Pasha, decisively defeat the Songhai Empire, marking the fall of one of the most prominent West African empires. Despite facing issues related to inadequate resources, Judar Pasha's strategic expertise coupled with powerful firearms proves too much for the Songhai troops who are unprepared to face these new and deadly weapons. Over the next months, Moroccan forces systematically establish their rule throughout the conquered lands, initiating an era of strained relationships between Morocco and various African tribes for years to come.

A finite difference is a mathematical expression of the form . If a finite difference is divided by , one gets a difference quotient. The approximation of derivatives by finite differences plays a central role in finite difference methods for the numerical solution of differential equations, especially boundary value problems.The difference operator, commonly denoted  is the operator that maps a function  to the function  defined byA difference equation is a functional equation that involves the finite difference operator in the same way as a differential equation involves derivatives. There are many similarities between difference equations and differential equations, specially in the solving methods.

Year 1396 (MCCCXCVI) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 19 – Martin I succeeds his brother, John I, as King of Aragon (modern-day north-east Spain). July 20 – Queen Margaret I of Denmark, Norway and Sweden publishes the Treaty of Kalmar, proposing the personal union of the three kingdoms of Denmark, Norway (with Iceland, Greenland, the Faroe Islands, Shetland and Orkney) and Sweden (including Finland and Åland). July 23 – Queen Margaret makes her great-nephew and adopted son Eric of Pomerania joint ruler of Sweden.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting, gluing, rearranging and overlapping two or more photographs into a new image. Sometimes the resulting composite image is photographed so that the final image may appear as a seamless physical print. A similar method, although one that does not use film, is realized today through image-editing software. This latter technique is referred to by professionals as "compositing", and in casual usage is often called "photoshopping" (from the name of the popular software system).

Year 1491 ( MCDXCI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1491 was marked by significant events and progress across Europe and the world. Key among them were ongoing struggles for power, cultural exchange, and exploration of new territories. The battle for influence between Spain's warring kingdoms came closer to a resolution with a crucial treaty, as navigators forged ahead in search of lucrative trade routes. This historical backdrop set the stage for a decisive shift towards political unity and the golden age of discovery in the years to come.

For other nobles of the same name , please see SigismundSigismund of Bavaria ( 26 July 1439 – 1 February 1501) was a member of the powerful Wittelsbach dynasty and served as the Duke of Bavaria from 1460 to 1467, after which he voluntarily abdicated in favor of his younger brother, Albert. As a skillful diplomat and strategist, Sigismund maintained stability and peace within the duchy, forging strategic alliances with neighboring territories to counterbalance potential threats. Though not primarily focused on territorial expansion, he valued strengthening the duchy's governance, developing trade, and promoting the growth of the arts and sciences within his domain.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech , 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol ( ; ; ; 11 May 1904 – 23 January 1989) was a renowned Spanish surrealist artist, best known for his unusual and innovative work that encompassed painting, sculpture, and filmmaking, among other forms. A truly original and pioneering figure, Dalí pushed the boundaries of artistic expression with his unmistakable personal style characterized by surreal dreamscapes, bizarre subject matters, and extraordinary attention to detail. One of his most iconic works, 'The Persistence of Memory' (1931), portrays melting watches, which reflect his musings on the elasticity of time.

Year 1328 (MCCCXXVIII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 24 – Philippa of Hainault marries King Edward III of England a year after his coronation. The marriage produces ten children, the eldest of whom is Edward the Black Prince. May 1 – Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton: England recognises Scotland as an independent nation, after the Wars of Scottish Independence. May 12 – Antipope Nicholas V is consecrated at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome by the bishop of Venice. May 26 – William of Ockham secretly leaves Avignon, under threat from Pope John XXII.

Year 1442 (MCDXLII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 18–25 – Battle of Hermannstadt: John Hunyadi defeats an army of the Ottoman Empire 80,000 strong, led by Mesid Bey of Vidin, near Sibiu in Transylvania. June 2 – Alfonso of Aragon proclaims himself King of Naples. September – John Hunyadi defeats another army of the Ottoman Empire (70,000 strong), led by Hadım Şehabeddin, Beylerbey (or governor) of Rumelia, near the Ialomița River. Following this, he places Basarab II as ruler of Wallachia.

Palermo ( , ; , locally also or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy , the capital of both the autonomous region of Sicily and the Metropolitan City of Palermo. Boasting a rich history that dates back 2,700 years, Palermo was once a key cultural and economic center during Roman, Byzantine, Arab, and Norman periods. Today, the city continues to offer visitors a taste of this ancient legacy with a remarkable ensemble of architectural and artistic wonders, from Arab-Norman buildings to the famous Cappella Palatina, showcasing mosaic art.

Lead azide is an inorganic compound . More so than other azides , is explosive . It is used in initiators for the detonation of explosives due to its highly sensitive and reactive nature. The compound, having the molecular formula Pb(N3)2, appears as a white or off-white crystalline substance. Owing to its ability to decompose with even slight agitation, handling and transportation of lead azide require strict precautionary measures. Additionally, it poses both health and environmental risks, with toxicity linked to lead exposure and the production of nitrogen gases.

Year 997 (CMXCVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  1 February: Empress Teishi give birth to Princess Shushi - she is the first child of the emperor, but because of the power struggle between Michinaga and Korechika, the empress is not allowed to go to the palace 18 May: The imperial court decides to pardon Korechika and Takaie under the illness of Teishi Byzantine Empire  July 16 – Battle of Spercheios: Byzantine forces, under General Nikephoros Ouranos, defeat the Bulgarians at the Spercheios River in Greece.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950, was an early national gay rights organization in the United States, perhaps preceded only by Chicago's Society for Human Rights. Communist and labor activist Harry Hay formed the group with a collection of male friends in Los Angeles to protect and improve the rights of gay men. Branches formed in other cities, and by 1961 the Society had splintered into regional groups.At the beginning of gay rights protest, news on Cuban prison work camps for homosexuals inspired Mattachine Society to organize protests at the United Nations and the White House in 1965.Founding Harry Hay conceived the idea of a gay activist group in 1948.

Year 1035 (MXXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July – The 8-year-old William I becomes duke of Normandy, after his father Robert I (the Magnificent) dies, on a pilgrimage at Nicaea (modern Turkey). Robert's death leads to a period of instability in Normandy, as William is too young to take his father's place. The Norman nobles in the region take the opportunity to settle old feuds, and to increase their private wealth.

Year 1319 ( MCCCXIX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year held many historical events, both of major and minor significance. It was marked by numerous power shifts and conflicts in Europe and Asia, shaping the geopolitical landscape for years to come. Notably, it witnessed the Siege of Medemblik, as well as the Battle of Dysart, showcasing the constantly shifting alliances among kingdoms and other political entities. Additionally, the Avignon Papacy, known for its corruption, was the dominating authority in Christianity, shaping religious life and doctrine during that time.

Year 1273 (MCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  January 22 – Muhammad II becomes Sultan of the Emirate of Granada after the death of his father, Muhammad I, in a riding accident. September 29 – Rudolph I of Germany is elected King of Germany over rival candidate King Otakar II of Bohemia, ending the Interregnum; Otakar refuses to acknowledge Rudolph as the new king, leading to the outbreak of war in 1276. Rudolph is the first of many Habsburgs to hold the throne.

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election, held on Tuesday, November 8, 1988. The Republican nominee, incumbent Vice President George H. W. Bush, defeated the Democratic nominee, Governor Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts. This was the first presidential election since 1948, and the most recent to date, in which a party won a third consecutive presidential term. This also remains the most recent election in which a candidate won over 400 electoral votes, and the last time a non-incumbent Republican candidate won the popular vote.Incumbent president Ronald Reagan was ineligible to seek a third term.

Year 1332 (MCCCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1329). August 10–11 – Battle of Dupplin Moor: Edward Balliol rebels, and the English defeat the loyalists of David II in Scotland. September – Edward Balliol crowns himself King of Scotland. November 7 – Lucerne joins the Swiss Confederation with Uri, Schwyz, and Unterwalden. December 16 – Battle of Annan: The loyalists of David II defeat Edward Balliol in Scotland.

In mathematics , an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere , which is an n-dimensional generalization of a sphere in our familiar 3-dimensional space. Simply put, an n-sphere is an n-dimensional shape that consists of all the points at an equal distance (known as radius) from a given center point. While spheres (2-spheres) and circles (1-spheres) are well known in lower dimensions, n-spheres extend this concept into higher-dimensional spaces. The properties and applications of hyperspheres vary based on the dimensions, and they play an important role in fields like algebraic topology, differential geometry, and multi-dimensional calculus.

Year 1038 ( MXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, significant events occurred across the globe, influencing the course of history. In Europe, Christianity continued its expansion, while the Normans strengthened their presence in Italy. Meanwhile, in Asia, the Seljuq Empire solidified its territorial gains, and trade flourished on the Silk Road. The Byzantine Empire also maintained its prominent position, showcasing remarkable architectural achievements such as the Hagia Sophia in Constantinople.

Year 1151 ( MCLI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events of this year include King Conrad III of Germany preparing for the conquest of Italy and consolidating his power within the Holy Roman Empire. Meanwhile, in Portugal, the famous Siege of Lisbon occurs, involving both Moorish and European forces. Religious conflicts continue to shape societies, with various kingdoms establishing closer relations with the papacy. Expansion of the Franciscan and Dominican orders contributes to spreading Christian ideals and influence throughout Europe during this pivotal year in medieval history.

Gravity , or gravitation , is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy , including planets , stars, galaxies, and even light, are attracted to one another. This force, described by Sir Isaac Newton and later elaborated upon by Albert Einstein, is fundamental to the universe and essential for understanding how objects move and interact in space. The strength of gravity depends on the mass of the objects and the distance between them. In everyday life, we experience gravity as the force that keeps us grounded and allows for phenomena like tides and planetary orbits.

1166 (MCLXVI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) asks Venice to help pay the costs of defending Sicily, whose Norman rulers have had good relations with Venice. Doge Vitale II Michiel refuses to pay the requested subsidy. Manuel begins to cultivate relationships with the main commercial rivals of Venice: Genoa and Pisa. He grants them their own trade quarters in Constantinople, very near to the Venetian settlements. Europe  May 7 – King William I (the Wicked) of Sicily dies at Palermo after a 12-year reign.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Monday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 26 – War of Spanish Succession: The uprising by Bavarians against the occupation of the  Electorate of Bavaria by Austrian troops ends after 75 days, and ends the plans of Maximilian, the Elector of Bavaria, to bring Bavaria under the rule of the House of Wittelsbach. January 26 – Great Northern War: The Battle of Grodno begins when a coalition of 34,000 Swedish and Polish troops besieges the then-Lithuanian city in the winter time and clashes with 41,000 Russian and Saxon troops.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word `` play '' is from Middle English pleye , which traces back to Old English plēġa, both meaning a game or sport. The word "wright" is derived from the Old English word wryhta, meaning a worker or maker. Thus, a playwright or dramatist can be described as a person who crafts or creates plays for the stage. A playwright usually begins their work by exploring an idea or theme that is relevant to society, and then uses their skills to develop engaging dialogue, complex characters, and an intricate plotline to convey their message.

Charles XIV John ( ; born Jean Bernadotte ; 26 January 1763 – 8 March 1844 ) was King of Sweden and Norway from 5 February 1818 until his death in 1844. Originally a French Marshal under Napoleon Bonaparte, he was unexpectedly elected Crown Prince of Sweden in 1810 despite having no previous connections to the country. His reign was marked by a progressive social and economic agenda, as well as the union of Sweden and Norway in 1814 following the Treaty of Kiel. Charles XIV John supported modernization, free trade and social reforms during his reign, helping the nation transition into the industrial age and maintain political stability.

In category theory, a branch of mathematics, the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of universal constructions such as products, pullbacks and inverse limits. The dual notion of a colimit generalizes constructions such as disjoint unions, direct sums, coproducts, pushouts and direct limits.Limits and colimits, like the strongly related notions of universal properties and adjoint functors, exist at a high level of abstraction. In order to understand them, it is helpful to first study the specific examples these concepts are meant to generalize.Definition Limits and colimits in a category  are defined by means of diagrams in .

Year 1303 ( MCCCIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked notable events that left their impact on various spheres including politics, conflicts, and natural phenomena. In Asia, the Mongols continued to exert dominance in the region. In Europe, disputes raged between the English and French royalty while major architectural works saw the rise in places like Italy. Science, education, and the arts evolved with prestigious establishments opening doors, providing platforms for knowledge. Furthermore, nature showed its fury with disasters causing devastation, redefining human development patterns during that year.

Year 1445 (MCDXLV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  October 10 – Battle of Mokra: The Albanian forces under Skanderbeg defeat the Ottoman forces (Pope Eugene IV raises a hymn of praise, that Christendom has been provided with a new defender, after he hears of the battle). Date unknown  The Portuguese set up their first trading post (Feitoria) in Africa, on the island of Arguin. Portuguese explorer Dinis Dias discovers the Cap-Vert, on the western coast of Africa.

Stigmata (, plural of  , 'mark, spot, brand'), in Christianity, are the appearance of bodily wounds, scars and pain in locations corresponding to the crucifixion wounds of Jesus Christ, such as the hands, wrists, and feet. Stigmata are primarily associated with Roman Catholicism. Many reported stigmatics are members of Catholic religious orders. St. Francis of Assisi was the first recorded stigmatic. For over fifty years, St. Padre Pio of Pietrelcina of the Order of Friars Minor Capuchin reported stigmata which were studied by several 20th-century physicians.

Alpine skiing , or downhill skiing , is the pastime of sliding down snow-covered slopes on skis with fixed-heel bindings , unlike Nordic skiing where the heel is free. It is a popular winter sport, enjoyed by millions of enthusiasts worldwide. Alpine skiing is typically performed at ski resorts, which offer various terrains suitable for different skill levels. Skiers wear specialized boots attached to their skis via bindings, along with essential protective gear, such as helmets and goggles. Advanced techniques, including carving and parallel turns, require a certain level of proficiency for safe navigation.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse ( often referred to as the Four Horsemen ) are figures in Christian religion , appearing in the New Testament's final book, Revelation, written by John of Patmos. The horsemen represent four disastrous events that signify the end of the world. These catastrophic phenomena include conquest (a white horse with its rider holding a bow), war (a red horse ridden by a warrior with a large sword), famine (a black horse with its rider holding a balance scale), and death (a pale green horse with its rider called Hades).

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech, 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol  (; ; ; 11 May 190423 January 1989) was a Spanish surrealist artist renowned for his technical skill, precise draftsmanship, and the striking and bizarre images in his work.Born in Figueres, Catalonia, Spain, Dalí received his formal education in fine arts in Madrid. Influenced by Impressionism and the Renaissance masters from a young age, he became increasingly attracted to Cubism and avant-garde movements. He moved closer to Surrealism in the late 1920s and joined the Surrealist group in 1929, soon becoming one of its leading exponents.

As of March 1 ( O.S . February 19 ) , where then Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the Gregorian calendar did not, a unique historical event took place. This resulted in the adoption of two different calendar systems simultaneously throughout various parts of the world. Countries adhering to the Gregorian calendar had to make adjustments to align their dates, leading to much confusion in areas that shared political and trade relationships. Despite the inconsistencies and complexities created, this ultimately marked a transition point in time, allowing societies to adapt and develop more cohesive communication and synchronization for future collaborations on a global scale.

Year 1511 (MDXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 26 - The 1511 Idrija earthquake occurs, with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme). The epicenter is around the town of Idrija in present-day Slovenia, although some place it some 15-20 kilometers to the west, between Gemona and Pulfero in Friulian Slovenia. The earthquake affects a large territory between Carinthia, Friuli, present-day Slovenia and Croatia. April 9 St John's College, Cambridge, England, founded by Lady Margaret Beaufort, receives its charter.The Şahkulu Rebellion breaks out in Anatolia.

Charles XV also Carl (Carl Ludvig Eugen); Swedish: Karl XV and Norwegian: Karl IV (3 May 1826 – 18 September 1872) was King of Sweden (Charles XV) and Norway, there often referred to accurately as Charles IV, from 1859 until his death in 1872. Though known as King Charles XV in Sweden (and also on contemporary Norwegian coins), he was actually the ninth Swedish king by that name, as his predecessor Charles IX (reigned 1604–1611) had adopted a numeral according to a fictitious history of Sweden.

Year 1363 ( MCCCLXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events that took place in the year 1363 included the conclusion of the Siege of Shuangyashan in modern-day China, with Ming forces triumphantly emerging victorious over the invading Yuan army. The Polish-Hungarian king, Casimir the Great, bestowed founding privileges for the University of Krakow, which would later be renamed Jagiellonian University. Meanwhile in Western Europe, England and France observed a brief and tenuous peace through the Treaty of Brétigny amidst the ongoing Hundred Years' War.

Roger Williams ( 21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683 ) was a Puritan minister , theologian , and author who founded the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations in 1636. He is best known for his strong stance on religious freedom and the separation of church and state. In 1644, Williams published "The Bloudy Tenent of Persecution," which fiercely condemned intolerance and advocated for civil authorities to protect diverse religious views. Additionally, he maintained amicable relations with Native American tribes, further emphasizing his commitment to inclusiveness and harmony within society.

Year 1533 (MDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – King Henry VIII of England formally but secretly marries Anne Boleyn, who becomes his second queen consort. January 26 – Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden, is appointed Lord Chancellor of England. March 30 – Thomas Cranmer becomes Archbishop of Canterbury. April – The Statute in Restraint of Appeals in England declares the king to be the supreme sovereign and forbids judicial appeals to the papacy.

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Great Britain by the Roman Empire. Beginning in AD 43 under Emperor Claudius, Roman forces, led by General Aulus Plautius, launched a successful invasion that established Roman rule across much of the island. Over the course of the next four centuries, Romans expanded and consolidated their territories, influencing the cultural, religious, and economic landscape of Britain. They built a sophisticated network of roads, established thriving cities, and introduced significant advancements in architecture, technology, and agriculture.

Year 1335 ( MCCCXXXV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, several significant events took place which impacted the course of history. In Europe, the Renaissance was steadily emerging, characterized by a revival in the arts, sciences, and the growth of humanism. In the East, the Ottoman Empire continued to expand under Sultan Orhan. Concurrently, a deadly plague was also sweeping through several regions, later identified as the first wave of the Black Death. Throughout the year, military skirmishes and socio-political unrest shaped this volatile period.

Year 1409 ( MCDIX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year was marked by several significant events across Europe and Asia, including political upheavals, cultural milestones, and natural disasters. The Council of Pisa was convened in an effort to end the Western Schism and reunify the Catholic Church. Lithuania saw the signing of the Treaty of Salynas, which solidified its union with Poland. Meanwhile, in the Middle East, Timur (Tamerlane) launched his last military campaign in the Persian Empire, sowing destruction in his path.

Year 1148 (MCXLVIII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   Second Crusade  January 1 – The French crusaders under King Louis VII defeat a Turkish ambush next to the Meander River. Three days later they arrive at Laodicea – passing the spot where the German contingent led by Otto of Freising has been so disastrously ambushed (see 1147). The Crusaders are badly mauled as they cross Mount Cadmus (around January 8) before reaching Adalia on January 20.

John Bunyan (; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of the Christian allegory The Pilgrim's Progress, which also became an influential literary model. In addition to The Pilgrim's Progress, Bunyan wrote nearly sixty titles, many of them expanded sermons.Bunyan came from the village of Elstow, near Bedford. He had some schooling and at the age of sixteen joined the Parliamentary Army during the first stage of the English Civil War. After three years in the  army he returned to Elstow and took up the trade of tinker, which he had learned from his father.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 5 – King Charles II of England gives the title Duke of St Albans to Charles Beauclerk, his illegitimate son by Nell Gwyn. January 15 (January 5 O.S.) - To demonstrate that the River Thames, frozen solid during the Great Frost that started in December, is safe to walk upon, "a Coach and six horses drove over the Thames for a wager" and within three days "whole streets of Booths are built on the Thames and thousands of people are continually walking thereon." Sir Richard Newdigate, 2nd Baronet, records the events in his diary.

Mary Virginia Martin (December 1, 1913 – November 3, 1990) was an American actress and singer. A muse of Rodgers and Hammerstein, she originated many leading roles on stage over her career, including Nellie Forbush in South Pacific (1949), the title character in Peter Pan (1954), and Maria von Trapp in The Sound of Music (1959). She was named a Kennedy Center Honoree in 1989. She was the mother of actor Larry Hagman.Early life Martin was born in Weatherford, Texas. Her autobiography described her childhood as secure and happy.

Year 1174 (MCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1174th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 174th year of the 2nd millennium, the 74th year of the 12th century, and the 5th year of the 1170s decade.Events  By place  England  July 13 – Battle of Alnwick: King William I (the Lion) supported by Flemish mercenaries invades England to help fight in the baronial rebellion against King Henry II. William attacks Prudhoe Castle in Northumberland, but is unable to capture it.

Year 1578 ( MDLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was marked by significant global events, notably the unfolding of the Age of Discovery as explorers sought new trade routes and lands. Spanish navigators sailed the Atlantic Ocean, resulting in key advancements in European maritime prowess. This period saw a power struggle between European powers, with key military conflicts and diplomatic endeavors shaping the course of history. Culture and arts flourished under the patronage of influential leaders, providing further momentum for scientific and technological breakthroughs of the era.

Events  January–June  January 5 – Franco-Dutch War – Battle of Turckheim: The French defeat Austria and Brandenburg. January 29 – John Sassamon, an English-educated Native American Christian, dies at Assawampsett Pond, an event which will trigger a year-long war between the English American colonists of New England, and the Algonquian Native American tribes. March 30 – The guild organisation Maîtresses couturières is founded in Paris. April – English merchant Anthony de la Roché, blown off course after rounding Cape Horn eastabout, makes the first discovery of land south of the Antarctic Convergence, landing on South Georgia and (probably) Gough Island.

Year 1023 ( MXXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1023, significant events occurred both in Europe and Asia. In Italy, Pietro Boccapecora, the Bishop of Ravenna, was captured by pirates, bringing attention to piracy in the region. Meanwhile, Emperor Sanjō ascended to the Japanese throne after Emperor Go-Ichijō retired at only the age of 22. In northern Europe, there were internal disputes and violence due to Prince Jaroslav Vladimirovich, later Jaroslav the Wise, briefly exiling his brother Mstislav of Chernigov.

Greyhound racing is an organized , competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track . There are two forms of greyhound racing, track racing and coursing. Track racing involves the use of an artificial hare, often referred to as a "lure," which the dogs chase as it travels around the circular or oval track. On the other hand, coursing sees greyhounds chase a live game animal, typically a rabbit, on an open field. Greyhound racing, popular for gambling and spectator enjoyment, dates back centuries but has faced increased scrutiny due to concerns regarding the welfare of the racing dogs.

Blum Blum Shub ( B.B.S . ) is a pseudorandom number generator proposed in 1986 by Lenore Blum , Manuel Blum, and Michael Shub. It is primarily used for cryptographic purposes due to its unique features of being secure, unpredictable, and unbiased. The generator operates on the quadratic residue formula of x^2 mod N, where N is a product of two prime numbers (P and Q). The core of the algorithm lies in the process of selecting two primes P and Q (of a particular form), initializing a random seed value X0, and iteratively squaring and computing modulus, thus yielding the random numbers.

John the Apostle ( ; ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to the New Testament. Generally listed as the youngest of the Apostles, he is also the only one who, according to tradition, was not martyred, but instead lived to old age. John is credited with writing the Gospel of John, as well as three Epistles, and the Book of Revelation. He is often identified with John the Evangelist and John of Patmos, and his relationship with Jesus Christ made him known as the disciple "whom Jesus loved."

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday , one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar. Sweden was undergoing a unique experiment in transitioning from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar by introducing the 'Swedish Calendar'. As part of this attempt, the year 1700 had February 29, making it the only time a Swedish calendar featured this additional day. This leap year resulted in confusion as dates differed between neighboring countries. Ultimately, in 1712, Sweden returned to the Julian calendar and only fully adopted the Gregorian calendar in 1753.

Melvin Kranzberg ( November 22 , 1917 – December 6 , 1995 ) was an American historian , and professor of the history of technology at the Georgia Institute of Technology. Born in St. Louis, Missouri, Kranzberg pursued his undergraduate and postgraduate education in history, eventually earning his doctorate in 1942. Best known for his significant contributions to the study and understanding of technology's role in society, Kranzberg is well-remembered for establishing Kranzberg's Laws of technology, the six key principles that continue to guide contemporary scholars and policy-makers in their exploration of technology and its societal implications.

Year 1507 ( MDVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a year marked by notable events and explorations in both the Old and New Worlds. In Europe, this was a period of great cultural achievements as the Italian Renaissance continued to flourish. Prominent artists such as Michelangelo, Leonardo da Vinci, and Raphael created their most enduring works during this time. Meanwhile, the New World witnessed an exciting age of discovery and exploration. In this year, cartographer Martin Waldseemüller first coined the name "America" in honor of explorer Amerigo Vespucci.

Anne Boleyn (;  1501 – 19 May 1536) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536, as the second wife of King Henry VIII. The circumstances of her marriage and of her execution by beheading for treason and other charges made her a key figure in the political and religious upheaval that marked the start of the English Reformation. Anne was the daughter of Thomas Boleyn, 1st Earl of Wiltshire, and his wife, Lady Elizabeth Howard, and was educated in the Netherlands and France, largely as a maid of honour to Queen Claude of France.

Year 1430 (MCDXXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 7 – Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, marries Isabella of Portugal. January 10 – Philip the Good founds the Order of the Golden Fleece. March 29 – The Ottoman Empire, under Murad II, captures Thessalonica after an eight-year siege. May 14 – The French first attempt to relieve the Siege of Compiègne. May 23 – Joan of Arc is captured by the Burgundians, while leading an army to relieve Compiègne.

Perpignan ( , , ; ; ; ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department ( known as Northern Catalonia ) in the Occitanie region of Southern France. Located close to the Mediterranean Sea and the French-Spanish border, it boasts a unique blend of cultures and architectural styles, making it a must-visit destination. With a population of over 120,000 people, Perpignan retains its traditional charm with a lively ambiance in its old town and numerous historic landmarks, including the Palace of the Kings of Majorca and the Saint-Jean Cathedral. The city is also a hub for tourism, commerce, and serves as a significant transportation link in the area.

In mathematics , open sets are a generalization of open intervals in the real line . In a metric space—that is, a set and a distance function (called a metric) defined on that set—an open set is a subset that has the following property: for every point in the subset, there exists a neighborhood (in this context, an open ball, meaning all points at a finite non-negative distance less than a given value) around that point, whose entire contents lie within the subset. The concept of open sets serves as a foundation for several branches of mathematics, including topology, calculus, and analysis.

Year 1357 ( MCCCLVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year was marked by numerous notable events and historical developments around the world. In the 14th century, European countries were facing socio-political changes, while Eastern realms underwent shifts in power dynamics. Major highlights include King Edward III of England invading France in a campaign known as the Hundred Years' War. Meanwhile, a new commercial treaty signed between England and Portugal promoted trade and marked the beginning of an influential alliance.

Year 1548 ( MDXLVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the history of the world, the year 1548 was marked by significant events, both joyful and devastating, that would come to shape the future in immeasurable ways. Power dynamics were shifting on the European continent, while voyages of exploration continued to traverse the vast seas, altering the geopolitical and cultural landscapes that defined these epoch-making times. Advances in the realms of art, science, and technology sought to uplift human existence as nations navigated the murky waters of war, peace, and everything in-between.

For other nobles of the same name, please see SigismundSigismund of Bavaria (26 July 1439 – 1 February 1501) was a member of the Wittelsbach dynasty. He ruled as Duke of Bavaria-Munich from 1460 to 1467, and then as Duke of Bavaria-Dachau until his death.BiographySigismund was the third son of Albert III of Bavaria with Princess Anna of Brunswick-Grubenhagen-Einbeck his second wife.Sigismund was Duke of Bavaria-Munich from 1460 to 1467, until 1463 together with his brother John IV. In 1467, he resigned in favor of his younger brother Albert IV and then kept only the new duchy of Bavaria-Dachau as his domain until his death.

Tequila  is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant, primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila  northwest of Guadalajara, and in the Jaliscan Highlands (Los Altos de Jalisco) of the central western Mexican state of Jalisco.The red volcanic soils in the region of Tequila are well suited for growing the blue agave, and more than 300 million of the plants are harvested there each year. Agave grows differently depending on the region. Blue agaves grown in the highlands Los Altos region are larger and sweeter in aroma and taste. Agaves harvested in the valley region have a more herbaceous fragrance and flavor.

Events  January–June  January 8 – The Jesuit educational plan, known as the Ratio Studiorum, is issued. March 12 – Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex, is appointed Lord Lieutenant of Ireland, by Queen Elizabeth I of England. April 23 – The Earl of Essex arrives in Dublin at the head of 16,000 troops, the largest army ever seen in Ireland. May 16 – The Kalmar Bloodbath takes place in Kalmar, Sweden. May 29 – Essex takes Cahir Castle, supposedly the strongest in Ireland, after a short siege. June 20 – The Synod of Diamper is convened.

Year 993 ( CMXCIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, several notable events shaped history around the globe. Europe saw the Byzantine Emperor Nikephoros II of Sicily sign a treaty of friendship with Holy Roman Emperor Otto III. Across the English Channel, King Aethelred the Unready became a stronger presence after having repulsed an attempted Danish invasion. China experienced steady technological advancements as movable type printing was refined and popularized, providing opportunities for further exchange of ideas and knowledge.

Year 1328 ( MCCCXXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, various historical events unfolded worldwide, impacting politics, religion, and society. Key happenings of 1328 included the Treaty of Edinburgh-Northampton between Scotland and England, establishing Scottish independence after years of conflict. France saw the initiation of Philip VI's reign, marking the beginning of the Valois dynasty. On the religious front, the appointment of William of Ockham as an influential theologian significantly impacted European scholastic thought, pushing the envelope for academic discourse in this age of transition.

Year 1310 (MCCCX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January –  Forces of the Kingdom of Castile retreat from the Siege of Algeciras, after enduring severe losses, and secure a peace treaty. March – Muhammed III, former Sultan of the Emirate of Granada, is blinded and found dead in a pool, after an attempted coup to retake his throne from his brother Nasr. May 11 – In France, 54 members of the Knights Templar are burned at the stake for heresy.Date unknown  Abu al-Fida becomes governor of Hama.

1499 ( MCDXCIX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was marked by several significant historical events, both in the realms of exploration and culture. In the area of exploration, notable figures such as John Cabot and Christopher Columbus continued their quest to chart new lands and routes. In Portugal, the Escorial of Naval Adventures is established, leading the way in maritime developments. Culturally, Renaissance ideas continued to spread throughout Europe, fostering a time of great artistic and scientific innovation.

Charles Pierce ( July 14 , 1926 – May 31 , 1999 ) was one of the 20th century 's foremost female impersonators, highly regarded for his uncanny portrayals of legendary figures like Bette Davis, Mae West, and Tallulah Bankhead. Throughout his remarkable career that spanned over five decades, Pierce entertained countless audiences across the United States and Europe, earning a loyal following with his wit, glamour, and unmatched talent. Despite battling with cancer, Pierce courageously continued to perform until the end of his life, leaving an unforgettable legacy that inspired the next generation of drag performers, pushing the boundaries of artistic expression, and celebrating individuality.

Year 1302 ( MCCCII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, many significant events took place around the globe. The Battle of Kortrijk occurred in July between the Flemish townspeople and the French army, with the former securing a notable victory against the latter. Meanwhile, Pope Boniface VIII issued the papal bull Unam Sanctam, asserting his supremacy and divine authority over monarchs. As exploration and trade flourished, there was increased interaction between different regions, cultures, and belief systems.

Year 1456 ( MCDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a period of political unrest and religious transformation in Europe, with notable events such as the Ottoman Empire's victory against the Hungarian Kingdom during the Siege of Belgrade, leading to the growth and consolidation of the Ottomans in Southeastern Europe. In the same year, the papal trial for Jeanne d'Arc took place, nullifying her previous conviction and legitimizing her as a national heroine for France. Gutenberg's first successful experiments on printing using the Gutenberg press were also witnessed in 1456.

Year 1325 (MCCCXXV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 7 – Afonso IV becomes King of Portugal. February – Muhammad bin Tughluq succeeds his father Ghiyath al-Din Tughluq, as Sultan of Delhi. July – War of the Bucket breaks out: Modena makes incursions into the territory of Bologna. November 15 – Battle of Zappolino: Modena defeats Bologna. Date unknown  The town of Bolu is conquered by the Ottoman Empire. Ibn Battuta begins his travels. Mansa Musa completes his pilgrimage to Mecca.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola, released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. It fixes several small flaws in the 68000, and adds a few features.The 68010 is pin-compatible with the 68000, but is not 100% software compatible. Some of the differences were: The MOVE from SR instruction is now privileged (it may only be executed in supervisor mode). This means that the 68010 meets Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements. Because the 68000 offers an unprivileged MOVE from SR, it does not meet them.

Year 1206 (MCCVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 31 – Battle of Rusion: The Bulgarian forces (some 7,000 men) under Tsar Kaloyan defeat the remnants of the Latin army near the fortress of Rusion in Thrace. Around 120 knights supported by soldiers and cavalry are killed in battle or captured. In February, the Bulgarians attack and loot the fortified town of Rodosto (see Battle of Rodosto), defended by a Venetian garrison. Later, Kaloyan captures many more towns and fortresses.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces. The basic goal is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, though usually most classify up to homotopy equivalence.Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible. Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.Main branches of algebraic topologyBelow are some of the main areas studied in algebraic topology:Homotopy groupsIn mathematics, homotopy groups are used in algebraic topology to classify topological spaces.

Year 1046 (MXLVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Autumn – King Henry III (the Black) travels to Italy to secure the imposition of Guido da Velate, archbishop of Milan, and other similarly loyal candidates in other sees (like Ravenna, Verona and Modena). Vatha Pagan Revolt: King Peter Orseolo (the Venetian) is overthrown after a 2-year reign. Bishops Gerard of Csanád and Bystrík (or Bestricus) are stoned to death in Budapest (Hungary).

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets. The series originated as two pilot episodes produced by Henson for ABC in 1974 and 1975. While neither episode was moved forward as a series and other networks in the United States rejected Henson's proposals, British producer Lew Grade expressed enthusiasm for the project and agreed to co-produce The Muppet Show for the British channel  ATV. Five seasons, totalling 120 episodes, were broadcast on ATV and other ITV franchises in the United Kingdom and in later first-run syndication in the US from 1976 to 1981.

Jan Bos ( born 29 March 1975 ) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist . In the late 1990s and early 2000s, he was among the top competitors in both disciplines, representing the Netherlands in numerous international competitions. Jan Bos first gained fame after winning the 1998 World Sprint Championship in speed skating, setting him on a trajectory for a successful athletic career. His achievements include winning several European and World Championship titles as well as breaking world records in the sprint cycling discipline. Even though he retired from competitive sports in 2012, Bos left a significant impact and lasting legacy on the world of sprint cycling and speed skating.

Year 998 (CMXCVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – Otto III retakes Rome and restores power in the papal city. Crescentius II (the Younger) and his followers barricade themselves in Castel Sant'Angelo. Otto's former tutor John Philagathos (Antipope John XVI), who tries to escape into Campania, is pursued by German troops and captured. He is horribly mutilated – his ears, nose and tongue cut off and his eyes are gouged out. Crescentius surrenders at his stronghold and is beheaded.

Digital electronics is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use or produce such signals. It is a vital area of study as the vast majority of modern electronic systems, including computers, communication systems, and multimedia devices, rely on digital electronics. Digital signals are a specific type of electronic signal, characterized by their discrete (distinct and non-continuous) values, typically represented using binary code (comprised of 0's and 1's). The primary advantages of digital electronics over analog electronics are higher precision, greater accuracy, better noise immunity, and easier storage and processing capabilities.

Year 1361 ( MCCCLXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, notable events occurred throughout the world. In Asia, the Goryeo army scored an astounding victory against the Red Turban Rebellion during the Battle of Geochang. Across Europe, war and politics continued to transform nations. King Valdemar IV regained control of Danish Estonia after winning the Battle of Lindanise. In England, a bubonic plague outbreak killed an estimated 20% of the population. Advancements were made in science, art, and diplomacy, all helping to shape our history.

Year 1470 ( MCDLXX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was marked by significant events and occurrences throughout Europe and the world. During this year, the Treaty of Skipton between Scotland and England aimed to calm tensions along the borders, but distrust persisted. In France, the Burgundians launched a crusade against the remnants of the Ile-de-France, driving Louis XI to embrace military measures in the form of allies and weapons. In Central America, the Maya empire continued to decline while a resurgence in nomadic lifestyles flourished.

Sigismund (26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496), a member of the House of Habsburg, was Duke of Austria from 1439 (elevated to Archduke in 1477) until his death. As a scion of the Habsburg Leopoldian line, he ruled over Further Austria and the County of Tyrol from 1446 until his resignation in 1490.BiographySigismund (or Siegmund, sometimes also spelled Sigmund) was born at the Tyrolean court in Innsbruck; his parents were the Further Austrian duke Frederick IV of Austria and his second wife , a daughter of the Welf duke Frederick I of Brunswick-Lüneburg.

Frederick II of Brandenburg  (19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471), nicknamed "the Iron" (der Eiserne) and sometimes "Irontooth" (Eisenzahn), was a Prince-elector of the Margraviate of Brandenburg from 1440 until his abdication in 1470, and was a member of the House of Hohenzollern.BiographyFrederick II was born at Tangermünde Castle (German: Burg Tangermünde), when Tangermünde was within the Margraviate of Brandenburg, to Frederick I, Brandenburg's first Hohenzollern ruler, and his wife Elizabeth, daughter of Frederick, Duke of Bavaria-Landshut, and Maddalena Visconti.

Year 1029 ( MXXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this time, significant historical events and advancements took place. In Europe, many regions focused on growth and stability, fostering new connections through trade, agriculture, and politics. Byzantine Empire faced a resurgence, battling foes to re-establish lost territories. The power struggles in Eastern Asia unfolded between kingdoms, culminating in surprising military tactics and diplomacy. New insights emerged in philosophy, science, and technology, contributing to an important and dynamic period in human history.

Year 1391 ( MCCCXCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events that occurred during this year included the widespread anti-Jewish violence and persecution in Spain, known as the Massacre of 1391, which led to thousands of Jews being killed or forcibly converted to Christianity. In Asia, the war between the Timurid Empire and the Golden Horde continued to ravage the region, further destabilizing Central Asia. In England, a dispute between Richard II and several nobles, later called the "Merciless Parliament," intensified political tension, laying the groundwork for the Wars of the Roses.

Robert I Estienne (; 15037 September 1559), known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Stephens, was a 16th-century printer and classical scholar in Paris. He was the proprietor of the Estienne print shop after the death of his father Henri Estienne, the founder of the Estienne printing firm. Estienne published and republished many classical texts as well as Greek and Latin translations of the Bible. Known as "Printer to the King" in Latin, Hebrew, and Greek, Estienne's most prominent work was the Thesaurus linguae latinae which is considered to be the foundation of modern Latin lexicography.

Year 1375 ( MCCCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year marked significant milestones in the Late Middle Ages. In April, as Pope Gregory XI's papal legate to Italy, Cardinal Robert of Geneva took stern measures against the Guelphs in Bologna, attempting to calm the chaotic state of the city. The Union of Krewo, which ultimately united Lithuania and Poland under a common monarch, commenced as Jogaila married Jadwiga on October 18, giving rise to a pivotal personal union in the shaping of Eastern Europe's political landscape.

John the Apostle (;  ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to the New Testament. Generally listed as the youngest apostle, he was the son of Zebedee and Salome. His brother was James, who was another of the Twelve Apostles. The Church Fathers identify him as John the Evangelist, John of Patmos, John the Elder, and the Beloved Disciple, and testify that he outlived the remaining apostles and was the only one to die of natural causes, although modern scholars are divided on the veracity of these claims.

Sigismund ( 26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496 ) , a member of the House of Habsburg , was Duke of Austria from 1446 to 1490 and ruler of Tyrol and the Further Austrian estates from 1446 until his death. He played a significant role in European politics, building alliances across various regions and amassing territories through conquest, strategic marriages, and negotiation. Born in Vienna as the only son of Duke Frederick IV, Sigismund became known for his liberal reforms, focusing on supporting the arts and establishing fair policies for his citizens.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891 . It is used to produce high-voltage, low-current, and high-frequency alternating-current electricity. Tesla coils consist of a primary coil, which transfers energy to a secondary coil, creating the impressive electrical arcs and sparks commonly associated with these devices. Initially, Tesla's intention was to develop a wireless power transmission system through his "world wireless system" concept. While this idea was not fully realized, Tesla coils have found numerous applications in modern times such as high-voltage transformers, scientific demonstrations, radio transmitters, and entertainment in visual performances and exhibits.

Year 1233 (MCCXXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  War of the Lombards: Lombard forces at Kyrenia surrender to John of Beirut, after a 10-month siege. The defenders, with their personal belongings, are allowed to retire to Tyre. Prisoners captured, are exchanged for those held by Richard Filangieri, commander of the Lombards, at Tyre. Cyprus is wholly restored under the rule of the 16-year-old King Henry I (the Fat). His vassals are rewarded, and loans that they have made are repaid.

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic, waterways and railroads. All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil and gas pipelines are regulated by the Ministry of Transportation of Azerbaijan Republic. For Soviet transportation, see Transport in the Soviet Union.RailwaysThere are  of rail tracks out of which only  are in common carrier service and  are industrial lines. Total:  (2013)Country comparison to the world: 59Broad gauge:  gaugeRailway links with adjacent countriesTimelineMetro System Currently, the only metro system in Azerbaijan is the Baku Metro, located in Baku, the country's capital.New plans to open metro systems in the most populated and developed cities of Azerbaijan were unveiled.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking, locating, acquiring, organizing, cataloging, displaying, storing, and maintaining items that are of interest to an individual collector. Collections differ in a wide variety of respects, most obviously in the nature and scope of the objects contained, but also in purpose, presentation, and so forth. The range of possible subjects for a collection is practically unlimited, and collectors have realised a vast number of these possibilities in practice, although some are much more popular than others.In collections of manufactured items, the objects may be antique or simply collectable.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling ( ; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994 ) was a Swedish actress , novelist and film director. Born in Västerås, Sweden, she began her career as an actress in the late 1940s with several prominent roles in Swedish cinema. Zetterling gained international acclaim following her move to Britain in the 1950s, starring in popular films such as "Frieda" (1947) and "Only Two Can Play" (1962). As a director, she made a name for herself through thought-provoking feminist and socially conscious films like "Loving Couples" (1964) and "Night Games" (1966).

Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at the E Center in West Valley City and Peaks Ice Arena in Provo, Utah. The tournament featured both men's and women's competitions, attracting top players from around the world. The 2002 Winter Olympics were marked by excellent sportsmanship, thrilling matches, and high-level skills that awed fans and participants alike. Notably, in the men's tournament, Team Canada secured their first gold medal since 1952 after defeating Team USA, 5-2 in the finals, thus ending a 50-year drought.

The Cape Cod Canal is an artificial waterway in the U.S. state of Massachusetts connecting Cape Cod Bay in the north to Buzzards Bay in the south, spanning approximately 7 miles in length. It was constructed primarily to create a safer and shorter route for maritime traffic and help ships avoid the hazardous waters around Cape Cod. Completed in 1914, it has since become an integral part of the maritime industry and a popular destination for recreational boating and sightseeing, offering beautiful scenery and an array of parks and beaches on both sides of the canal.

The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom, British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds sterling (symbol "£"), and ranges in value from one penny to two pounds. Since decimalisation, on 15 February 1971, the pound has been divided into 100 (new) pence. Before decimalisation, twelve pence made a shilling, and twenty shillings made a pound. British coins are minted by the Royal Mint in Llantrisant, Wales. The Royal Mint also commissions the coins' designs.In addition to the circulating coinage, the UK also mints commemorative decimal coins (crowns) in the denomination of five pounds.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 1 – The Abenaki tribe and the Massachusetts colonists sign a treaty , ending the conflict between the two parties that had lasted for several years. The agreement outlines specific terms and territories, ensuring peaceful coexistence for the foreseeable future. January 18 – A large-scale revolt occurs in Southern Spain, known as the Andalusian Uprising, with peasants and townspeople rising up against unfair taxation policies imposed by local aristocrats. February 15 – Russia and Sweden enter into the Treaty of Nystad, concluding the Great Northern War and signifying a significant shift in the balance of power in Europe, with Russia emerging as a major player.

Year 1452 ( MCDLII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1452 marked significant events and achievements across the globe, ranging from discoveries in science, accomplishments in art, to developments in politics. In Europe, Italian artist and scientist Leonardo da Vinci was born, who would later become an influential figure during the Renaissance era. Pope Nicholas V issues a Papal Bull endorsing the enslavement of African populations, thus laying the groundwork for the trans-Atlantic slave trade.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde ( born 30 November 1971 ) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in the sprint distances. Van Velde was born in Wolvega, Friesland, and first rose to prominence when he secured multiple podium finishes at World Cup events in the 1990s. Despite early promise, a significant career breakthrough eluded him until 2002, when he won gold at the Salt Lake City Winter Olympics in the men's 1000 meters. Van Velde broke the world record and became the first Dutchman to win Olympic gold in speed skating since 1972.

Year 1335 (MCCCXXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 2 – Otto the Merry, Duke of Austria, becomes Duke of Carinthia. July 30 – Battle of Boroughmuir: John Randolph, 3rd Earl of Moray defeats Guy, Count of Namur in Scotland. November 30 – Battle of Culblean: David Bruce defeats Edward Balliol in Scotland. December 1 – Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan dies, a victim of the plague that ravages the Ilkhanate. This is an early outbreak of the Black Death.

Michelangelo Antonioni ( , ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007 ) was an Italian film director , screenwriter , editor, and author. Widely considered one of the greatest and most influential filmmakers in cinema history, Antonioni's career spanned six decades, during which he crafted visually striking and deeply introspective films. A key figure in postwar Italian cinema, Antonioni helped define the neorealism movement with his unique narrative style and attention to mood, psychology, and emotion in the portrayal of the human condition. Throughout his career, he earned numerous accolades, including the Golden Lion at Venice Film Festival and the Academy Award for Lifetime Achievement.

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack, such as the sheepshank. The sheepshank knot is not stable. It will fall apart under too much load or too little load.The knot has several features which allow a rope to be shortened: It provides two loops, one at each end of the knot which can be used to pass another rope through The knot remains somewhat secure under tension; the coarser the rope the more secure it is (see Disadvantages, below) The knot falls apart easily when tension is removedConstruction methods A sheepshank knot may be constructed as follows: ...

Otto III ( June/July 980 – 23 January 1002 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death in 1002. He was the son of Emperor Otto II and Empress Theophanu. As a teenager, Otto III was determined to rule his realm independently and revitalize the Empire, turning his sights on centralizing authority and restoring the Christian faith. He successfully undertook numerous expeditions against foreign foes and helped expand the Holy Roman Empire's territory. Despite his efforts, his short reign faced various internal conflicts, religious struggles, and external threats.

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped, facultatively anaerobic, motile, beta-hemolytic, spore-forming bacterium commonly found in soil, food and marine sponges. The specific name, cereus, meaning "waxy" in Latin, refers to the appearance of colonies grown on blood agar. Some strains are harmful to humans and cause foodborne illness, while other strains can be beneficial as probiotics for animals. The bacteria is classically contracted from fried rice dishes that have been sitting at room temperature for hours. B. cereus bacteria are facultative anaerobes, and like other members of the genus Bacillus, can produce protective endospores.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch (15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908) was a German humorist, poet, illustrator, and painter. He published wildly innovative illustrated tales that remain influential to this day.Busch drew on the tropes of folk humour as well as a profound knowledge of German literature and art to satirize contemporary life, any kind of piety, Catholicism, Philistinism, religious morality, bigotry, and moral uplift.His mastery of drawing and verse became deeply influential for future generations of comic artists and vernacular poets. Among many notable influences, The Katzenjammer Kids was inspired by Busch's Max and Moritz.

John Bunyan ( ; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688 ) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of the Christian allegory The Pilgrim's Progress. In addition to The Pilgrim's Progress, Bunyan wrote nearly sixty titles, many of them expanded sermons. Bunyan was born in Bedfordshire, England, to a modest family and experienced a deeply turbulent spiritual journey throughout his life. He served in the Parliamentary Army during the English Civil War before dedicating himself to a life of preaching, spiritual writings, and teaching.

arXiv (pronounced "archive"—the X represents the Greek letter chi [χ]) is an open-access repository of electronic preprints and postprints (known as e-prints) approved for posting after moderation, but not peer review. It consists of scientific papers in the fields of mathematics, physics, astronomy, electrical engineering, computer science, quantitative biology, statistics, mathematical finance and economics, which can be accessed online. In many fields of mathematics and physics, almost all scientific papers are self-archived on the arXiv repository before publication in a peer-reviewed journal.

Year 1145 (MCXLV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Seljuk forces led by Imad al-Din Zengi capture Saruj, the second great Crusader fortress east of the Euphrates. They advance to Birejik and besiege the city, but the garrison puts up a stiff resistance. Meanwhile, Queen-Regent Melisende of Jerusalem joins forces with Joscelin II, count of Edessa and approaches the city. Zengi raises the siege after hearing rumours of trouble in Mosul. He rushes back with his army to take control.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting , gluing , rearranging and overlapping two or more photographs into a new image. This artistic technique is often used in advertisements, digital media, and the entertainment industry, transforming and blending multiple elements into a seamless and visually striking representation. As a form of graphic design, photomontage serves to explore creative expression and communicate strong messages by amalgamating various photographic elements. Through juxtaposition, scaling, and recombination, it transcends conventional photography, enabling artists to push boundaries, challenge perspectives, and capture the essence of diverse ideas and emotions in a single, unique image.

In the performing arts, a scenario (, ; from Italian: "that which is pinned to the scenery", ) is a synoptical collage of an event or series of actions and events. In the commedia dell'arte it was an outline of entrances, exits, and action describing the plot of a play, and was literally pinned to the back of the scenery. It is also known as canovaccio  or "that which is pinned to the canvas" of which the scenery was constructed.Surviving scenarios from the Renaissance contain little other than character names, brief descriptions of action, and references to specific lazzi with no further explanation.

Year 1132 ( MCXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this remarkable year, events took place that shaped the course of history for years to come. Major occurrences included the founding of several new monastic communities and the rapid expansion of some European towns. Furthermore, advances in literature, arts, and the sciences took place, with numerous skilled craftsmen, poets, and scholars contributing significantly to this progressive atmosphere. Consequently, the year 1132 marked a period of noteworthy innovation and the dawning of new cultural perspectives across various domains.

Year 1539 ( MDXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1539, several significant events took place that shaped the course of history. Among them was the founding of St. Augustine in Florida by the Spanish, which would eventually become the oldest city in the United States. Furthermore, in England, King Henry VIII proclaimed the Dissolution of the Monasteries, leading to the redistribution of land and wealth amongst the aristocracy, greatly impacting religion and society. Meanwhile, Ottoman emperor Suleiman the Magnificent organized a grand expedition to spread influence over western Europe, ultimately capturing numerous territories.

Poltava ( , ; ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine . It is the administrative center of the Poltava Oblast (province) and the Poltava Raion (district) within the province. Founded in the 10th century, Poltava is known for its historical significance in Ukrainian history and culture, as well as its beautiful architecture and landmarks, such as the Octagonal Church and The White Arbor. With a population of approximately 296,000, Poltava is the seventh largest city in Ukraine, offering visitors and residents a vibrant city life rich in traditional music, art, and festivals.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (often referred to as the Four Horsemen) are figures in Christian religion, first appearing in the Old Testament's prophetic Book of Zechariah and in the Book of Ezekiel, where they are named as punishments from God, and later in the New Testament's final book, Revelation, an apocalypse written by John of Patmos.Revelation 6 tells of a book or scroll in God's right hand that is sealed with seven seals. The Lamb of God/Lion of Judah opens the first four of the seven seals, which summons four beings that ride out on white, red, black, and pale horses.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga, which are separated geographically by the Murray River and politically by a state border: Albury on the north of the river is part of New South Wales, while Wodonga on the south bank is in Victoria.History Albury-Wodonga is located on the lands of the Dyinningmiddhang people of the Dhudhuroa language group.In the early 1970s Albury–Wodonga was selected as the primary focus of the Whitlam Federal Labor government's scheme to arrest the uncontrolled growth of Australia's large metropolitan areas (in particular Sydney and Melbourne) by encouraging decentralisation.

A finite difference is a mathematical expression of the form . If a finite difference is divided by , one obtains a finite difference quotient. The concept of finite differences plays a crucial role in numerical analysis and approximation methods, especially when dealing with the derivation and integration of functions. Finite difference methods provide a way to calculate approximate values for a given function or equation without needing exact analytical solutions. This is especially useful in engineering, physics, and various applied sciences where differential equations often arise, and closed-form solutions are hard to obtain.

Year 1392 (MCCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 13 – An assassination attempt by Pierre de Craon against Olivier de Clisson, Constable of France, fails. August 5 General Yi Seong-gye crowns himself Taejo of Joseon, ending the Goryeo Dynasty in the Korean Peninsula, and establishing the Joseon Dynasty, which will last for more than 500 years. Charles VI of France (later known as "Charles the Mad") suffers a serious bout of psychosis, which will continue throughout his life.

Year 1378 ( MCCCLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked the beginning of a period characterized by important events across the realms of culture, politics, and science. This year saw the eruption of the Great Papal Schism within the Roman Catholic Church as rival factions emerged in support of two popes, Pope Urban VI and Pope Clement VII. The French Court moved from Paris to the city of Avignon, resulting in artistic growth, notably among Italian painters like Giacomo Puccini.

Stephen Arthur Cook,  (born December 14, 1939) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made major contributions to the fields of complexity theory and proof complexity. He is a university professor at the University of Toronto, Department of Computer Science and Department of Mathematics.BiographyCook received his bachelor's degree in 1961 from the University of Michigan, and his master's degree and Ph.D. from Harvard University, respectively in 1962 and 1966, from the Mathematics Department. He joined the University of California, Berkeley, mathematics department in 1966 as an assistant professor, and stayed there until 1970 when he was denied reappointment.

Moore 's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit ( IC ) doubles approximately every two years. This trend, which has persisted for more than five decades, was first coined in 1965 by Gordon E. Moore, co-founder of Intel. This significant increase in transistor count has led to exponential improvements in processing power, enabling major advances in computing technology and digital electronics. However, in recent years, Moore's Law has been approaching its physical limitations, leading researchers to explore alternative technologies like quantum computing, neuromorphic computing, and optical computing in the quest to continue advancements in computing capabilities.

Electroporation , or electropermeabilization , is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing various substances such as DNA, RNA, or drugs to be introduced into the cell. This technique is widely utilized in molecular biology, cell biology, and gene therapy research for purposes such as introducing specific genes or genetic material into target cells or promoting uptake of therapeutic drugs for cancer treatment. The main advantage of electroporation is its non-toxic nature, efficiency, and its capacity to process a large number of cells simultaneously.

Year 1181 ( MCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year was significant for multiple historical events, both in political and religious arenas. The year began with Pope Lucius III ruling the papacy, helping to shape Christianity in the European region. The notable marriage of Alexios Komnenos and Eudokia Angelina further strengthened the ties of powerful Byzantine Empire families. In Japan, civil war broke out between the ruling Heian Imperial Family and the insurgent Minamoto and Taira samurai clans, with Kyoto, the ancient capital, as the battleground.

Year 1031 (MXXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 20 – King Robert II (the Pious) dies at Melun, after a 35-year reign. He is succeeded by his 23-year-old son, Henry I, who becomes the sole ruler of France. Henry's mother, Queen dowager Constance of Arles, prefers her third son, Robert, as heir to the throne and, with the help of Count Odo II, begins a war against Henry.
