Year 1489 (MCDLXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 14 – The Queen of Cyprus, Catherine Cornaro, sells her kingdom to the Republic of Venice. March 26 – The Treaty of Medina del Campo between England and Spain includes provision for a marriage between Arthur, the son of King Henry VII of England, and Princess Catherine of Aragon.June 29 – King James IV grants Andrew, Lord Gray, the lands and Barony of Lundie in Scotland. July 17 – Delhi Sultanate: Sikandar Lodi succeeds Bahlul Khan Lodi as sultan.

Year 1484 ( MCDLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, significant events occurred across Europe and the world that shaped history. In Portugal, King John II endorsed the exploration of Africa's western coast, resulting in the advancement of knowledge in geography, as well as igniting the interest in trans-Atlantic explorations, eventually culminating in the discovery of the New World by Christopher Columbus a few years later. This leap year also saw Pope Innocent VIII issue a papal bull against witchcraft, heralding the notorious witch trials of the early modern period.

Dissociative identity disorder (DID), previously known as multiple personality disorder (MPD), is a mental disorder characterized by the maintenance of at least two distinct and relatively enduring personality states. The disorder is accompanied by memory gaps beyond what would be explained by ordinary memory issues. The personality states alternately show in a person's behavior; however, presentations of the disorder vary. Other conditions that often occur in people with DID include post-traumatic stress disorder, personality disorders (especially borderline and avoidant), depression, substance use disorders, conversion disorder, somatic symptom disorder, eating disorders, obsessive–compulsive disorder, and sleep disorders.

Year 1148 ( MCXLVIII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1148 was marked by a series of events that had significant impact on the politics and the economy of that time. Some of the major happenings during this period were:

The city of Tortosa, present-day Spain, was captured by the forces of the Second Crusade, who sought to retake lands lost to Muslims. European economic conditions began improving with the founding of Almazán in present-day Spain, while Africa's Carthaginians endured conflict during the failed Normandy invasion.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business , the methods for attaining those goals, and the time-frame for achieving them. It also includes details about the organization's background, management team, financial projections, market analysis, marketing strategy, and competition. A well-structured business plan serves as a blueprint for guiding business growth, attracting investors, securing funding, and monitoring progress. Regularly updating and adapting the plan is vital to ensure ongoing success as market conditions change, customer needs evolve, and new opportunities arise.

Year 1271 (MCCLXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 2 – Kings Otakar II of Bohemia and Stephen V of Hungary sign the first Peace of Pressburg, settling territorial claims, following the failed invasion of Hungary by Otakar II. September 1 – Pope Gregory X succeeds Pope Clement IV as the 184th pope, as the compromise candidate between French and Italian cardinals, ending a three-year conclave, the longest ever. The County of Toulouse is returned to the crown of France.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml) is a general-purpose, multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of ML with object-oriented features. OCaml was created in 1996 by Xavier Leroy, Jérôme Vouillon, Damien Doligez, Didier Rémy, Ascánder Suárez, and others.The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM). OCaml was initially developed in the context of automated theorem proving, and has an outsize presence in static analysis and formal methods software.

Year 1342 ( MCCCXLII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a time marked by various significant global events and milestones. In Europe, King Edward III claimed the French throne, escalating political tensions that led to the Hundred Years' War. Over in Asia, the Golden Horde experienced internal strife, weakening the once-dominant Mongol Empire. As arts and sciences flourished in the Islamic Golden Age, Timbuktu emerged as a prominent trade center in Africa, attracting scholars and merchants from afar.

Broca's area, or the Broca area (, also , ), is a region in the frontal lobe of the dominant hemisphere, usually the left, of the brain with functions linked to speech production.Language processing has been linked to Broca's area since Pierre Paul Broca reported impairments in two patients. They had lost the ability to speak after injury to the posterior inferior frontal gyrus (pars triangularis) (BA45) of the brain. Since then, the approximate region he identified has become known as Broca's area, and the deficit in language production as Broca's aphasia, also called expressive aphasia.

Robert I Estienne ( ; 15037 September 1559 ) , known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Stephens in English, was a prominent French printer, publisher, and classical scholar during the Renaissance. He was born into a family of prominent publishers and, as a young man, trained extensively under his father, Henri Estienne. After taking over the family business, Robert published numerous works including significant editions of the Greek New Testament and Hebrew Bible. His tireless work earned him the nickname "Parisianus" or "Princeps scholarum" among contemporaries, making him a leading figure in Renaissance learning and bookmaking.

Year 1433 (MCDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 31 – Sigismund is crowned Holy Roman Emperor in Rome. There has been no crowned Emperor since the death of his father, Charles IV, in 1378. August 14 – Edward I becomes King of Portugal. September – Cosimo de' Medici, later the de facto ruler of Florence and patron of Marsilio Ficino, is exiled by the Albizzi/Strozzi faction (Cosimo returns a year later, in September 1434).

Year 1207 ( MCCVII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( full calendar ) under the Julian calendar.Events In the year 1207 (MCCVII), a range of significant events occurred. The University of Cambridge was unofficially founded when scholars from the University of Oxford left due to disputes with the townspeople. Pope Innocent III, in an attempt to end a power struggle between secular and church authorities, placed England under an interdict - which effectively meant no Christian burials or church services could take place. Additionally, King Valdemar II of Denmark completed his conquest of Estonia, incorporating the region into the growing Danish Empire.

The Duchy of Anjou (, ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire. Its capital was Angers and it was roughly coextensive with the diocese of Angers. Anjou was bordered by Brittany to the west, Maine to the north, Touraine to the east and Poitou to the south. The adjectival form is Angevin, and inhabitants of Anjou are known as Angevins. In 1482, the duchy became part of the Kingdom of France, and from then remained a province of the Kingdom under the name of the Duchy of Anjou.

Blum Blum Shub (B.B.S.) is a pseudorandom number generator proposed in 1986 by Lenore Blum, Manuel Blum and Michael Shub that is derived from Michael O. Rabin's one-way function.Blum Blum Shub takes the form,where M = pq is the product of two large primes p and q. At each step of the algorithm, some output is derived from xn+1; the output is commonly either the bit parity of xn+1 or one or more of the least significant bits of x<sub>n+1</sub>.The seed x0 should be an integer that is co-prime to M (i.e.

Year 1390 ( MCCCXC ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. At the time, the European continent was undergoing significant socio-political changes. Power struggles among ruling families were frequent, often leading to territorial conflicts and war. This era was also witnessing a steady decline in the influence of the Catholic Church as various monarchs pursued centralization and consolidation of power. Advancements in science, arts, and literature marked the early stages of the Renaissance period. Moreover, increasing maritime exploration propelled technological innovation and contributed to economic development throughout the world.

The Zwinger  is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden, Germany. Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann, it is one of the most important buildings of the Baroque period in Germany. Along with the Frauenkirche, the Zwinger is the most famous architectural monument of Dresden. The name "Zwinger" goes back to the name used in the Middle Ages for a fortress part between the outer and inner fortress walls, even though the Zwinger no longer had a function corresponding to the name at the start of construction.The Zwinger was built in 1709 as an orangery and garden as well as a representative festival area.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Friday , one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar. As Swedes went about their daily lives, they were adapting to cultural, social, and technological changes. During this time, industrialization had started gaining momentum in the country, leading to increased urbanization and improved living standards for many citizens. Moreover, education reforms and gender equality movements made significant progress. Although much was achieved in this common year in Sweden, many traditions and customs remained, and a blend of old and new norms continued shaping the Swedish culture for years to come.

Mariner 3 (together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed and built by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) for NASA's Mariner-Mars 1964 project that were intended to conduct close-up (flyby) scientific observations of the planet Mars and transmit information on interplanetary space and the space surrounding Mars, televised images of the Martian surface and radio occultation data of spacecraft signals as affected by the Martian atmosphere back to Earth.Although the launch was initially successful, there was a separation issue and Mariner 3 stopped responding when its batteries ran out of power.

Year 1449 (MCDXLIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 6 – Constantine XI Palaiologos is crowned Byzantine Emperor at Mistra; he will be the last in a line of rulers that can be traced to the founding of Rome. February – Alexăndrel seizes the throne of Moldavia, with the support of the boyars. March 24 – Hundred Years' War: English capture Fougères in Brittany. April 7 – The last Antipope, Felix V, abdicates. April 19 – Pope Nicholas V is elected by the Council of Basel.

Georg Hackl (often named: Hackl Schorsch, ; born 9 September 1966) is a German former luger who was three time Olympic and World Champion. He is known affectionately as Hackl-Schorsch or as the Speeding Weißwurst a reference to what he looks like in his white bodysuit coming down the luge at fast speeds.BiographyHackl was born in Berchtesgaden, Bavaria. He took up luge as part of his physical education lessons whilst at school, learning to slide at the Königssee track.Hackl was known for his rivalry with Markus Prock, with Prock being dominant in World Cup competition whilst Hackl consistently achieved success at the Winter Olympics.

The African clawed frog (Xenopus laevis, also known as the xenopus, African clawed toad, African claw-toed frog or the platanna) is a species of African aquatic frog of the family Pipidae. Its name is derived from the three short claws on each hind foot, which it uses to tear apart its food. The word Xenopus means 'strange foot' and laevis means 'smooth'.The species is found throughout much of Sub-Saharan Africa (Nigeria and Sudan to South Africa), and in isolated, introduced populations in North America, South America, Europe, and Asia.

Year 1452 (MCDLII) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February – Alexăndrel retakes the throne of Moldavia, in his long struggle with Petru Aron. February 22 – William Douglas, 8th Earl of Douglas is killed by James II of Scotland, at Stirling Castle. March 17 – Reconquista – Battle of Los Alporchones (around the city of Lorca in Murcia): The combined forces of the Kingdom of Castile, and its subsidiary kingdom of Murcia, defeat the Emirate of Granada.

Year 1302 (MCCCII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 10 – The first meeting of the Estates General of the Kingdom of France is convened by Philip IV of France, at the Notre-Dame in Paris.May 18 – Bruges Matins: The French garrison in Bruges is massacred at night, by members of the local Flemish militia. June 12 – Rakvere, Estonia, receives Lübeck city rights. July 11 – Battle of the Golden Spurs (also called the Battle of Courtrai): the County of Flanders gains a major victory over the Kingdom of France.

The Tandy 1000 is the first in a line of IBM PC compatible home computer systems produced by the Tandy Corporation for sale in its Radio Shack and Radio Shack Computer Center chains of stores.OverviewIn December 1983, an executive with Tandy Corporation, maker of TRS-80 computers, said about the new IBM PCjr: "I'm sure a lot of people will be coming out with PCjr look-alikes. The market is big". While preparing the Tandy 2000—the company's first MS-DOS computer—for release in November 1983, Tandy began designing the Tandy 1000, code named "August".

Year 1513 (MDXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 9 – Pope Leo X (layman Giovanni di Lorenzo de' Medici) succeeds Pope Julius II, as the 217th pope, despite a strong challenge by Hungarian cardinal Tamás Bakócz. March 27 – Juan Ponce de León becomes the first European definitely known to sight Florida, mistaking it for another island. April 2 – Juan Ponce de León and his expedition become the first Europeans known to visit Florida, landing somewhere on the east coast.

Year 1198 ( MCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year was marked by significant events in politics, religion, and war. In politics, Pope Innocent III was elected and emerged as a powerful leader with considerable influence throughout Christendom. His strong ideals and emphasis on papal authority heavily shaped the medieval Catholic Church. Simultaneously, King Richard I of England returned from the Third Crusade and was subsequently captured in Austria, while ongoing conflicts between Christians and Muslims intensified during the Reconquista in Spain.

Frederick Barbarossa (1122 – 10 June 1190), also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor from 1155 until his death 35 years later. He was elected King of Germany at Frankfurt on 4 March 1152 and crowned in Aachen on 9 March 1152. He was crowned King of Italy on 24 April 1155 in Pavia and emperor by Pope Adrian IV on 18 June 1155 in Rome. Two years later, the term  ("holy") first appeared in a document in connection with his empire. He was later formally crowned King of Burgundy, at Arles on 30 June 1178.

Year 1201 (MCCI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  July 31 – John Komnenos the Fat, a Byzantine aristocrat, attempts to usurp the imperial throne; he is proclaimed emperor and crowned by Patriarch John X Kamateros, at Constantinople. Meanwhile, Emperor Alexios III Angelos, who resides in the Palace of Blachernae, dispatches a small force under Alexios Palaiologos, Alexios' son-in-law, who is regarded as his heir-apparent. With support of the Varangian Guard, John is overthrown and decapitated by the end of the day.

The picometre (international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures; SI symbol: pm) or picometer (American spelling) is a unit of length in the metric system, equal to , or one trillionth  of a metre, which is the SI base unit of length.The picometre is one thousandth of a nanometre ( nm), one millionth of a micrometre (also known as a micron), one billionth of a millimetre, and one trillionth of a metre. The symbol μμ was once used for it.

Year 1193 (MCXCIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  March 4 – Saladin (the Lion) dies of a fever at Damascus. The lands of the Ayyubid Dynasty of Syria and Egypt are split among his relatives. During his reign, he briefly unites the Muslim world, and drives the Crusaders out of Jerusalem to a narrow strip of coast. At the time of his death, Saladin has seventeen sons and one little daughter. Al-Afdal succeeds his father as ruler (emir) of Damascus, and inherits the headship of the Ayyubid family.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum . The disease affects the nervous system and can lead to muscle weakness, paralysis, and even death if left untreated. Botulism can occur in three main forms: foodborne botulism, wound botulism, and infant botulism. Symptoms include difficulty swallowing or speaking, facial weakness, blurred vision, and difficulty breathing. Proper food preservation methods, such as using pressure canning, can prevent foodborne botulism. Immediate treatment is crucial, often requiring antitoxin administration and intensive care.

Year 1233 ( MCCXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1233, significant events shaped both politics and culture. The Holy Roman Empire continued its conflicts in Europe as tensions with the papacy persisted. This period also witnessed the Spanish Reconquista as the Moors faced steady defeat, diminishing their control over the Iberian Peninsula. Additionally, new scientific and academic ideas emerged in notable institutions, contributing to important technological advancements. During this time, widespread architectural accomplishments displayed medieval splendor while formidable figures rose in the political sphere, guiding powerful dynasties to future prosperity.

Year 1051 ( MLI ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events marked this year, both at the global level and within individual kingdoms. King Macbeth of Scotland, known for his Shakespearean role, embarked on a pilgrimage to Rome, demonstrating religious devotion despite being marred in controversy. Further east, in the Byzantine Empire, constant strife prevailed as its army began defending its territories against renewed Pecheneg attacks. Tensions were also brewing among noble families in Western Europe as Henry I of France set about dismantling the county of Sens.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word "play" is from Middle English pleye, from Old English plæġ, pleġa, plæġa ("play, exercise; sport, game; drama, applause"). The word "wright" is an archaic English term for a craftsman or builder (as in a wheelwright or cartwright). The words combine to indicate a person who has "wrought" words, themes, and other elements into a dramatic form—a play. (The homophone with "write" is coincidental.

Mariner 2 ( Mariner-Venus 1962 ) , an American space probe to Venus , was the first robotic space probe to successfully conduct a flyby of another planet. Launched on August 27, 1962, by NASA, the mission aimed to gather scientific data on Venus and interplanetary space. Mariner 2 performed numerous measurements on its journey, such as temperature, magnetic fields, and solar particles. Upon reaching its destination on December 14, 1962, it discovered Venus had cooler cloud temperatures than expected and lacked a discernable magnetic field. The spacecraft continued transmitting data until January 3, 1963.

Year 1194 ( MCXCIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) In 1194, significant events shaped both politics and religion. It marked the triumphant return of Richard the Lionheart, King of England, after being imprisoned by Holy Roman Emperor Henry VI, as well as the consolidation of power by the Sultanate of Rum. This was also the year when Palermo's Cathedral and Oxford's Queen's College were founded, emphasizing the interplay between culture and religion. Despite numerous upheavals, this dynamic year facilitated advancements and the resurgence of leaders that shaped the course of medieval history.

New England Digital Corporation ( 1976–1993 ) was founded in Norwich , Vermont , and relocated to White River Junction in 1980. The company was renowned for their innovative products, including the cutting-edge Synclavier digital synthesizer and music workstation, which garnered the attention of notable musicians like Frank Zappa, Michael Jackson, and Sting. Despite its prestigious reputation, the rapid advancements in music technology during the early '90s posed several challenges for New England Digital Corporation. In 1993, due to mounting financial difficulties, the corporation was forced to declare bankruptcy, eventually dissolving and marking an end to its 17 years of contribution to the music industry.

Louis the Roman ( 7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365 ) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor Louis IV and his second wife, Margaret of Holland. He held the titles of Duke of Bavaria and Brandenburg and Count of Tyrol. Growing up in the tumultuous time of the late medieval period, Louis the Roman showed promise as a capable ruler and military commander. However, during his reign, he faced various challenges such as constant conflict with neighbouring states, power struggles within his territories, and tension with the papacy. Despite these hurdles, Louis worked tirelessly to secure his legacy and maintain stability throughout the realm.

Year 1490 ( MCDXC ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this notable year, important events occurred both in politics and culture. While in Spain, Queen Isabella I of Castile signed a decree on maritime policy for her colonies, strengthening their trade networks; in Asia, a rebellion arose in Korea known as the Yeonsangun, drastically changing the local power structure. Meanwhile, Leonardo da Vinci created his iconic "Vitruvian Man" in Italy, marking an important step for artistic understanding and cultural legacy.

Year 1343 ( MCCCXLIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked significant events, changes, and shifts in the world scene. At that time, much of Europe was recovering from the impact of the Great Famine (1315–1317). Feudal society was in decline and local power was expanding, with city-states and emerging nation-states exerting their influence. Among noteworthy occurrences were advancements in architecture, philosophy, literature, and art – largely fueled by the early stages of the Italian Renaissance.

Year 1022 (MXXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Battle of Svindax: The Byzantine army under Emperor Basil II defeats the Georgians at Svindax (modern Turkey). King George I is forced to negotiate a peace treaty, ending the Byzantine–Georgian wars. Summer – Nikephoros Phokas (Barytrachelos) conspires with the Byzantine general Nikephoros Xiphias against Basil II. The rebellion collapses and Xiphias assassinates Phokas. Europe  Spring – Emperor Henry II divides his army into three columns and descends through Rome onto Capua.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus ( ; Latin `` oak tree '' ) of the beech family, Fagaceae. There are approximately 600 known species of oaks, which can be found in various regions across the northern hemisphere, such as North America, Europe, and Asia. Oaks are characterized by their distinct leaves with lobate margins, and the production of hard acorns as their fruit. These deciduous or evergreen trees typically possess longevity and immense strength, making their wood highly valuable for numerous uses, including construction, furniture-making, and the manufacturing of barrels.

Year 1567 ( MDLXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1567 was marked by several key events and changes that shaped the course of history. Notably, Mary, Queen of Scots was forced to abdicate in July, paving the way for her one-year-old son James VI to succeed her as ruler of Scotland, later uniting the thrones of Scotland and England as James I. Meanwhile, the Eighty Years' War continued as Dutch rebels struggled for independence from Spain, and Ivan the Terrible's reign witnessed Russia experiencing unprecedented political turbulence.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest , described as the Varian Disaster by Roman historians , took place at modern -day Germany in September, 9 AD. During the battle, an alliance of Germanic tribes led by Arminius ambushed and decisively defeated three Roman legions commanded by Publius Quinctilius Varus. The devastating loss resulted in the Romans abandoning their plans to conquer the Germanic territories, a region which remained mostly outside Roman rule until Charlemagne's reign in the 8th century. Consequently, the battle left a significant long-term impact on European history, as it marked the establishment of the Rhine-Danube river boundary which later influenced the formation of nation-states in Europe.

Year 1038 (MXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Conrad II (the Elder) travels to Southern Italy and holds court in Troia. He orders Pandulf IV of Capua to restore the territories of Monte Cassino. Pandulf holes himself up in the fortress of Sant'Agata de' Goti, and dispatches tribute (300 lb of gold) and his son as hostage to Troia as a token of peace. Conrad accepts his offer, but the son escapes.

Adrian of Nicomedia ( also known as Hadrian ) or Saint Adrian ( , died 4 March 306 ) was a Herculian Guard of Emperor Galerius Maximian, who became a martyr for his conversion to Christianity. Initially charged with persecuting Christians under Roman law, Adrian was deeply touched by the faith and resilience of those facing martyrdom. Thus, he and his wife Natalia secretly converted to Christianity. Adrian was ultimately arrested for defying the emperor's orders and tortured for his newfound faith. On March 4, 306, Adrian was executed, solidifying his place as a saint and martyr in the early Christian Church.

The Quirinal Hill (; ;  ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome, at the north-east of the city center. It is the location of the official residence of the Italian head of state, who resides in the Quirinal Palace; by metonymy "the Quirinal" has come to stand for the Italian president. The Quirinal Palace has an extension of 1.2 million square feet.History According to Roman legend, the Quirinal Hill was the site of a small village of the Sabines, and king Titus Tatius would have lived there after the peace between Romans and Sabines.

A sifaka   is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates. The name of their family is an onomatopoeia of their characteristic "shi-fak" alarm call. Like all lemurs, they are found only on the island of Madagascar. All species of sifakas are threatened, ranging from endangered to critically endangered.Anatomy and physiology Sifakas are medium-sized indrids with a head and body length of  and a weight of . Their tail is just as long as their body, which differentiates them from the Indri. Their fur is long and silky, with coloration varying by species from yellowish-white to blackish-brown.

Samuel de Champlain ( ; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635 ) was a French colonist , navigator , cartographer, explorer, and diplomat who founded New France, laying the foundation for modern-day Canada. He established the settlement of Quebec City in 1608, serving as its administrator until his death in 1635. Known as the "Father of New France," Champlain navigated and explored the region extensively, notably discovering Lake Champlain in modern-day Vermont in 1609. His diplomatic efforts forged alliances with Indigenous peoples, vital for trade and the growth of New France.

Year 1515 (MDXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – Francis I of France is crowned (r. until 1547). May 13 – Mary Tudor, Queen of France, and Charles Brandon, 1st Duke of Suffolk, are officially married at Greenwich (near London). June 13 – Battle of Turnadag: The army of Ottoman sultan Selim I defeats the beylik of Dulkadir under Bozkurt of Dulkadir. July–December  July 2 – Manchester Grammar School is endowed by Hugh Oldham, the first free grammar school in England.

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate : genetics (nature) and environmental influences (nurture). Advocates of the nature argument claim that an individual's traits, behaviors, and personality are largely determined by their genetic makeup. On the other hand, proponents of the nurture side argue that it is external factors and experiences that play the crucial role in shaping who we are. Over the years, research in psychology and genetics has illuminated the complex interplay between both factors, making it difficult to separate one from the other.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in October 2013. The twelfth tropical cyclone and eleventh named storm of the well below-average 2013 Atlantic hurricane season, Karen originated from a tropical wave that departed from the west coast of Africa on September 16. After passing south of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands, the storm became a tropical cyclone to the northeast of the Yucatán Peninsula. The storm peaked shortly afterward, with 1-minute sustained winds of 65 mph (100 km/h).

Eleusine coracana , or finger millet , also known as ragi in India , kodo in Nepal , is an annual plant species widely cultivated in Asia and Africa. It is highly valued for its nutritional properties and climate resilience. This nutrient-dense grain is rich in proteins, fiber, vitamins, and minerals, especially calcium and iron, which makes it an ideal food for growing children and lactating mothers. It is also a popular ingredient in traditional recipes and serves as a vital dietary component in regions facing food insecurity. Finger millet is extremely versatile and can be ground into flour, brewed into beer, or eaten as a porridge.

Year 1373 (MCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 24 – The Treaty of Santarém is signed between Ferdinand I of Portugal and Henry II of Castile, ending the second war between the two countries. April 28 – Hundred Years' War: The French re-capture most of Brittany from the English, but are unable to take Brest. May 13 – English anchoress Dame Julian of Norwich receives the sixteen Revelations of Divine Love. June 16 – The Anglo-Portuguese Treaty is signed in London, and is the oldest active treaty in the world.

The Battle of Trafalgar ( 21 October 1805 ) was a naval engagement between the British Royal Navy and the combined fleets of the French and Spanish Navies during the War of the Third Coalition, which was part of the Napoleonic Wars. The battle took place near Cape Trafalgar, off the Spanish coast. British Admiral Lord Nelson, leading 27 British ships, clashed against French and Spanish forces composed of 33 ships under the French Admiral Villeneuve. Lord Nelson utilized an unconventional, aggressive tactic – known as the "Nelson touch" – effectively dividing the enemy fleet, forcing them to engage in separate fights.

Dissociative identity disorder ( DID ) , previously known as multiple personality disorder ( MPD ) , is a mental condition in which an individual exhibits two or more distinct personalities or identity states that may control their thoughts, feelings, and actions at different times. These alternating identity states are thought to develop as a coping mechanism in response to extreme childhood trauma or chronic abuse, serving as a way to disconnect from or suppress painful memories. People with DID may experience memory gaps, heightened anxiety, depression, and difficulties with social functioning, impacting their overall well-being.

Year 1145 ( MCXLV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events during this year included the beginning of the construction of the Bamberg Cathedral in Germany, under the patronage of Bishop Eberhard II. The powerful philosopher and scholar, Robert of Ketton, completed the first Latin translation of the Qur'an. In Iberia, the Spanish King Alfonso VII conquered the strategically significant town of Calatrava, which played a vital role in the subsequent military efforts of the Reconquista against the Almohads in Andalusia.

Year 1510 ( MDX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year marked several significant historical events across the globe. In Europe, the Republic of Venice and the Papal States allied against the rising power of the Ottoman Empire. Meanwhile, in the Americas, Spanish colonization was rapidly increasing as explorers ventured into new territories, leading to encounters with indigenous peoples. These explorations contributed to the establishment of key trading routes and paved the way for future political and cultural shifts.

In metaphysics, extension signifies both 'stretching out' (Latin: extensio) as well as later 'taking up space', and most recently, spreading one's internal mental cognition into the external world.The history of thinking about extension can be traced back at least to Archytas' spear analogy for the infinity of space. How far can one's hand or spear stretch out until it reaches the edge of reality? “If I arrived at the outermost edge of the heaven, could I extend my hand or staff into what is outside or not?

Year 1439 (MCDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 4 – Battle of Grotnik: Władysław III's royal army defeats the Hussite movement in Poland. June 29 – Date of Venerable Macarius' Miracle of the Moose, according to Russian hagiographers. July 6 – Pope Eugene IV issues the Bull of Union with the Greeks, proclaiming the end of the East–West Schism, which was repudiated by most eastern bishops shortly thereafter. September 8 – Cardinal Giovanni Vitelleschi captures Foligno, ending Trinci's signoria.

Stephen Arthur Cook , ( born December 14 , 1939 ) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made significant contributions to the fields of complexity theory and proof theory. Born in Buffalo, New York, Cook moved to Canada to further his academic pursuits. He is best known for formulating the concept of NP-completeness, a groundbreaking discovery that laid the foundation for understanding computational complexity. This achievement garnered him the prestigious Turing Award in 1982. Over the years, Cook has taught at prestigious institutions, such as the University of Toronto, and mentored a generation of scholars in theoretical computer science.

Events January–December February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna , ending the da Polenta Dynasty . In February, the Republic of Venice made a bold move to expand its territory by annexing the seigniory of Ravenna, effectively putting an end to the influential da Polenta Dynasty that had reigned supreme for centuries. As tensions in the Italian peninsula grew, other major political entities and city-states remained cautious and vigilant, keeping a watchful eye on the seemingly unstoppable power that was Venice. This strategic addition allowed Venice to enhance its military and economic control, reaffirming its status as a dominant player on the European stage.

Events  January–June  January–March – Archangelsk is founded as New Kholmogory in northern Russia, by Ivan the Terrible. January 11 – Sir Walter Mildmay is given a royal licence to found Emmanuel College, Cambridge. March 18 (N.S. March 28) – Ivan the Terrible, ruler of Russia since 1533, dies; he is succeeded as Tsar by his son, Feodor. May 17 – The conflict between Toyotomi Hideyoshi and Tokugawa Ieyasu culminates in the Battle of Nagakute. June 1 – With the death of the Duc d'Anjou, the Huguenot Henry of Navarre becomes heir-presumptive to the throne of France.

Year 1420 (MCDXX) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March – The Çelebi Sultan Mehmed Mosque in Didymoteicho is inaugurated. May 21 – Treaty of Troyes:  With the Burgundian faction dominant in France, King Charles VI of France acknowledges Henry V of England as his heir, and as virtual ruler of most of France. May 25 –  Henry the Navigator is appointed governor of the Portuguese Order of Christ. June 2 – Catherine of Valois marries King Henry V of England.

ext3 , or third extended filesystem , is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel . It was introduced in 1999 as an improvement to the earlier ext2 filesystem and quickly became the default file system in many Linux distributions. Ext3 brought notable enhancements, such as better performance, improved storage capacity, and the journaling feature, which improved the reliability and data integrity by recording changes to the filesystem in a special 'journal' before committing them to the main filesystem. Over time, ext3 was eventually succeeded by the ext4 file system, offering even more advanced features and optimizations for modern hardware, while maintaining backward compatibility.

Year 1150 ( MCL ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In 1150, notable events transpired across different parts of the world. In the Christian world, the religious leaders wrestled to exert influence on political powers. European realms battled for territories and dealt with diplomatic matters, while Asian kingdoms focused on trade, urbanization, and enhancing their art and technology. Furthermore, education underwent substantial progress with the development of universities in Bologna, Italy and Paris, France, emphasizing law, theology, and natural sciences, consequently molding the intellectual legacy of the Middle Ages.

Spiro Theodore Agnew ( November 9 , 1918 – September 17 , 1996 ) was the 39th vice president of the United States, serving from 1969 to 1973 under President Richard Nixon. Born in Baltimore, Maryland, Agnew attended Johns Hopkins University and graduated from the University of Baltimore School of Law. He later embarked on a career in politics, holding positions as the county executive of Baltimore County and the governor of Maryland. Despite his accomplishments, Agnew resigned as vice president in 1973 amidst allegations of tax evasion and political corruption.

Year 1525 (MDXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – The Swiss Anabaptist Movement is born when Conrad Grebel, Felix Manz, George Blaurock, and about a dozen others baptize each other in the home of Manz's mother on Neustadt-Gasse, Zürich, breaking a thousand-year tradition of church-state union. February 24 – Battle of Pavia: German and Spanish forces under Charles de Lannoy and the Marquis of Pescara defeat the French army, and capture Francis I of France, after his horse is wounded by Cesare Hercolani.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 16 – Francesco Morosini , the Doge of Venice since 1688 , dies after a brief illness. He is remembered for his successful military campaigns, including the defense against the Ottoman Empire and capturing key territories such as Morea. February 5 – Spain signs the Treaty of Den Haag with the Quadruple Alliance, composed of Great Britain, France, the Holy Roman Empire, and the Dutch Republic, effectively ending the War of the Quadruple Alliance that began in 1717. As part of the treaty, Spain agrees to abandon its aspirations in Italy and relinquish its conquests to their former owners.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE , FRAeS , ( 20 May 189511 June 1937 ) was a British aircraft designer who is best known for creating the legendary Supermarine Spitfire, a fighter aircraft that played a crucial role during World War II, particularly in the Battle of Britain. Mitchell's relentless dedication to excellence in aircraft design led to various groundbreaking developments, such as incorporating monocoque construction techniques and using the innovative Merlin engine, which vastly improved the aircraft's speed and maneuverability. Though Mitchell succumbed to cancer in 1937, his impact on the field of aviation and Britain's wartime effort is a lasting testament to his unmatched genius and legacy.

Year 1392 ( MCCCXCII ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a time of significant events and changes throughout Europe, the Middle East, and Asia. Some key moments included the establishment of Joseon dynasty in Korea by General Yi Seong-gye, and the outbreak of the Ghazanfarids-Djanbegids conflict in Persia, signaling shifting political and cultural dynamics in the region. During this period, literature and the arts also flourished with prominent scholars such as Geoffrey Chaucer beginning work on his celebrated English masterpiece, The Canterbury Tales.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman. Set in Hawaii, the show originally aired for 12 seasons from 1968 to 1980, and continues in reruns. At the airing of its last episode, it was the longest-running police drama in American television history and the last fictional primetime show that debuted in the 1960s to leave the air.The show starred Jack Lord as Detective Captain Stephen "Steve" McGarrett, the head of a special state police task force in Hawaii which was based on an actual unit that existed under martial law after  World War II.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE, FRAeS, (20 May 189511 June 1937) was a British aircraft designer who worked for the Southampton aviation company Supermarine from 1917 to 1936. He is best remembered for designing racing seaplanes such as the  Supermarine S.6B, and the Supermarine Spitfire.Born in Butt Lane, Staffordshire, Mitchell attended Hanley High School and afterwards worked as an apprentice at a locomotive engineering works, whilst also studying engineering and mathematics at night. In 1917 he joined Supermarine, where he was appointed Chief Engineer in 1920 and Technical Director in 1927.

Albert III ( 9 November 141411 March 1486 ) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death , the third member of the House of Hohenzollern to hold the position. As Elector, Albert III oversaw the reformation of Brandenburg, strengthening both its political and religious footing. Under his rule, Brandenburg witnessed significant growth in trade, stability, and prestige in the Holy Roman Empire. He was an influential supporter of Emperor Frederick III, and played a critical role in fostering a robust relationship between Brandenburg and other territories. The latter part of his reign was characterized by progressive reforms that eventually laid the foundation for Brandenburg-Prussia's future dominance.

Year 1486 ( MCDLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full Julian calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, numerous significant events shaped the world. The emergence of the age of exploration led to the enhancement of navigational and cartographical knowledge. Remarkable scientific achievements made this period progressive, leading to changes in several domains, like trade, politics, and cultural practices. Furthermore, due to technological advancements and scientific breakthroughs, international connections expanded, catalyzing developments across the globe, shaping this dynamic epoch into the beginning of an era with unparalleled global interaction.

Events  January–June  January 23 – The Triple Alliance of 1668 is formed between England, Sweden and the United Provinces. February 13 – In Lisbon, a peace treaty is established between Afonso VI of Portugal and Carlos II of Spain, by mediation of Charles II of England, in which the legitimacy of the Portuguese monarch is recognized. Portugal yields Ceuta to Spain. May 2 – The first Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle ends the War of Devolution. July–December  July 7 – Bishop Isaac Barrow founds the Bishop Barrow Trust with the intention of establishing a university on the Isle of Man; this becomes King William's College.

Year 1295 ( MCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year held many significant events that shaped the course of history. In Europe, Scotland and France solidified their alliance through the signing of the Treaty of Paris, also known as the Auld Alliance, ensuring mutual support against English aggression. The Eighth Crusade came to an end with King Louis IX of France, dying from dysentery after invading Tunis, making way for King Edward I of England to gain prominence on the European stage.

arXiv ( pronounced `` archive '' —the X represents the Greek letter chi [ χ ] ) is an open-access repository for electronic preprints (also known as e-prints) of scientific papers in the fields of mathematics, physics, astronomy, computer science, quantitative biology, statistics, and economics. Launched by Paul Ginsparg in 1991, arXiv is now hosted by Cornell University Library, and serves millions of scholars by offering a robust platform to upload, download and share articles with ease. The repository supports researchers globally by disseminating new ideas, fostering scientific collaborations and accelerating scholarly discovery, thereby advancing human knowledge and driving progress in numerous scientific disciplines.

Year 1355 ( MCCCLV ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Notable events during this year included the military campaign led by Edward of Woodstock, popularly known as the Black Prince, against the French during the Hundred Years War. Meanwhile in Central Asia, Toghan Temur, the last Khagan of the Mongol Empire's Yuan Dynasty, consolidated his reign despite ongoing conflicts with neighboring territories. Additionally, the Republic of Venice embarked on a journey of expansion, establishing outposts throughout the Mediterranean region.

Banksia is a genus of around 170 species in the plant family Proteaceae. These Australian wildflowers and popular garden plants are easily recognised by their characteristic flower spikes and fruiting "cones" and heads. Banksias range in size from prostrate woody shrubs to trees up to 30 metres (100 ft) tall. They are found in a wide variety of landscapes: sclerophyll forest, (occasionally) rainforest, shrubland, and some more arid landscapes, though not in Australia's deserts.Heavy producers of nectar, banksias are a vital part of the food chain in the Australian bush.

Johan August Arfwedson (12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841) was a  Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium in 1817 by isolating it as a salt.Life and work Arfwedson belonged to a wealthy bourgeois family, the son of the wholesale merchant and factory owner Jacob Arfwedson and his spouse, Anna Elisabeth Holtermann. The younger Arfwedson matriculated as a student at the University of Uppsala in 1803 (at the time, matriculating at a young age was common for aristocratic and wealthy students), completed a degree in Law in 1809 and a second degree in mineralogy in 1812.

Sigismund of Luxembourg (15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437) was a monarch who reigned as king of Hungary and Croatia from 1387, king of Germany from 1411, king of Bohemia from 1419, and Holy Roman Emperor from 1433 until his death in 1437, as well as prince-elector of Brandenburg (1378–1388 and 1411–1415). He was the last male member of the House of Luxembourg.Sigismund was born in Nuremberg, the son of Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV and Elizabeth of Pomerania. He married Queen Mary of Hungary in 1385 and was crowned King of Hungary soon after.

Year 1293 (MCCXCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By areaAfrica December – Mamluk sultan of Egypt Khalil is assassinated by his regent Baydara, who briefly claims the sultanate, before being assassinated himself by a rival political faction.Asia May 26 – An earthquake in Kamakura, Japan kills an estimated 23,000. May 31 – The forces of Raden Wijaya win a major victory in the Mongol invasion of Java, which is considered to be the founding date of the city of Surabaya. The Japanese era Shōō ends, and the Einin era begins.

Donnybrook is a district of Dublin , Ireland . It is situated on the southside of the city , in the Dublin 4 postal district. The area is renowned for its charming and picturesque scenery, rich history, and lively social scene. Donnybrook boasts an array of amenities including cafes, boutiques, parks, and schools, making it an attractive choice for residents and tourists alike. Its history can be traced back to the medieval times and over the years, it has witnessed numerous significant events, from its iconic fairs to 1916 Easter Rising.

Year 1532 ( MDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) In 1532, significant historical events unfolded throughout Europe and the Americas. On January 26, the city of Basel joined the Swiss cantons in a key development that expanded the Confederation's territory. A momentous exchange took place when Henry VIII decided to separate the Church of England from Rome on May 23. Meanwhile, a colossal invasion by Spanish conquistadors led by Francisco Pizarro began on September 13, with the attack on Tumbes in the Inca Empire.

Lead azide   is an inorganic compound. More so than other azides,  is explosive. It is used in detonators to initiate secondary explosives. In a commercially usable form, it is a white to buff powder.Preparation and handlingLead azide is prepared by the reaction of sodium azide and lead(II) nitrate in aqueous solution. Lead acetate can also be used.Thickeners such as dextrin or polyvinyl alcohol are often added to the solution to stabilize the precipitated product. In fact, it is normally shipped in a dextrinated solution that lowers its sensitivity.Production historyLead azide in its pure form was first prepared by Theodor Curtius in 1891.

Abolitionism, or the abolitionist movement, was the movement to end slavery. In Western Europe and the Americas, abolitionism was a historic movement that sought to end the Atlantic slave trade and liberate the enslaved people.The British abolitionist movement started in the late 18th century when English and American Quakers began to question the morality of slavery. James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament, and eventually encouraging his friends Granville Sharp and Hannah More to vigorously pursue the cause.

EventsJanuary–March  January 1 – Prince Muhammad Akbar, son of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb, initiates a civil war in India. With the support of troops from the Rajput states, Akbar declares himself the new Mughal Emperor and prepares to fight his father, but is ultimately defeated. January 3 – The Treaty of Bakhchisarai is signed, between the Ottoman vassal Crimean Khanate and the Russian Empire. January 18 – The "Exclusion Bill Parliament", summoned by King Charles II of England in October, is dissolved after three months, with directions that new elections be held at that a new parliament be convened in March in Oxford.

Year 1349 ( MCCCXLIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a year marked by significant events worldwide, such as the bubonic plague or the Black Death ravaging across Europe and devastating its population. The economic and social turmoil led to major changes in politics and culture, notably in art and literature. The plague forced the cessation of the Hundred Years' War between France and England temporarily. The Eastern world witnessed a prolonged confrontation, where the Ottoman Empire launched invasions to expand its territories, shaping history for centuries to come.

It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral exactly once (1000(M)+500(D)+100(C)+50(L)+10(X)+(-1(I)+5(V)) = 1664).Events  January–June  January 5 – Battle of Surat: Maratha Chhatrapati Shivaji defeats Mughal captain Inayat Khan, and sacks Surat. May 9 – Robert Hooke discovers Jupiter's Great Red Spot. June – Gazzetta di Mantova is first published in Mantua, Italy. It's the world's oldest private newspaper still published, and the oldest continuously published in print.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray, which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Sedley amid their friends and families during and after the Napoleonic Wars. It was first published as a 19-volume monthly serial from 1847 to 1848, carrying the subtitle Pen and Pencil Sketches of English Society, which reflects both its satirisation of early 19th-century British society and the many illustrations drawn by Thackeray to accompany the text. It was published as a single volume in 1848 with the subtitle A Novel without a Hero, reflecting Thackeray's interest in deconstructing his era's conventions regarding literary heroism.

The Polish People 's Party ( , PSL ) is an agrarian political party in Poland . It is currently the third-largest party in the Polish parliament, holding a considerable number of seats in the Sejm and the Senate. Established in 1990, PSL advocates for rural development, social justice, and sustainable agriculture. It mainly represents the interests of farmers and residents of small towns and villages in Poland. The PSL maintains a centrist position in Polish politics, promoting both conservative and liberal policies, and has formed various coalition governments with different parties in its history, thus illustrating its capacity for collaboration and adaptability.

Year 1231 (MCCXXXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Frederick II promulgates the Constitutions of Melfi (Liber Augustalis), a collection of laws for Sicily, as well as the edict of Salerno, regulating the exercise of medicine and separating the professions of physician and apothecary, and requiring medical schools to practice dissection. Castillan forces under King Ferdinand III (the Saint) re-conquer the city of Quesada. Battle of Jerez: Ferdinand III defeats Emir Ibn Hud of the Taifa of Murcia.

Alpine skiing, or downhill skiing, is the pastime of sliding down snow-covered slopes on skis with fixed-heel bindings, unlike other types of skiing (cross-country, Telemark, or ski jumping), which use skis with free-heel bindings. Whether for recreation or for sport, it is typically practiced at ski resorts, which provide such services as ski lifts, artificial snow making, snow grooming, restaurants, and ski patrol. "Off-piste" skiers—those skiing outside ski area boundaries—may employ snowmobiles, helicopters or snowcats to deliver them to the top of a slope.

Year 1239 (MCCXXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – A German expeditionary force under Emperor Frederick II invades the Romagna and Tuscany, hoping to capture Rome. He appoints his 21-year-old son, Enzo of Sardinia, as imperial vicar general for Northern Italy. Frederick also threatens with war against Venice, who has sent ships to blockade the harbors on Sicily. In order to finance his growing need for arms, he institutes an administrative reorganization of the Holy Roman Empire (among others, the formation of 10 vice regencies in Italy).

Events January–June January 11 – The Cortes of Castile approves a new subsidy , the millones . March – Maurice of Nassau becomes stadtholder of Zeeland and Holland. March 3 – James I of England creates the position of Poet Laureate, naming Ben Jonson as the first recipient. April 25 – Portuguese explorer Pedro Álvares Cabral lands on the coast of Brazil and claims it for the Kingdom of Portugal, initiating Portuguese colonial presence in South America. May 1 – Tokugawa Ieyasu becomes the de facto leader of Japan as Shōgun, centralizing his rule and beginning the Tokugawa shogunate that would last until 1868.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC . During this period, significant developments occurred in various civilizations worldwide. Some notable events include the rise of powerful kingdoms, such as the Neo-Assyrian Empire, which flourished in the Near East region under great rulers like Adad-nirari II, Tiglath-Pileser III, and Sargon II. In Greece, the early city-states started taking form and developing, marking the transition from the Dark Ages to the Archaic period. Simultaneously, cultures like the Olmecs in present-day Mexico began to establish intricate cities and artistic expressions that have significantly influenced later civilizations.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking . They may be eaten while ripe or unripe and are generally starchy. In contrast to dessert bananas, cooking bananas are more versatile in culinary applications due to their firmer and less sweet flesh. They are commonly referred to as plantains or green bananas in different regions across the world. The most common usage of cooking bananas involves frying, boiling, baking, or grilling them to make various delicious dishes. Some popular recipes include savory snacks like tostones and sweet dishes like banana fritters.

Events  January–June  January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas: The Portuguese beat the Spanish. January 24 – Pierre Corneille's Oedipe premieres in Paris. February 2 – Jan van Riebeeck produces the first South African wine, at the Cape of Good Hope. February 11 – The Assault on Copenhagen by Swedish forces is beaten back, with heavy losses. February 16 – The first known cheque (400 pounds) is written. April 22 – Lord Protector Richard Cromwell dissolves the English Parliament. May 21 – The Kingdom of France, the Commonwealth of England and the Dutch Republic sign the Concert of The Hague.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus . It focuses on the pursuit of pleasure and personal happiness, often through moderation and detachment from worldly desires. At its core, Epicureanism asserts that happiness is attainable by finding a balance between mental and physical well-being, specifically by acquiring knowledge, forming friendships, avoiding negative emotions, and limiting desires. The core of the belief revolves around the concept of "ataraxia" - achieving inner peace by accepting and learning from natural occurrences.

Year 1217 (MCCXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Fifth Crusade  Summer – Various groups of French knights reach the Italian ports. King Andrew II of Hungary arrives with his army in Split, in Dalmatia. He is joined by German forces, led by Duke Leopold VI (the Glorious). At the end of July, Pope Honorius III orders the crusaders assembled in Italy and Sicily to proceed to Cyprus, but there is no transport provided by the Italian city-states, Venice, Genoa and Pisa.

Year 1347 ( MCCCXLVII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a time when significant social and cultural transformations were unfolding across Europe. The Black Death pandemic arrived, eventually claiming over 50 million lives and shifting the course of history. Meanwhile, kingdoms and city-states forged new alliances as the Hundred Years' War continued to dominate regional politics. Trade flourished along the Silk Road, bringing knowledge and goods from Asia to Europe. In science and the arts, it was an age of intellectual exploration that set the stage for the upcoming Renaissance.

Digital electronics  is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use or produce them. This is in contrast to analog electronics and analog signals.Digital electronic circuits are usually made from large assemblies of logic gates, often packaged in integrated circuits. Complex devices may have simple electronic representations of Boolean logic functions.HistoryThe binary number system was refined by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (published in 1705) and he also established that by using the binary system, the principles of arithmetic and logic could be joined. Digital logic as we know it was the brain-child of George Boole in the mid 19th century.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Tuesday , one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar. Sweden had officially adopted the Julian calendar in 1700, and it was to be an exciting time as plans were being made for a significant shift to the more precise Gregorian calendar, established in 1582 by Pope Gregory XIII. As the days of the year continued, the citizens eagerly anticipated and prepared for this change. This leap, however, brought forth numerous concerns as society endeavored to maintain accurate historical, religious, and social events.

The Hubble Space Telescope ( often referred to as HST or Hubble ) is a space telescope that was launched into Earth's orbit in April 1990. Named after astronomer Edwin Hubble, it has significantly impacted the field of astronomy, providing unparalleled insights into the cosmos. Unlike ground-based telescopes, Hubble avoids the distortion caused by Earth's atmosphere, producing high-resolution images of deep space. Over the past three decades, the HST has made many breakthrough discoveries, including determining the rate of the universe's expansion and capturing stunning visuals of faraway galaxies.

Mariner 3 ( together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964 ) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed by NASA to study Mars and its atmosphere, providing vital data on the Red Planet. Launched on November 5, 1964, Mariner 3 was intended to perform a flyby mission to capture images and scientific readings to better understand Martian geology and meteorology. However, due to a technical malfunction during launch, the spacecraft's protective shroud failed to eject properly. As a result, Mariner 3 could not generate enough power for its journey to Mars and lost contact with Earth, making it an unsuccessful mission.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation . It commonly consists of a magnetic needle or a freely moving magnetized component, often a card that is balanced on a pivot. The magnetic needle or card aligns itself with the Earth's magnetic field, which allows the user to determine the direction of magnetic north, and from there, the four cardinal directions: north, south, east, and west. Apart from their widespread use in outdoor activities like hiking and camping, compasses are integral tools for mariners and aviation personnel.

Year 1056 (MLVI) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 31 – Empress Theodora (a sister of the former Empress Zoë) dies after a 18-month reign, by a sudden illness at Constantinople. She is succeeded by Michael VI (the Old), who had served as military finance minister under the former Emperor Romanos III. Michael is appointed through the influence of Leo Paraspondylos, Theodora's most trusted adviser. This ends the Macedonian Dynasty.

Events  January–December  February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna, ending the da Polenta Dynasty. February 12 – King's College, Cambridge, is founded by King Henry VI of England. March 1 – Battle of Samobor: The army of Ulrich II, Count of Celje, defeats the army of Stjepan Banić at Samobor, Croatia in union with Hungary. November 10 – Alfonso V of Aragon lays siege to Naples. November 20 – The Peace of Cremona (1441) ends the war between the Republic of Venice and the Duchy of Milan.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc . Developed in 1999, it provided a significant breakthrough for the free software and digital rights communities, by enabling users to legally bypass copyright protections and access digital content. Its creation also fueled controversies about copyright infringement and led to numerous legal battles. While the debate rages on, DeCSS serves as an essential tool for content access, stimulating conversation about the rights of consumers to legally and ethically utilize multimedia material without fear of repercussions.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc. Before the release of DeCSS, open source operating systems (such as BSD and Linux) could not play encrypted video DVDs.DeCSS's development was done without a license from the DVD Copy Control Association (CCA), the organization responsible for DVD copy protection—namely, the Content Scramble System (CSS) used by commercial DVD publishers. The release of DeCSS resulted in a Norwegian criminal trial and subsequent acquittal of one of the authors of DeCSS.

Year 1047 ( MXLVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the year 1047, several significant events occurred that had a lasting impact on global history. Europe witnessed power struggles, leading to a dramatic shift in political dynamics. England experienced the tumultuous reign of Edward the Confessor, a decisive force in shaping English history. Elsewhere, many famous cultural and religious landmarks were established, such as the Abbey of Cluny in France, showcasing the stunning Romanesque architecture prevalent during this time.

Events January–June January 20 – Russo-Polish War ( 1654–1667 ) : Poland cedes Kiev , Smolensk , and eastern Ukraine to Russia in the Treaty of Andrusovo, ending the thirteen-year conflict. The successful outcome for the Tsardom of Russia results in significant territorial gains, and helps to further establish Russia as a growing regional power in Eastern Europe. Meanwhile, Poland faces the prospect of further internal turmoil, having been significantly weakened both territorially and economically as a result of the protracted war. As power dynamics begin to shift, smaller nations caught between these emerging forces prepare themselves for a rapidly changing geopolitical landscape.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets . The series originally aired from 1976 to 1981 and quickly gained a massive fan base for its unique blend of wit, charm, and musical numbers. With unforgettable characters such as Kermit the Frog, Miss Piggy, Fozzie Bear, and Gonzo, the show often included appearances by notable guest stars like Elton John, Steve Martin, and Julie Andrews. In its 120 episodes, The Muppet Show brilliantly bridged the gap between children's programming and adult humor, leaving a lasting legacy on the worlds of comedy and entertainment for generations to come.

All figure skating events in 2002 Winter Olympics were held at the Salt Lake Ice Center.Medal summaryMedal tableMedalistsResultsMenMedals awarded Thursday , February 14, at the Salt Lake Ice Center. Gold: Alexei Yagudin (Russia)
Silver: Evgeni Plushenko (Russia)
Bronze: Timothy Goebel (USA)

Women
Medals awarded Thursday, February 21, at the Salt Lake Ice Center. Gold: Sarah Hughes (USA)
Silver: Irina Slutskaya (Russia)
Bronze: Michelle Kwan (USA)

Pairs
Medals awarded Monday, February 11, at the Salt Lake Ice Center.

Juggling is a physical skill , performed by a juggler , involving the manipulation of objects for recreation , entertainment , or artistic expression. This captivating art form requires exceptional hand-eye coordination, balance, and concentration. A juggler usually handles multiple objects, such as balls, rings, or clubs, and skillfully tosses and catches them in continuous patterns. Popular tricks include the basic cascade, the shower, and the more advanced siteswap. Besides being a popular street performance and circus act, juggling is often showcased in variety shows and festivals.

Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is , to distinguish or to inflect words. All languages use tone to varying degrees to convey meaning or emotion. For example, in tonal languages like Mandarin Chinese, pitch can drastically change the meaning of a word, while in non-tonal languages like English, tone mainly serves to convey emphasis or emotions. Intonation, a part of tone, plays an important role in creating coherence in language by helping in identifying questions, exclamations, or declarations. Accurately perceiving and using tone is vital for clear and effective communication across different languages and cultures.

Year 1501 ( MDI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a period marked by notable events, cultural changes, and advancements in various fields. Some significant events included the voyages of Christopher Columbus and other explorers, who discovered and charted new lands and opened the way for future explorations. Additionally, during this time, great strides were made in the realms of art, architecture, and science, most notably with the famous Italian master Leonardo da Vinci painting the renowned masterpiece "The Last Supper."

Year 1207 (MCCVII) was a common year starting on Monday (full calendar) under the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Siege of Attalia: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I besiege the city port of Attalia (modern-day Antalya) with siege machines. After a siege of more than 2 months, the city is captured, Kaykhusraw allows his forces 3-day looting and slaughtering. The capture of the port gives the Seljuk Turks a major path into the Mediterranean. September 4 – Battle of Messinopolis: Latin forces under Boniface of Montferrat are ambushed and defeated at Messinopolis.

Year 1384 ( MCCCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1384 (MCCCLXXXIV), a leap year starting on Friday, many significant events occurred across different countries, changing the course of history. Rulers rose and fell, and alliances shifted. Trade prospered and cultural movements grew. It was a dynamic period with new developments in various fields such as technology, philosophy, art, and architecture. To explore more in detail, the full calendar provides insights into daily occurrences and gives a better understanding of this period.

Year 1271 ( MCCLXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events unfolded throughout the world that year. The stage was set for a turning point in medieval history, as numerous key developments shaped the politics and cultural landscape of that time. Major highlights include Marco Polo's historic journey to Asia, which expanded global connections and began an era of cultural exchange. This same year saw the establishment of Lithuania's city, Klaipėda, and important strides in astronomy through the introduction of astronomical tables in Paris, thereby revolutionizing astronomical understanding.

Year 1538 ( MDXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Notable events from this year included the expansion of the Ottoman Empire in Europe, capturing Buda from the Hungarians, leading to a period of 150 years of Turkish occupation. Meanwhile, Spanish conquistador Gonzalo Jiménez de Quesada discovered the Magdalena River and navigated through it, giving rise to Colombia. Additionally, amidst the spread of the Protestant Reformation, Catholic King Henry VIII ordered all churches across England to adopt English translations of the Bible, forever altering religious life and scripture in the country.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold , Suffolk , England , by George and Ernest Adnams . Over the years, Adnams has become known for their high-quality beers, spirits, and award-winning pubs. They pride themselves on blending traditional brewing methods with innovative technology, resulting in unique and consistently excellent brews. A prime example of their progressive ethos is Adnams' modern, environmentally-conscious brewery, designed to reduce its carbon footprint and waste. Now run by the fourth generation of Adnams family members, the brand has managed to maintain its commitment to heritage while keeping an eye on sustainable innovation, ensuring their well-loved legacy thrives.

Adrian of Nicomedia (also known as Hadrian) or Saint Adrian (, died 4 March 306) was a Herculian Guard of the Roman Emperor Galerius Maximian. After becoming a convert to Christianity with his wife Natalia (Ναταλία), Adrian was martyred at Nicomedia in Asia-Minor             (Turkey). Hadrian was the chief military saint of Northern Europe for many ages, second only to Saint George, and is much revered in Flanders, Germany and the north of France.MartyrdomAdrian and Natalia lived in Nicomedia during the time of Emperor Maximian in the early fourth century.

Year 1230 ( MCCXXX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events in 1230 included the conclusion of the Mongol invasion of the Khwarazmian Empire led by Genghis Khan, leading to its eventual collapse. The growing trade between Europe and Asia via the Silk Road thrived under the Pax Mongolica. Also in Europe, various territories evolved towards becoming recognizable nation-states. These included the Holy Roman Empire's Germany, France, England, and Spain, along with Papal interference in regional politics.

Year 1395 (MCCCXCV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1395th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 395th year of the 2nd millennium, the 95th year of the 14th century, and the 6th year of the 1390s decade.Events  January–December  February 12 – The army led by Sigismund of Luxembourg is ambushed by Stephen I of Moldavia, on its way back after conquering Neamț Citadel, and the Hungarians must retreat empty handed.

Year 1340 ( MCCCXL ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In 1340, various significant events shaped the world, particularly in Europe and Asia. England and France were engaged in the Hundred Years' War, causing turmoil and unrest on the continent. Additionally, the Golden Horde, a vast Mongol-Tatar state, was facing the rising powers of the Khanates, ultimately resulting in the Battle of Velbazhd. These events dramatically altered the course of the middle ages, as dynasties, societies, and borders shifted in response to these monumental episodes of history.

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow , twisting , banked , iced tracks in a gravity-powered sleigh. Teams consist of two or four members who must work in unison to achieve maximum speed while steering the sled with precision. Races typically begin with athletes pushing the sleigh before quickly boarding it as they navigate their way down the track. Skillful coordination, agility, and strong teamwork are essential to excel in this high-speed adrenaline-pumping sport. Bobsleigh is highly popular in the Winter Olympics, capturing the excitement and passion of millions of spectators worldwide.

Year 1375 (MCCCLXXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 14 – The Mamluks from Egypt complete their conquest of the Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia. Levon V Lusignan of Armenia is imprisoned for several years in Cairo, until a ransom is paid by King John I of Castile. April 21 – Mujahid Shah succeeds his father, Mohammed Shah I, as ruler of the Bahmani Sultanate in the Deccan Plateau of southern India. June 18 – The future King John I of Castile marries Eleanor of Aragon.

Year 1358 (MCCCLVIII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 18 – Treaty of Zadar, between Louis I of Hungary/Croatia and the Republic of Venice: The Venetians lose influence over their former Dalmatian holdings. March 16 – King Haakon VI of Norway designates the city of Skien as a city with trading privileges, making it the sixth town with city status in the Norway.
