May 28 – Hundred Years' War – The Jacquerie: A peasant rebellion begins in France, which consumes the Beauvais, and allies with Étienne Marcel's seizure of Paris.

Year 1422 ( MCDXXII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this pivotal year, significant political, religious, and social events were shaping Europe and its surrounding regions. The Hundred Years' War, a longstanding conflict between England and France, witnessed the accession of King Charles VII after the sudden passing of King Henry V. Meanwhile, the 15th-century Renaissance was ushering in the age of exploration, and the Ottoman Empire's territorial expansions under Sultan Murad II brought about more clashes with Byzantine and Venetian powers.

Year 1516 (MDXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Juan Díaz de Solís discovers the Río de la Plata (in future Argentina). January 23 – With the death of Ferdinand II of Aragon, his grandson, Charles of Ghent, becomes King of Spain; his mother Queen Joanna of Castile also succeeds as Queen of Aragon and co-monarch with Carlos, but remains confined at Tordesillas. March 1 – Desiderius Erasmus publishes a new Greek edition of the New Testament, Novum Instrumentum omne, in Basel.

Wenceslaus IV ( also Wenceslas ; ; , nicknamed `` the Idle '' ; 26 February 136116 August 1419 ) was a King of Bohemia and, as Wenceslaus I, the Holy Roman Emperor, ruling from 1378 until his death in 1419. Despite his initial popularity, Wenceslaus ultimately earned the nickname "the Idle" due to his passive rule and frequent conflicts with powerful nobles in his domain. A weak ruler, he failed to maintain royal authority during the ecclesiastical and political crisis that unfolded in the early 15th century, later known as the Western Schism.

Dyson 's eternal intelligence concept ( the Dyson Scenario ) , proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979 , proposes a means by which advanced civilizations can perpetually harness energy to sustain intelligence indefinitely in a universe that is ever-expanding and cooling down. According to Dyson, this can be achieved by leveraging the energy resources available in a civilization's vicinity and incrementally reducing energy consumption to match the available supply, thus stalling the threat of energy scarcity. The Dyson Scenario requires significant advancements in technology and continuous innovation to adjust energy use patterns, adapt to evolving external conditions, and maintain perpetual growth of information-processing capabilities.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking , locating , acquiring , organizing , cataloging , displaying , storing , and maintaining items that are of interest to the collector. Collectors often have diverse tastes, focusing on various categories such as coins, stamps, dolls, vintage cars, and other unique memorabilia. They spend their free time researching and attending events, such as auctions or trade shows, in order to add new items to their collections. Over time, a collector's pursuit may lead to expertise and connoisseurship, as well as increased social connections and involvement in clubs or organizations.

Year 1384 (MCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May – September 3 – Siege of Lisbon by the Castilian army, during the 1383–85 Crisis in Portugal. August 16 – The Hongwu Emperor of Ming China hears a case of a couple who tore paper money notes, while fighting over them. Under the law, this is considered to be destroying stamped government documents, which is to be punished by a caning with a bamboo rod of 100 strokes. However, the Emperor decides to pardon them, on the grounds that it was unintentional.

Year 1379 ( MCCCLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. At this time, significant power struggles emerged among various regions, leading to the expansion of the Catholic Church, especially in England. Furthermore, notable alliances and diplomatic endeavors were formed between various rulers such as Venice, Brabant, France, and several Holy Roman Empire territories. Advancements in architecture and cultural celebrations marked this era with the initiation of The Italian Carnival tradition. Meanwhile, the arts flourished in Central Asia with famed painter Muhammad Siyah Qalam emerging as a pioneering talent.

Frederick II of Brandenburg ( 19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471 ) , nicknamed `` the Iron '' ( der Eiserne) and "the Irontooth" (der Eisenzahn), was a powerful ruler in the Holy Roman Empire during the 15th century. As a member of the House of Hohenzollern, he diligently worked to strengthen and expand his realm. With skillful diplomacy and military strength, Frederick consolidated the family's holdings in the northern German territories, solidifying the power and influence of Brandenburg in European politics. His leadership set the stage for his successors to propel the region further onto the path toward eventual Prussian hegemony in northern Germany.

McLean Hospital  (formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont, Massachusetts. It is noted for its clinical staff expertise and neuroscience research and is also known for the large number of famous people who have been treated there. McLean maintains the world's largest neuroscientific and psychiatric research program in a private hospital. It is the largest psychiatric facility of Harvard Medical School, an affiliate of Massachusetts General Hospital, and part of Mass General Brigham, which also includes Brigham and Women's Hospital.History McLean was founded in 1811 in a section of Charlestown, Massachusetts that is now a part of Somerville, Massachusetts.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde (born 30 November 1971) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in sprinting. He won an Olympic gold medal in 2002.BiographyVan Velde was considered the best Dutch sprinter during the early 1990s, but did not manage to win a medal in either the 1992 or 1994 Winter Olympics. The 1992 Games were particularly frustrating, as he missed a bronze medal by only one-hundredth of a second.During the late 1990s, clap skates became standard in Olympic competition. Van Velde had such difficulty adjusting to the techniques required with these new skates that he retired from skating and became a car salesman.

Louis I, also Louis the Great (; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian (; 5 March 132610 September 1382), was King of Hungary and Croatia from 1342 and King of Poland from 1370. He was the first child of Charles I of Hungary and his wife, Elizabeth of Poland, to survive infancy. A 1338 treaty between his father and Casimir III of Poland, Louis's maternal uncle, confirmed Louis's right to inherit the Kingdom of Poland if his uncle died without a son. In exchange, Louis was obliged to assist his uncle to reoccupy the lands that Poland had lost in previous decades.

Year 1446 (MCDXLVI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+(-10(X)+50(L))+5(V)+1(I) = 1446).Events  January–December  September 27 – Battle of Otonetë: Skanderbeg defeats the Ottomans. Before October – Sultan Mehmed II of the Ottoman Empire is forced to abdicate, in favor of his father Murad II, by the Janissaries.

Year 1579 ( MDLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, significant events were happening around the world, shaping the future for years to come. Spain formally established its first colony in South America by creating the Tucumán province in present-day Argentina. Additionally, James VI, future King of England and Scotland, was crowned as the King of Scots, cementing the power of the Stuart Dynasty. Meanwhile, the early stages of Dutch Rebellion unfolded, eventually leading to the establishment of the Dutch Republic.

Year 1047 (MXLVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 25–28 – Rebel general Leo Tornikios (a nephew of Emperor Constantine IX) proclaims himself emperor at Adrianople, and besieges Constantinople. Byzantine troops personally led by Constantine repel him, and re-occupy the walls. Tornikios is forced to withdraw, while his followers start to abandon him. Finally, he is captured at a church in Boulgarophygon (modern Turkey), and is publicly blinded.

In physics, quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy, more precisely a scalar field, postulated  as an explanation of the observation  of an accelerating rate of expansion of the universe. The first example of this scenario was proposed by Ratra and Peebles (1988). The concept was expanded to more general types of time-varying dark energy and the term "quintessence" was first introduced in a 1998 paper by Robert R. Caldwell, Rahul Dave and Paul Steinhardt. It has been proposed by some physicists to be a fifth fundamental force.

Year 1502 ( MDII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year was filled with numerous significant historical events, from the voyages of exploration by prominent explorers such as Christopher Columbus, Amerigo Vespucci, and Vasco da Gama, to the foundation of cities like Havana and conflicts like the Italian War of 1501–1504. Moreover, it marked progress in art and architecture as Italian Renaissance continued to influence cultural developments. Additionally, during 1502, powerful alliances and strategic diplomacy also shifted power structures among Europe's dominant states.

Charles XV also Carl ( Carl Ludvig Eugen ) ; Swedish : Karl XV and Norwegian : Karl IV ( 3 May 1826 – 18 September 1872) was King of Sweden from 8 July 1859 until his death in 1872, and the last of the House of Bernadotte. He was the son of King Oscar I and Queen Josephine, and an older brother of Prince Gustaf, Duke of Uppland. Charles XV is mainly remembered for his liberal reforms and efforts to modernize the kingdom. He significantly improved the infrastructure of the country and established social welfare programs that helped uplift the living conditions for the Swedish people.

Year 1474 ( MCDLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked a time of significant events, both in Europe and Asia. In Europe, the struggle for power continued between the French, Burgundians, and English during the Hundred Years' War. Meanwhile, Russia consolidated under Ivan III and resisted Mongol domination, foreshadowing their growing status as a world power. In Asia, the highly anticipated royal wedding between Charles the Bold and Margaret of York was in full preparation, leading to a possible reinforcement of the alliance between the territories involved.

Events  January–March  January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against France. January 27 – The first fire engine company (in what will become the United States) goes into service. February 18 – The first part of English nonconformist preacher John Bunyan's Christian allegory, The Pilgrim's Progress, is published in London. March 6 – King Charles II of England opens his third Parliament. March 21 – Thomas Shadwell's comedy, A True Widow, is given its first performance, debuting at The Duke's Theatre and staged by the Duke's Company.

Dyson's eternal intelligence concept (the Dyson Scenario), proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979, proposes a means by which an immortal society of intelligent beings in an open universe may escape the prospect of the heat death of the universe by extending subjective time to infinity even though expending only a finite amount of energy.Bremermann's limit can be invoked to deduce that the amount of time to perform a computation on 1 bit is inversely proportional to the change in energy in the system. As a result, the amount of computations that can be performed grows over time.

Year 1140 ( MCXL ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this significant year, numerous noteworthy events occurred across the globe. Various kingdoms were caught up in political upheavals and battles for power. New advancements were witnessed in science, medicine, and the arts. The cultural and political influences were distinctly seen during this period as multiple kingdoms emerged, dominated and receded. Historically, it is known to be the period when the Würzburg St. Kilian Legends manuscript was created, bearing importance for art historians even to this day.

Year 1357 (MCCCLVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 28 – Erik Magnusson is recognized as king of most of Sweden, in opposition to his father, King Magnus. May 28 – Peter I becomes King of Portugal, after the death of his father, Alfonso IV. July 9 – Charles Bridge in Prague is founded. Date unknown  King David II of Scotland is released by the English, in return for a ransom. Berdibek succeeds Jani Beg, as Khan of the Blue Horde.

The Polish People's Party (, PSL) is an agrarian political party in Poland. It is currently led by Władysław Kosiniak-Kamysz.Its history traces back to 1895, when it held the name People's Party, although its name was changed to the present one in 1903. During the Second Polish Republic, the Polish People's Party was represented by a number of parties that held its name. They were all supportive of agrarian policies, although they spanned from the left-wing to the centre-right on the political spectrum. It was reformed into the People's Party shortly after the Sanacja regime took power.

The Khlysts or Khlysty (,  "whips") were an underground Spiritual Christian sect, which split from the Russian Orthodox Church and existed from the 1600s until the late 20th century.NameThe members of the sect referred to themselves by various names, including "God's People" (liudi bozh'i), "followers of Christ's faith" (Khristovovery), or simply "Christs" (Khristy). The appellation "Khlysty" is a derogatory term applied by critics of the sect. The origin of the term is disputed.

Year 1276 (MCCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.It is the only Year of Four Popes.Events By areaAfrica Mamluk sultan Baibars conquers Al-Maris, previously part of Makuria, and annexes it into Egypt.Americas A severe 23-year drought begins to affect the Grand Canyon area, eventually forcing the agriculture-dependent Anasazi culture to migrate out of the region.Asia February – The court of the Southern Song Dynasty of China and hundreds of thousands of its citizens flee from Hangzhou to Fujian, and then Guangdong, in an effort to escape an invasion by Kublai Khan's Yuan Dynasty.

Phillis Wheatley Peters , also spelled Phyllis and Wheatly ( c. 1753 – December 5 , 1784 ) was an African-American poet and the first African-American woman to publish a book. Born in West Africa and sold into slavery in the British colonies, Wheatley was transported to North America at the age of seven. As a young slave in Boston, she received an education from the Wheatley family, who noticed her intellectual prowess. Her work included vivid, emotional and thought-provoking themes which were largely focused on religion and social commentary. As an emancipated woman, Phillis faced numerous challenges but still solidified her literary prominence in early American history.

Year 1051 (MLI) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – William of Normandy consolidates his power in Normandy. He fights over the control of Maine (after the death of Count Hugh IV), and lays siege to the fortresses of Alençon and Domfront (Western France). May 19 – King Henry I of France marries Anne of Kiev at the cathedral of Reims. William of Normandy marries Matilda of Flanders, daughter of Count Baldwin V, which Henry sees as a threat to his throne.

Year 1372 (MCCCLXXII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May – Owain Lawgoch makes a second attempt to take the throne of Wales. Whilst attacking the island of Guernsey, he abandons the invasion in order to fight for France at La Rochelle. June 22 – Battle of La Rochelle: The French and the Castilians defeat the English. The Castilians gain control of the English Channel for the first time since 1340. November 9 – Trần Duệ Tông succeeds his brother Trần Nghệ Tông as King of Vietnam.

Year 1432 ( MCDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the year 1432, significant events unfolded across the world that would leave a lasting impact. As the Age of Discovery loomed on the horizon, many explorations and diplomatic expeditions took place during this period, resulting in remarkable cross-cultural encounters, the foundation of future trade relationships, and innovations in technology. Europe witnessed shifting alliances and crucial moments in historical battles, such as the Hundred Years War, and notable individuals like Saint Joan of Arc stepped onto the world stage to change the course of history.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description, understanding and prediction of natural phenomena, based on empirical evidence from observation and experimentation. Mechanisms such as peer review and repeatability of findings are used to try to ensure the validity of scientific advances.Natural science can be divided into two main branches: life science and physical science. Life science is alternatively known as biology, and physical science is subdivided into branches: physics, chemistry, earth science, and astronomy. These branches of natural science may be further divided into more specialized branches (also known as fields).

Year 1434 (MCDXXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 14 – The foundation stone of Nantes Cathedral in Nantes, France, is laid. May 30 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Lipany: The Catholics and Ultraquists defeat the Taborites, ending the Hussite Wars. June 19 or 20 – Zara Yaqob becomes Emperor of Ethiopia. Late June – Miner Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson begins a Swedish rebellion against King Eric of Pomerania (named the Engelbrekt rebellion after him), eventually leading to the deposition of the king.

Year 994 ( CMXCIV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 994 was marked by numerous notable events and historical milestones, shaping the political, economic, and cultural landscape. Major events included battles and political negotiations in the quest to gain new territories and strengthen existing alliances. During this time, trade routes were rapidly expanding and spreading ideas, creating new markets and encouraging interactions between civilizations. Key developments in the areas of arts and sciences were being explored and studied, all of which contributed to the development of global civilization.

Year 1344 (MCCCXLIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – Reconquista: The Siege of Algeciras (1342–44), one of the first European military engagements where gunpowder is used, ends with the Muslim city of Algeciras surrendering and being incorporated into the Kingdom of Castile. April 17 – Constantine II, King of Armenia, is killed in an uprising and succeeded by a distant cousin, Constantine III. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising: The Livonian Order hangs Vesse, the rebel Estonian Elder of Saaremaa Island.

Nvidia Corporation is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara , California . It designs graphics processing units (GPUs) for the gaming and professional markets, as well as system on chip (SoC) units for the mobile computing and automotive industries. Founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem, Nvidia initially gained prominence with their powerful GPUs capable of providing high-quality gaming experiences. Today, the company's expertise extends to fields like artificial intelligence, deep learning, and parallel computing.

J. Robert Oppenheimer (; April 22, 1904 – February 18, 1967) was an American theoretical physicist who was professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley. Oppenheimer was the wartime head of the Los Alamos Laboratory and is among those who are credited with being the "father of the atomic bomb" for their role in the Manhattan Project – the World War II undertaking that developed the first nuclear weapons. Oppenheimer was among those who observed the Trinity test in New Mexico, where the first atomic bomb was successfully detonated on July 16, 1945.

A conjugate acid , within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory , is a chemical compound formed when an acid donates a proton (H⁺) to a base. This process is known as protonation or acid-base reaction, which plays an important role in chemical reactions and biochemical processes. The term "conjugate" in the conjugate acid means that it is directly related to its counterpart, the conjugate base, from which it was derived after donating a proton. Conjugate acid-base pairs represent an essential concept for understanding pH, buffering capacity, and the chemical properties of substances in solution.

Events January–June January – Six months into King Philip 's War , Metacomet ( King Philip ) , leader of the Wampanoag tribe, intensifies his campaign against the English colonists in New England. Facing immense loss and violence, many colonists desperately seek peace, but failed diplomatic efforts with neighboring Native American tribes lead to escalating tensions. February – The General Court of Massachusetts passes a resolution encouraging military enlistment among colonists to battle against Metacomet's forces, deepening divisions between the English settlers and the Native American tribes. March – Raids and guerrilla warfare disrupt normal colonial life throughout the region, resulting in significant hardships on both sides.

Abolitionism , or the abolitionist movement , was the movement to end slavery . In Western Europe and the Americas , abolitionism was a historic social and political movement that sought to eradicate the inhumane practice of owning and exploiting enslaved people. This movement, which emerged in the late 18th century and continued throughout the 19th century, consisted of diverse groups, including religious organizations, anti-slavery activists, and politicians. Notably, it played a crucial role in fueling social and legal reforms that led to the eventual emancipation of millions of enslaved individuals. As the abolitionist movement gained momentum, it significantly influenced public opinion and various legislative measures across multiple countries.

Events January–June January 5 – Franco-Dutch War – Battle of Turckheim : The French defeat Austria and Brandenburg . January 12 – King John IV of Portugal signs a treaty with France to protect against the Dutch. February 6 – British Colonies form a New England confederation. March 1 – Publication of Robert Boyle's book "New Experiments Physico-Mechanical", which includes Boyle's Law. April 7 – King James II of England sends troops to Dunkirk to secure its acquisition from the French. May 20 – War of the Devolution: France invades Flanders and claims several cities including Lille and Douai.

Year 1569 (MDLXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January 11–May 6 – The first recorded lottery in England is performed nonstop, at the west door of St Paul's Cathedral. Each share costs ten shillings, and proceeds are used to repair harbours, and for other public works. March 13 – Battle of Jarnac: Royalist troops under Marshal Gaspard de Tavannes surprise and defeat the Huguenots under the Prince of Condé, who is captured and murdered. A substantial proportion of the Huguenot army manages to escape, under Gaspard de Coligny.

Year 1027 ( MXXVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events of the year include King Cnut the Great's effort to unify the English and Danish Christian churches under the North Sea Empire. In Asia, during the Song dynasty, the ancient Chinese architectural treatise "Yingzao Fashi" was written by the Song Emperor Renzong's government minister, Li Jie. In this period, increasing global interaction fostered economic growth and intellectual progress, particularly through expanding trade networks, exchanges of artistic traditions, and scholarly dialogue.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus . Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection and may include a high fever, headache, vomiting, muscle and joint pains, and a characteristic skin rash. While the majority of cases result in mild symptoms, the infection can progress to severe dengue or dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF), leading to plasma leaking, fluid accumulation, and potential organ failure. This dangerous complication has a mortality rate of around 20% without treatment but can be reduced to under 1% with early recognition and adequate healthcare support.

Events  January–June  January 3 – The Long Parliament adopts the Directory for Public Worship in England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland, replacing the Book of Common Prayer (1559). Holy Days (other than Sundays) are not to be observed. January 10 – Archbishop of Canterbury William Laud is executed for treason on Tower Hill, London. January 14 – English Civil War: Fairfax is appointed Commander-in-Chief. January 29 – English Civil War: Armistice talks open at Uxbridge. February 2 – Battle of Inverlochy: The Covenanters are defeated by Montrose.

Year 1539 (MDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Toungoo–Hanthawaddy War – Battle of Naungyo, Burma: The Toungoos decisively defeat the Hanthawaddys. January 12 – Treaty of Toledo: Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor (and Charles I of Spain) and Francis I of France agree to make no further alliances with England. The treaty comes after Henry VIII of England's split with Rome and Pope Paul III. January 14 – Spain annexes Cuba.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be a courtesan. As a former manipulative schemer, La Ruffiana now thrives on gossip and drama, intervening in others' romantic pursuits with her sharp tongue and keen observations. She can often be found orchestrating various affairs for personal satisfaction or revenge, wearing worn-out elegant attire and the mask of a smirking old woman, her outfit evoking her faded allure. Despite her age, La Ruffiana proves to be a captivating and complex figure, both admired and feared for her cunning and calculated charisma.

Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell (also called electrotransfer). In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used.

Year 1216(MCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  Spring – First Barons' War: The English army, led by King John (Lackland), sacks the town of Berwick-on-Tweed (or Berwick), and raids southern Scotland. John pushes up towards Edinburgh over a ten-day period. On his return, he puts down a revolt in East Anglia. On March 24, King John arrives at Hertford, to deal with the challenge of a coming French invasion.

Optical rotation , also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence , is the rotation of the orientation of the plane of polarization about the optical axis of linearly polarized light as it passes through certain optically active materials, such as liquids or crystals with an asymmetric molecular structure. These materials cause the orthogonal polarization components of the incoming light to propagate with different phase velocities, leading to a change in the plane of polarization. Optical rotation is commonly observed and exploited in various scientific, medical, and technological applications such as analyzing chemical structures, enantiomers in pharmaceuticals, and polarization devices in telecommunications.

In physics , optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power through a material. In simpler terms, it quantifies the ability of a material to absorb or scatter light. Optical depth is a unitless and dimensionless quantity, usually denoted by the Greek letter 'τ'. A high optical depth signifies that most of the light passing through a medium will be absorbed or scattered, while a low optical depth means that most of the light will be transmitted without any significant interaction with the medium.

Year 1181 (MCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  King Philip II (Augustus) annuls all loans made by Jews to Christians, and takes a percentage for himself. A year later, he confiscates all Jewish property and expels the Jews from Paris. Philip II begins a war against Philip of Alsace, count of Flanders, over the Vermandois. He claims the territory for his wife Isabella of Hainault as her dowry. Philip is unwilling to give it up.

Year 1176 (MCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Summer – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) assembles a Byzantine expeditionary force and marches towards Iconium the Seljuk capital. Meanwhile, hordes of Seljuk Turks destroy crops and poison water supplies, to make Manuel's march more difficult, and harass the Byzantine army in order to force it into the Meander valley. Kilij Arslan II, ruler of the Sultanate of Rum, hears of the expedition and sends envoys to ask for peace.

Year 1510 (MDX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Catherine of Aragon gives birth to her first child, a stillborn daughter. January 23 – An 18-year-old Henry VIII of England jousts anonymously at Richmond, Surrey and draws applause, before revealing his identity. February 27–November 25 – Portuguese conquest of Goa: Afonso de Albuquerque of Portugal conquers Goa. March 1 – Battle of Salt River: Indigenous ǃUriǁʼaekua decisively defeat sailors of the Portuguese Empire in South Africa.

Year 1042 (MXLII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April 19 – Emperor Michael V Kalaphates banishes his adoptive mother and co-ruler Zoë, for plotting to poison him, to the island of Principo. His announcement as sole emperor leads to a popular revolt. April 20 – Zoë is proclaimed as empress at an assembly in Hagia Sophia, along with her sister Theodora, as co-ruler. Michael V flees to the monastery of Stoudios, but is arrested, blinded and castrated.

Year 1056 ( MLVI ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1056, a series of remarkable events occurred across the globe. In Europe, Empress Theodora, the influential leader of the Byzantine Empire, passed away in June. Her death left the door open for imperial throne disputes, shaping Byzantine politics for decades to come. In Asia, the Chinese emperor Renzong passed away, and his young son Yingzong ascended to the throne, setting the stage for both domestic and international challenges.

A sifaka is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates . The name sifaka derives from their unique call, which sounds like "shi-fak" when communicating with others in the group. Sifakas are endemic to the island of Madagascar, where they primarily reside in tropical rainforests and dry deciduous forests. Known for their distinctive method of moving around, sifakas travel using an effortless and acrobatic form of locomotion called "vertical clinging and leaping." This skill, combined with their large, powerful hind legs, allows them to leap up to 30 feet between tree branches.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain , situated in Lullingstone near the village of Eynsford in Kent, England. Constructed in the 1st century AD, it underwent several significant developments over the years until its eventual decline in the early 5th century. This impressive villa showcases exquisite Roman mosaics, a spectacular pagan and early Christian religious site, well-preserved and elaborate bathing suites, as well as agricultural lands which once flourished in the surrounding areas. Today, Lullingstone Roman Villa stands as an important archaeological site, attracting thousands of tourists every year and providing valuable insights into Roman Britain's culture and way of life.

It is one of eight years ( CE ) to contain each Roman numeral exactly once ( 1000 ( M )+500 (D)+100 (C)+50 (L)+10 (X)+5 (V)+1 (I)= 1666). Known as Roman numeral years, the other years in this unique group include 1444, 1555, 2002, 2112, and 2223. These years showcase the mathematical marvel and striking precision of the Roman numeral system. Roman numeral years typically have the highest perceptive interest since they engage not only historians and mathematicians but also fans of unique coincidences in culture and history.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative , facultative anaerobic , rod-shaped , coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms (endotherms). Most E. coli strains are harmless, and they play a crucial role in the human gut, helping to break down and digest food substances, as well as in producing vitamin K2. However, some serotypes are pathogenic, causing various types of gastrointestinal illnesses, such as diarrhea and abdominal pain. In severe cases, it can also lead to life-threatening infections like kidney failure or sepsis.

New England Digital Corporation (1976–1993) was founded in Norwich, Vermont, and relocated to White River Junction, Vermont. It was best known for its signature product, the Synclavier Synthesizer System, which evolved into the Synclavier Digital Audio System or "Tapeless Studio." The company sold an FM digital synthesizer/16-bit polyphonic synthesizer and magnetic disk-based non-linear 16-bit digital recording product, referred to as the "Post-Pro." The Synclavier was developed as the "Dartmouth Digital Synthesizer" by Dartmouth College Professors Jon Appleton and Frederick J. Hooven, in association with NED co-founders Sydney A. Alonso and Cameron W. Jones.

Year 1043 (MXLIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Constantine IX Monomachos sends a Byzantine expeditionary force to the Balkans against the rebellious George Maniakes, governor of the Catepanate of Italy. The two armies meet near Thessaloniki in northern Greece. The rebel army – better organized, seasoned and with superior leadership – fights initially successful, but Maniakes is killed by an arrow at the moment of his triumph. After this, his army is routed.

Optical rotation, also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence, is the rotation of the orientation of the plane of polarization about the optical axis of linearly polarized light as it travels through certain materials. Circular birefringence and circular dichroism are the manifestations of optical activity. Optical activity occurs only in chiral materials, those lacking microscopic mirror symmetry. Unlike other sources of birefringence which alter a beam's state of polarization, optical activity can be observed in fluids. This can include gases or solutions of chiral molecules such as sugars, molecules with helical secondary structure such as some proteins, and also chiral liquid crystals.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis from a specially designed curved ramp. Along with jump length, competitor's aerial style and other factors also affect the final score. Ski jumping was first contested in Norway in the late 19th century, and later spread through Europe and North America in the early 20th century. Along with cross-country skiing, it constitutes the traditional group of Nordic skiing disciplines.The ski jumping venue, commonly referred to as a hill, consists of the jumping ramp (in-run), take-off table, and a landing hill.

Mercia ( , ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy . The name is a Latinisation of the Old English Mierce, meaning "border people". Located in the central region of what is now England, Mercia dominated its surrounding areas from the 7th to the 9th centuries AD. At its zenith, under the rule of King Offa, the kingdom extended across a vast territory that included present-day areas of the West Midlands, East Midlands, and East Anglia. However, as the 9th century unfolded, Mercia experienced continuous conflicts, eventually succumbing to the invading Danes and diminishing into a less influential province.

Year 1513 ( MDXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Notable events during this year included the appointment of Giovanni de' Medici as Pope Leo X in March, Vasco Núñez de Balboa's discovery of the Pacific Ocean in September, and James V ascending to the Scottish throne. Furthermore, England faced military challenges including the Battle of Flodden in September, wherein they emerged victorious against the invading Scottish forces. Also in the realm of exploration, Juan Ponce de León reached Florida, marking Spain's entrance into the colonization of the Americas.

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC. The 8th century BC is a period of great change for several historically significant civilizations. In Egypt, the 23rd and 24th dynasties lead to rule from Nubia in the 25th Dynasty. The Neo-Assyrian Empire reaches the peak of its power,  conquering the Kingdom of Israel as well as nearby countries.Greece colonizes other regions of the Mediterranean Sea and Black Sea. Rome is founded in 753 BC, and the Etruscan civilization expands in Italy.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state 's military forces . As the chief executive officer of the state, the governor has the responsibility to uphold and enforce the state's laws, as well as supervise and direct the functions of various agencies and departments within Montana. The governor's duties also involve presenting Montana's annual state budget to the legislature, setting policies, and advocating for legislative priorities. In the event of any natural disaster or emergency situation, the governor coordinates response efforts to ensure the well-being of Montana's residents.

Year 1556 (MDLVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 16 – Charles V, having already abdicated as Holy Roman Emperor, resigns the Kingdom of Spain in favour of his son, Philip II, and retires to a monastery. January 23 –  The Shaanxi earthquake, the deadliest earthquake in history, occurs with its epicenter in Shaanxi province, China; 830,000 people may have been killed. February 5 – Truce of Vaucelles: Fighting temporarily ends between France and Spain.

Charles Pierce (July 14, 1926 – May 31, 1999) was one of the 20th century's foremost female impersonators, particularly noted for his impersonation of Bette Davis.Life and careerBorn in Watertown, New York, he began his show business career playing the organ and acting in radio dramas at station WWNY. He branched out into a comedy routine, attired in tuxedo, yet managing to evoke eerily convincing imitations of popular movie actresses. Eschewing the term drag queen, which he hated, he billed himself as a male actress.Initially playing in small gay clubs, his fame spread.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be a prostitute. She is used most often in relationship to the vecchi of which group she is a nominal member. Ruffiana is most often romantically involved with Pantalone, though his love may easily be unrequited if it suits the plot. She is generally described as being talkative/gossipy, sneaky, and mischievous, but deep down is actually kind. She has been described as an "outsider" that always mixes things up and causes trouble for the rest of the characters.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy , authority or control within the internet. It serves as an address to easily locate and access websites on the world wide web. These domain names are governed and regulated by domain name registries and are created according to the rules and policies of the Domain Name System (DNS). Each domain name comprises of at least two parts – a second-level domain and a top-level domain (TLD), with the latter representing a specific purpose or region (e.g. .com for commercial or .uk for United Kingdom).

Year 1349 (MCCCXLIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December January 22 – An earthquake affects L'Aquila in southern Italy with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme), causing severe damage, and leaving 2,000 dead. February 14 – Jewish persecutions during the Black Death: Strasbourg massacre – Because they are believed by the residents to be the cause of the Black Death, roughly 2,000 Jews are burned to death. February 19 – Jewish persecutions during the Black Death: The entire Jewish community in the remote German village of Saulgau is wiped out.

Year 1569 ( MDLXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1569 was marked by significant events in various fields, including politics, religion, and exploration. In the political sphere, it witnessed the beginning of the Livonian War, fought between Tsar Ivan IV's Russia, Denmark, Poland-Lithuania, and Sweden for control of the strategic Baltic Sea trade. Also, this year brought religious conflict in the form of the Northern Rebellion, a revolt against the Protestant Church of England, as some dissatisfied nobles in Northern England attempted to reinstate Catholicism.

Jon Howard Appleton ( January 4 , 1939 – January 30 , 2022 ) was an American composer , an early pioneer in the field of electronic music, and a respected educator. Born in Los Angeles, he spent the majority of his career teaching and creating innovative musical compositions. With a diverse background in both traditional and experimental music forms, Appleton's contributions helped shape the evolution of modern electronic and digital music. Appleton taught at institutions such as Dartmouth College, where he established the influential Bregman Studio, which facilitated the emergence of a new generation of experimental artists.

In mathematics, open sets are a generalization of  open intervals in the real line. In a metric space—that is, when a distance function is defined—open sets are the sets that, with every point , contain all points that are sufficiently near to  (that is, all points whose distance to  is less than some value depending on ).More generally, one defines open sets as the members of a given collection of subsets of a given set, a collection that has the property of containing every union of its members, every finite intersection of its members, the empty set, and the whole set itself.

Year 1022 ( MXXII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The world in the year 1022 was marked by significant cultural, political, and religious events. The Holy Roman Emperor, Henry II, continued to consolidate his empire, attempting to further Christianize various parts of Europe, specifically in areas of Poland and Hungary. Meanwhile, Al-Andalus saw increased fragmentation amongst its Muslim population, which weakened their influence in Spain. Further east, the Indian Chola Dynasty solidified its rule over parts of the Indian subcontinent, constructing architectural marvels that can still be admired today.

The term chat room , or chatroom ( and sometimes group chat ; abbreviated as GC ) , is primarily used to describe any form of synchronous conferencing, occasionally even asynchronous conferencing. The term can thus mean any technology ranging from real-time online chat over instant messaging and online forums to fully immersive graphical social environments. Chat rooms gained popularity in the 1990s, providing a virtual platform for people to connect with each other, share ideas, and foster a sense of community. With advancements in technology, chat rooms have evolved, now often incorporating video and audio elements, along with modern messenger applications, further enhancing virtual communication experiences.

Year 1529 ( MDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year held great significance due to a number of notable events that occurred globally. One of the most prominent happenings of 1529 was the historic signing of the Treaty of Cambrai or the "Ladies' Peace" between France, Spain, and the Papal States. During the same year, European religious reformation was in full swing as Martin Luther faced imperial scrutiny. Moreover, the Turkish Empire laid siege on Vienna, attempting to conquer the key city, but eventually met with failure.

Year 1575 (MDLXXV)  was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – Queen Elizabeth I of England grants a monopoly on producing printed sheet music, to Thomas Tallis and William Byrd. February 8 – William I of Orange founds Leiden University. February 13 – Henry III of France is crowned at Reims. February 14 – Henry III of France marries Louise de Lorraine-Vaudémont. March 3 – Battle of Tukaroi: The Mughal Empire decisively defeat the Karrani dynasty of Bengal. June 24 – William I of Orange marries Charlotte of Bourbon.

Year 1463 ( MCDLXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) In the year 1463, a common year starting on Saturday, the world experienced many important historical events. This year, hostilities arose as the Ottoman Empire fought the Kingdom of Bosnia, bringing an end to Bosnian independence. France and Spain renewed their commitments to support England against potential invasions, while the Russian cities of Pskov and Great Novgorod defied Prince Dmitri Shemyaka in their quest for self-governance. Skanderbeg initiated resistance against the Ottoman forces, laying the foundation for an Albanian uprising.

Year 1383 (MCCCLXXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 17 – King John I of Castile and Leon marries Beatrice of Portugal. July 7 – The childless James of Baux, ruler of Taranto and Achaea, and last titular Latin Emperor, dies. As a result: Charles III of Naples becomes ruler of Achaea (now southern Greece). Otto, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen, the widower of Joanna I of Naples, becomes ruler of Taranto (now eastern Italy).

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea, mainly occupied by Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, and parts of Southern Russia. The Caucasus Mountains, including the Greater Caucasus range, have historically been considered a natural barrier between Eastern Europe and Western Asia.Mount Elbrus, Europe's highest mountain, is in the Western Caucasus. On the southern side, the Lesser Caucasus includes the Javakheti Plateau and the Armenian highlands, part of which is in Turkey.The Caucasus is divided into the North Caucasus and South Caucasus, although the Western Caucasus also exists as a distinct geographic space within the North Caucasus.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese (born 17 April 1954) is an Italian former racing driver, who raced in Formula One from  to . For 19 years, he held the record for the most Grand Prix starts.He became the first Formula One driver to achieve 200 Grand Prix starts when he appeared at the 1990 British Grand Prix, and the first to achieve 250 starts at the 1993 German Grand Prix. Patrese entered 257 Formula One World Championship Grands Prix and started 256 races. As of the end of the  season he is the ninth-most experienced F1 driver in history.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Friday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–March  January 1 – Battle of St. John's: The French capture St. John's, the capital of the British colony of Newfoundland. January 6 – Western Europe's Great Frost of 1709, the coldest period in 500 years, begins during the night, lasting three months, with its effects felt for the entire year. In France, the Atlantic coast and Seine River freeze, crops fail, and 24,000 Parisians die.

Year 1165 (MCLXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) makes an alliance with Venice against Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), who takes an oath at the Diet of Würzburg to support Antipope Paschal III against Pope Alexander III. Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Manuel I, escapes from prison at Constantinople. After passing through many dangers, he reaches Kiev and seeks refuge at the court of Prince Yaroslav Osmomysl.

The sousaphone is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba . Created around 1893 by American composer and bandleader John Philip Sousa, the sousaphone was designed as a more comfortable and easily maneuverable alternative to the tuba for use in marching bands. The most noticeable feature of the sousaphone is its wide, bell-shaped structure that encircles the player's head, creating a deep and rich sound that carries well on the field. Since its introduction, the sousaphone has become an integral part of traditional brass bands and marching ensembles around the world, symbolizing both majesty and tradition in American and international music.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891. It is used to produce high-voltage, low-current, high frequency alternating-current electricity. Tesla experimented with a number of different configurations consisting of two, or sometimes three, coupled resonant electric circuits.Tesla used these circuits to conduct innovative experiments in electrical lighting, phosphorescence, X-ray generation, high frequency alternating current phenomena, electrotherapy, and the transmission of electrical energy without wires. Tesla coil circuits were used commercially in sparkgap radio transmitters for wireless telegraphy until the 1920s, and in medical equipment such as electrotherapy and violet ray devices.
